ith Crisco]], American businessman and politician (d. 2014)\n* 1943 &ndash; [[Janet Evanovich]], American author\n* 1943 &ndash; [[Louise Gl\u00fcck]], American poet\n* 1943 &ndash; [[John Maples, Baron Maples]], English lawyer and politician, [[Shadow Secretary of State for Defence]] (d. 2012)\n* 1943 &ndash; [[Scott W. Williams]], American mathematician and professor\n*[[1944]] &ndash; [[Steve Fossett]], American businessman, pilot, and sailor (d. 2007)\n* 1944 &ndash; [[Doug Jarrett]], Canadian ice hockey player (d. 2014)\n* 1944 &ndash; [[Joshua Rifkin]], American conductor and musicologist\n*[[1945]] &ndash; [[Gopalkrishna Gandhi]], Indian civil servant and politician, 22nd [[Governor of West Bengal]]\n* 1945 &ndash; [[Demetrio Stratos]], Egyptian-Italian singer-songwriter (d. 1979)\n*[[1946]] &ndash; [[Steven L. Bennett]], American captain and pilot, [[Medal of Honor]] recipient (d. 1972)\n* 1946 &ndash; [[Paul Davies]], English physicist and author\n* 1946 &ndash; [[Louise Harel]], Canadian lawyer and politician\n* 1946 &ndash; [[Archy Kirkwood, Baron Kirkwood of Kirkhope]], Scottish lawyer and politician\n* 1946 &ndash; [[Nicholas Stern, Baron Stern of Brentford]], English economist and academic\n* 1946 &ndash; [[John Waters]], American actor, director, producer, and screenwriter\n*[[1948]] &ndash; [[John Pritchard (bishop)|John Pritchard]], English bishop\n*[[1949]] &ndash; [[Spencer Haywood]], American basketball player<ref>{{cite web|title=Spencer Haywood|url=http://www.hoophall.com/hall-of-famers/spencer-haywood/|publisher=The Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n*[[1950]] &ndash; [[Peter Frampton]], English singer-songwriter, guitarist, and producer \n* 1950 &ndash; [[Jancis Robinson]], English journalist and critic\n*[[1951]] &ndash; [[Paul Carrack]], English singer-songwriter and guitarist \n* 1951 &ndash; [[Aivars Kal\u0113js]], Latvian organist, composer, and pianist\n* 1951 &ndash; [[Ana Mar\u00eda Shua]], 