{"title_page": "J\u00f3zef Retinger", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Polish diplomat and activist}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger\n|image             = File:Jozef Retinger.jpg\n|image_size        = \n|caption           = J\u00f3zef Retinger, recovering from a poisoning attempt c.1944<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n|birth_date        = {{birth date|1888|04|17|df=y}}\n|birth_place       = [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]]\n|death_date        = {{death date and age|df=yes|1960|06|12|1888|04|17}}\n|death_place       = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|citizenship       = Polish\n|nationality       = Polish\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = Economics, international relations, politics\n|work_institutions = [[Sorbonne University]] Phd, [[London School of Economics]], [[Polish government-in-exile]]\n|doctoral_advisor  =\n|doctoral_students =\n|known_for         = [[Bilderberg Group]], [[European Movement International]]\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo =\n|influences        = [[Jesuits]], [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]]\n|influenced        = [[Joseph Conrad]], foundation of [[European Union]], the [[Bilderberg Group]]\n|prizes            = [[Nobel Peace Prize]] Nomination 1958\n|footnotes         =\n|signature         =\n}}\n'''J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger''' ([[Krak\u00f3w]], 17 April 1888 {{spaced ndash}} 12 June 1960, [[London]]; [[World War II]] [[nom de guerre|noms de guerre]] ''Salamandra'', \"Salamander\", and ''Brzoza'', \"Birch Tree\") was a [[Poles|Polish]] diplomat, international political adviser and activist, and writer.<ref name = \"JR\">{{cite book|title=Joseph Retinger - Memoirs of an Eminence Grise|editor=John Pomian|publisher=Sussex University Press/ Chatto & Windus|date= 1972|url=https://ia800905.us.archive.org/5/items/MemoirsOfAnEminenceGrise1972/Memoirs%20of%20an%20Eminence%20Grise%2C%201972.pdf}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War I]], Retinger was politically active in [[Austria-Hungary]] and Russia on behalf of the Polish independence movement. After the [[Russian Revolution]], he had to retreat to [[Central America]], where he became an economic adviser. After the outbreak of  [[World War II]], he was principal adviser to the [[Polish government-in-exile]].<ref name=\"Oleks\">{{cite web|title=The Most Mysterious Man in 20th-Century Politics|author=Oleksiak, Wojciech|publisher=Culture.pl|date=2016-12-14|url=https://culture.pl/en/article/the-most-mysterious-man-in-20th-century-politics|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> A Freemason with a reputation as a [[grey eminence]], he went on to cofound the [[European Movement]], which led to establishment of the [[European Union]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pieczewski|first1=Andrzej|title=Joseph Retinger's conception of and contribution to the early process of European integration|journal=European Review of History|date=11 Aug 2010|volume=17|issue=4|pages=581\u2013604|doi=10.1080/13507486.2010.495766}}</ref> and was instrumental in forming the [[Bilderberg Group]]. In 1958 he was nominated for the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Emilian Czyrnia\u0144ski.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Emilian Czyrnia\u0144ski]], Retinger's maternal grandfather, 1878 photo by [[Walery Rzewuski]]]]\n[[File:Wierchy-1925---W\u0142adys\u0142aw-Zamoyski-(1853-1924).png|thumb|150px|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]] (1853-1924)]]\n[[File:Misa Sert.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Misia Sert|Misia Godebska Sert]], Retinger's Parisian cousin]]\nJ\u00f3zef Retinger was born in [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Poland]] (then part of [[Austria-Hungary]]), the youngest of five children: his father had a daughter, Aniela, from a first marriage to Helena Jawornicka.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\">{{cite web|title=J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|url=https://kangur.uek.krakow.pl//biblioteka/retinger/B.%20Podgorski%20-%20J.H.%20Retinger%201888-1960.pdf|lang=pl|page=5|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> His mother was Maria Krystyna [[Emil Czyrnia\u0144ski|Czyrnia\u0144ska]], daughter of a [[Greek Catholic Church|Greek Catholic]] [[Lemkos|Lemko]] professor of chemistry at the [[Jagiellonian University]]. His father, J\u00f3zef Stanis\u0142aw Retinger, was the personal legal counsel and successful adviser to French-born Count [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]]. Retinger's great grandfather, Filip Rettinger, was a Jewish tailor from [[Tarn\u00f3w]] who with his family converted to Catholicism in 1827.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Sypek, Antoni|title=\u017bydowskie konwersje na chrze\u015bcija\u0144stwo w Tarnowie, w latach 1785-1900|journal= Rocznik Tarnowski|date= 2013| page= 128|trans-title= Jewish conversions to christianity in Tarn\u00f3w in 1785-1900}}</ref> When his lawyer grandson died, Count Zamoyski took the promising youngster, J\u00f3zef, into his household and paid for him to attend the [[Bart\u0142omiej Nowodworski High School]] in Krak\u00f3w. Retinger's eldest brother, Emil, became a commander in the [[Polish Navy]], while his son, {{Interlanguage link|Witold Retinger|pl}}, was stationed in the [[United Kingdom]] during [[World War II]] (1943-45), as a member then leader of [[No. 308 Polish Fighter Squadron|Squadron 308]] of the [[Polish Air Forces in France and Great Britain|Polish Air Force]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafweb.org/Squadrons/Sqn300-318.htm|title=History of No.'s 300\u2013318 Squadrons at RAF Web|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Retinger's brother, Juliusz, taught [[physiological chemistry]] at the [[University of Chicago]] and [[University of Wilno]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Polish Biographical Dictionary|title-link= Polish Biographical Dictionary|volume= 127|page= 152|lang=pl}}</ref> Retinger himself initially considered a career in the priesthood, but three months in the Jesuit [[novitiate]] in [[Rome]] confirmed he would not be suited to the life.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n\nFurther financed by Count Zamoyski in 1906, Retinger entered simultaneously the [[Ecole des sciences politiques]] and the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] in [[Paris]] and two years later, aged twenty, became the youngest person ever to earn a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in literature from there.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> While in the French capital, armed with introductions from Zamoyski and his own relative, the salonni\u00e8re and pianist [[Misia Sert]], he moved in intellectual circles and was befriended by among others, [[Andr\u00e9 Gide]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Mauriac]], [[Bernard Grasset]], [[Jean Giraudoux]], [[Erik Satie]] and [[Maurice Ravel]]. His early literary ambitions were stopped in their tracks when he presented his first novel, ''\"Les Souffleurs\"'' to Andr\u00e9 Gide for his opinion. Gide told him: ''Joseph, you will never be a writer.''<ref name = \"JR\"/>{{rp|pages=11\u201313}} \n\nHe next went to [[Munich]] to study [[comparative psychology]] for a year. From there, encouraged by Zamoyski, in 1910 he moved to [[England]], where he entered the [[London School of Economics]] for a year's study and began a lobbying operation on behalf of the Polish cause and its populations scattered across three ailing empires. Formally he became Director of the London Office of the Polish National Committee (1912\u20131914).<ref>{{cite web|title=Jozef Retinger - cv|url=https://www.cvce.eu/en/obj/joseph_retinger-en-9d454c22-957c-49ef-8c7b-be5f98d676fc.htmlE|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|first1=Wojciech|last1=Roszkowski|first2=Jan|last2=Kofman|title=Biographical Dictionary of Central and Eastern Europe in the Twentieth Century|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date=2016|isbn=9781317475934|chapter-url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=RnKlDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA2377|access-date=2017-07-25|chapter=Retinger J\u00f3zef}}</ref> During this time he continued to move in \u00e9lite circles and  thanks to an introduction by [[Arnold Bennett]] whom he had met in Paris, Retinger developed a close friendship with his older Polish compatriot, the already well established novelist, [[Joseph Conrad]].<ref name=\":0\"/> Retinger urged Conrad to visit Poland, and on 28 July 1914, the day [[World War I]] broke out, Retinger, his wife Otolia, and Conrad, his wife, and their two sons arrived in Krak\u00f3w, the two men's childhood stamping grounds (they were alumni of the same [[secondary school]]). Due to the closeness of the Russian border (Russia was then allied to Great Britain), the Conrads soon sought greater safety in the [[Tatra Mountains]] resort of [[Zakopane]].<ref>[[Zdzis\u0142aw Najder]], ''Joseph Conrad: A Life'', Rochester, New York, Camden House, 2007, {{ISBN|978-1-57113-347-2}}, pp. 459\u201363.</ref> Retinger would write about Conrad in his 1943 book, ''Conrad and His Contemporaries''. Historian [[Norman Davies]] suggests that it was probably Conrad who introduced the \"polyglot and polymath\" Retinger to the British intelligence services.<ref name=\"Davies\">{{cite book|author=Davies, Norman|title=Rising '44: The Battle for Warsaw|title-link=Rising '44|year=2003|place= London|publisher= Pan Books|isbn=0-333-90568-7| page= 53}}</ref> Later Retinger became a personal friend of Major-General Sir [[Colin Gubbins]], wartime head of [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]], and after the war an [[Special Intelligence Service|MI6]] \"asset\".<ref name=\"wilford\">{{cite book|title=The CIA, the British Left and the Cold War: Calling the Tune? Studies in Intelligence|author= Wilford, Hugh|publisher=Routledge|date= 2013|page=242|isbn=978-1135294779}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dorril, Stephen|title= A Critical Review: MI6: Fifty years of special operations. Doctoral thesis|publisher= University of Huddersfield|date=2010|url=http://eprints.hud.ac.uk/id/eprint/9763/1/sdorrilfinalthesis.pdf|page=27}}</ref>\n\n===World War I===\n[[File:Joseph Conrad author.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Joseph Conrad]]]]\nWith the clouds of war closing in, the project of writing a play together with Conrad based on the latter's novel, ''[[Nostromo]]'' had to be abandoned as both men hurriedly left Austria Hungary. Retinger would have been eligible for military call up in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]], but no mention of this is made by his biographers. Instead, he put aside literary endeavours and once more assumed the role of a political lobbyist for Poland, publishing pamphlets and travelling between London, Paris and [[New York City|New York]], aided by Conrad in London.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=10}} In the first years of the war, this was not on the agenda of the major powers. Retinger looked instead for other potential alliances and political leverage which led to meetings with leading [[Zionism|Zionists]] of the time, including [[Chaim Weizmann]], [[Vladimir Zhabotinski]] and [[Nahum Sokolow]] who were seeking international recognition and rights for the [[Jewish diaspora]].<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=11}} In 1916 guided by Zamoyski and with the approval of [[Herbert Asquith]], [[David Lloyd George]] and [[Georges Clemenceau]] with his old Parisian connections, [[Prince Sixtus of Bourbon-Parma|Sixtus]] and [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Xavier de Bourbon Parme]], the Duchess of Montebello and Marquis [[Boni de Castellane]], as well as Zamoyski's friend the Polish [[General of the Jesuits]], [[Wlodimir Led\u00f3chowski|W\u0142odzimierz Led\u00f3chowski]], Retinger became a \"courier\" in the secretive European dynastic negotiation suing for peace with Austria.<ref name= \"Kultura\">{{cite journal|author=Jele\u0144ski, K.A.|title=Prekursor anachroniczny|journal=[[Kultura|Kultura Paryska]]|location=Paris|date=1961|lang=pl|trans-title= Anachronistic Precursor (Obituary)|pages=190-193|url=http://static.kulturaparyska.com/attachments/51/96/79311ebf90d26ec65a78e3b802589c43f76cb880.pdf#page=97}}</ref> It became known as the ''[[Sixtus Affair]]'' but was a failure, due to Germany's refusal to cooperate thus making Austria more dependent on it.<ref>{{cite book|title=Informal Alliance: The Bilderberg Group and Transatlantic Relations during the Cold War, 1952-1968|series=  Routledge Studies in Modern History|author=Gijswijt, Thomas W.|chapter=J\u00f3zef Retinger - Informal diplomat|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date= 2018|isbn=978-1-3511-8102-0}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1 = Demblin, August | author2 = Demblin, Alexander | title = Minister gegen Kaiser : Aufzeichnungen eines \u00f6sterreichisch-ungarischen Diplomaten \u00fcber Aussenminister Czernin und Kaiser Karl |lang= de| date = 1997 | publisher = B\u00f6hlau | place = Vienna | isbn = 3-205-98762-4 | trans-title=Minister versus Kaiser: The designs of an Austro-Hungarian Diplomat to outwit Foreign Minister Czernin and [[Charles I of Austria|Kaiser Charles]]}}</ref> In 1917 he met [[Boy Capel|Arthur \"Boy\" Capel]], the half-French dilettante, polo player and \"sponsor\" of [[Coco Chanel]]. Capel is said to have planted in Retinger's mind the idea of a world federal government based on an Anglo-French alliance.<ref>{{cite journal|author= Biskupski, M. B.|title= Spy, Patriot or Internationalist? The Early Career of J\u00f3zef Retinger, Polish Patriarch of the European Union|journal= The Polish Review, Vol. 43, No. 1|date= 1998|pages= 23\u201367}}</ref> After concerns for his personal safety due to his \"political meddling\" in Austria-Hungary and in the emergent [[Soviet Union]], in 1918 Retinger was banned from France, and sought sanctuary in [[Spain]] for several months.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=12}}\n\n==Mexican years==\n[[File:Jane Anderson 1917.JPG|thumb|left|150px|US journalist [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]] 1917]] \nHe travelled on to [[Cuba]] and then to [[Mexico]], where he became an unofficial political adviser to union organizer [[Luis Morones]] whom he fortuitously met crossing the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]], and to President [[Plutarco El\u00edas Calles]].<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/><ref name=\"Oleks\"/> A glimpse of Retinger, newly divorced and love lorn for the American journalist, [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]], appears in the biography of another American woman, the communist sympathiser [[Katherine Anne Porter]], a member of the Morones circle. In it he is described as a \"Polish intriguer\" and \"British Marxist\". In 1921 while on an obscure mission to the [[United States]] to buy saddles, Retinger was arrested and imprisoned in [[Laredo, Texas|Laredo]] and Porter was despatched from Mexico to get him released.<ref name= \"Stout\">{{cite book|title=Katherine Anne Porter: A Sense of the Times - Minds of the new South|author=Stout, Janis P.|publisher=University of Virginia Press|date= 1995|pages=47\u201351|isbn= 978-0-813915685}}</ref> That same year Retinger had proposed that Katherine Porter and her friend Mary Doherty accompany him to Europe to do \"collaborative work\", an offer that was spurned.<ref name= \"Stout\"/>{{rp|pages=94-95}} Retinger helped advance Mexico's nationalization of its oil industry in 1928.<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\">{{cite journal|author=Ethridge, Marcus E.|title= Review of M.B.B. Biskupski, \"War and Diplomacy in East and West: A Biography of J\u00f3zef Retinger\", London, Routledge, 2017, ISBN: 978-1-138-21845-1|journal= [[The Polish Review]]| volume= 64|date= 2019|issue= 1| page= 95|doi= 10.5406/polishreview.64.1.0094}} Ethridge's full review is on pp. 94\u201395</ref> His activities in Mexico lasted a total of almost seven years and only ended with Calles's fall from power in 1936. They inspired Retinger to write three volumes on the tumultuous events of that Latin American republic.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/> The Mexican years were punctuated by trips back to Europe where he took on the role of Representative in the United Kingdom of the Polish Socialist Party (1924\u20131928). In 1926 he married his second wife, Stella, with whom he travelled to Mexico on one occasion. After her death in 1933 his two daughters were left in the care of their maternal grandmother and were estranged from him until the 1950s.\n\nIn the rest of the interwar period, he published many contributions in periodicals, such as the Polish ''Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie'' (Literary News), on literary and political subjects.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n\n==Building blocks on the table==\n[[File:W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski, 1923.jpg|thumb|150px|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]], Polish prime minister in 1923]]\nDuring [[World War II]], Retinger who was in [[London]], was involved in arranging for Polish troops to be transferred to Britain from France. He was bidden by Winston Churchill personally to escort [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]] by plane to England from France which had just capitulated to the invading Germans.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=16}} He became principal adviser and confidant to the Prime Minister of the [[Polish Government in Exile]] now re-established in London.<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>{{rp|page= 95}}<ref>{{cite web|title=London Gazette|date=1942-12-04|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/35811/page/5301/data.pdf|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> In fact, their political relationship went back to 1916 and was strengthened during [[Wladyslaw Sikorski]]'s earlier brief stint as prime minister, 1922-23 in newly independent Poland, and came to greater fruition when both men were later in exile in London.<ref name=\"Lane\">{{cite book|title=Poland and European Integration: The Ideas and Movements of Polish Exiles in the West, 1939\u201391|author1=Lane, Thomas |author2=Wolanski, Marian|publisher=Springer|date= 2009|page=18|isbn=978-0-2302-71784}}</ref>\n\nSikorski's dependence on Retinger was the greater as he did not have mastery of [[English language|English]]. At this time Retinger was despatched to talk with other exiled government representatives in London, who included [[Marcel-Henri Jaspar]], [[Paul Van Zeeland]], [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] in preparation for a post-war geopolitical landscape.<ref>{{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1|page=455}}</ref> He went on to posit a \"Sikorski Plan\" consisting of two stages, the first of which was signed in January 1942 and proposed a Polish-Czech confederation.<ref>{{cite book|author=Walter Lipgens|title=Documents on the history of European integration: Plans for European union in Great Britain and in exile, 1939\u20131945 (including 107 documents in their original languages on 3 microfiches)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X3TsVCAt9F4C&pg=PA648|accessdate=10 August 2011|year=1985|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-009724-5|page=648}}</ref> The idea was to expand it into a [[wikt:Central Europe|Central Europe]]an confederation with Poland and [[Lithuania]], [[Czechoslovakia]] as its nucleus around which would be grouped [[Romania]], [[Hungary]], Yugoslavia and [[Greece]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Schmidt, Andrea|title=From Intermarium to the Three Seas Initiative: The Implications of the Polish Orientation Over the Central and Eastern European Region on Hungarian Policy in Baltic-Black Sea Regionalisms: Patchworks and Networks at Europe's Eastern Margins|editor1=Bogdanova, Olga |editor2=Makarychev, Andrey|publisher=Springer Nature|date= 2019|page=157|isbn= 978-3-0302-48789}}</ref> The agenda behind this was to create a common political blue-print for smaller countries abutting larger European powers and became the basis of a Belgian-Dutch union which would mirror the Polish-Czech arrangement.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Together and Alone in Allied London: Czechoslovak, Norwegian and Polish Governments-in-Exile, 1940\u20131945|author=Jakubec, Pavol|journal=[[International History Review]]|date=2019|doi=10.1080/07075332.2019.1600156}}</ref>\n\nThis scheme of Retinger's caused problems between London and [[Moscow]]. In order not to tread on Soviet toes, the British altered their position and refused to back Sikorski's negotiations with the eight smaller European states. In his speech on the Council of Europe, [[Winston Churchill]] [https://www.winstonchurchill.org/resources/speeches/1941-1945-war-leader/national-address/ BBC radio broadcast] on 21 March 1943 referred to the necessity of smaller nations forming groupings, but that it was too early to go into detail. The most Retinger was able to achieve was to push through the [[Sikorski-Mayski Agreement]], signed on 30 July 1941, which provided for the formation of the [[Anders' army]], thus ridding Stalin of the immediate human problem posed by the hundreds of thousands of Polish [[Prisoner of war|POW]]s and deportees from the [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u201345)|Soviet occupied]] [[Kresy Zachodnie|Kresy]] regions of the former [[Second Polish Republic]], who after an arduous odyssey across thousands of miles would eventually end up as the [[United Kingdom]]'s human problem.<ref>{{cite book|author=Anders, Lt.-General W\u0142adys\u0142aw|title= An Army in Exile|publisher= MacMillan & Co. Ltd|date=1949|page=73}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Polish Underground Army, the Western Allies, and the Failure of Strategic Unity in World War II|author=Peszke, Michael Alfred|publisher=McFarland|date= 2015|isbn=978-1-4766-10276|page=70}}</ref> This trade-off adumbrated the [[Tehran Conference|Tehran]] and [[Yalta Conference]]s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Identity in Flux. The Polish Community in Britain|author=Sword, Keith|place=London|publisher=School of Slavonic and East European Studies - SSEES Occasional Papers No. 36| date=1996|isbn=0-903425-60-2|pages=24\u201330|url=https://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/id/eprint/10078280/1/SSEES0012.pdf|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Brushes with death==\nRetinger narrowly avoided perishing in the sea off [[Gibraltar]] with [[Wladyslaw Sikorski's death controversy|W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]], in July 1943, but for the fact that he was not needed to accompany the premier on a troop inspection in the Middle East and would be better employed in London. The spare seat on the plane went to Sikorski's daughter who died with her father.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> Retinger was devastated by this turn of events. His relationship with Sikorski's successor, [[Stanislaw Mikolajczyk]] was much more ambivalent, but he obtained his consent for a special mission to Poland under [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]] in April 1944.<ref>Bu\u0142hak, W\u0142adys\u0142aw. \"The Foreign Office and the [[Special Operations Executive]] and the Expedition of J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger to Poland, April\u2013July 1944\", ''[[The Polish Review]]'', vol. 61, no. 3, 2016, pp. 33\u201357.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Members of the Polish Government, Prime Minister's Office|publisher=the Gazette|location=Edinburgh|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/Edinburgh/issue/16118/page/134/data.pdf|page=184|date=1944-04-21|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nWith an SOE brief and without prior training, Retinger, aged 56, parachuted into [[German-occupied Poland|occupied Poland]] with 2nd Lt. [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt]], (see [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt#Operation \"Salamander\"|Operation Salamander]]), to meet with Polish underground figures, to deliver money to the Polish underground, and to \"explain to his fellow Poles in the homeland 'how are we going to lose this war'\".<ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\">{{cite book|last1=Eringer|first1=Robert|author-link=Robert Eringer|title=The Global Manipulators|publisher=Pentacle Books|asin=B00546KTEM|oclc=26551991}}</ref>{{rp|pages=16\u201322}} <ref name = \"JR\"/>{{rp|page=265}}<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>  Following at least one assassination attempt on him, Retinger expressed his frustration thus:\n\n{{blockquote|You know why I came.  The [Underground] [[Government Delegation for Poland|Delegate]] knows as well.... They know that I only want to convince them that it will be necessary in the future to cooperate with the Communists, because no English are coming here, only Russians.  If we do not get along with them somehow, it will be a terrible tragedy, because we well know what [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]] and the [[NKVD]] [Interior Ministry of the Soviet Union] are. And it's about trying to make people here understand this fact. And they want to murder me!}}<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>\n\nThe latter quip was a reference to elements in the [[Polish Underground Army]], the [[Armia Krajowa|AK]] who were convinced Retinger was not serving the interests of his country and should therefore be \"removed\". One apparent attempt to liquidate him in Poland was on the grounds of a \"death sentence\" to be carried out on the alleged orders of general [[Kazimierz Sosnkowski]]. It was foiled by the intervention of an old friend and [[Armia Krajowa|AK fighter]], Tadeusz Gebethner.<ref>{{cite web|title=The story of Tadeusz Gebethner|url=https://sprawiedliwi.org.pl/en/stories-of-rescue/story-tadeusz-gebethner|publisher=sprawiedliwi.org.pl |access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> There was also an attempt during his visit in occupied Poland to poison him, which failed. On his return to London, he spent some time in the [[Dorchester Hotel]] in London's [[Park Lane, London|Park Lane]] recovering from his ordeal of the trip, which left him lame in one leg for the rest of his life, possibly due to the [[Polyneuritis]] brought on by the poison. His first visitor at the Dorchester was Sir [[Anthony Eden]], the foreign secretary.<ref name=\"Davies\"/><ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\"/>\n\nImmediately after the war, in 1945-6 Retinger travelled to [[Warsaw]] with emergency aid for the capital's population. It consisted largely of tons of British and US Army surplus, such as equipment, blankets and field-kitchens.<ref name= \"Kultura\"/> When his erstwhile military escort from \"operation Salamander\", [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Tadeusz Chciuk]] and his new wife, Ewa, were arrested in Poland as subversives by the Polish Communist security service, Retinger allegedly appealed over their heads directly to [[Vyacheslav Molotov|Molotov]] in [[Moscow]] to have them released. Apparently the personal intervention succeeded. In 1948 the Chciuks became refugees in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jozef Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Chciuk-Celt, Jan|url=http://pdf.amazingdiscoveries.org/References/RB/275%20PDFs/jozef-hieronim-retinger-slide-79.pdf|access-date=2020-03-03}} Jan Chciuk-Celt is the younger son of Tadeusz Chciuk, Retinger's military courier during \"Operation Saamander\" and was a co-author and editor of his father's war memoirs.</ref><ref>{{cite book|authors=[[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Marek Celt]], Jan Chciuk-Celt|title=Parachuting into Poland, 1944: Memoir of a Secret Mission with Jozef Retinger|publisher=McFarland|page=17|date= 2013|isbn=978-1-4766-03384}}</ref>\n\n===Unwanted intrusion===\nDark days followed World War II when tensions rose between former Western and Eastern allies and in April 1946 Retinger's flat in [[Bayswater]], West London, was broken into and his and his secretary's files ransacked by persons unknown. He reported the matter to [[Scotland Yard]], but the [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]] were not overly bothered. As a result, Retinger escalated his complaint and ended up being interviewed by the Britain's security services. His view was that the newly communist embassy of the [[Polish People's Republic]] were responsible for the break-in.<ref>{{cite book|author=Moss, Eloise|title=Night Raiders: Burglary and the Making of Modern Urban Life in London, 1860-1968|publisher=Oxford University Press|date= 2019|pages=186-87|isbn=978-0-1925-7677-4}}</ref>\n\nFrom the moment Winston Churchill had made his \"[[Iron Curtain]]\" speech in [[Fulton, Missouri]], in April 1946, Retinger turned his efforts to a modified European project he had harboured for decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.winstonchurchill.org/i4a/pages/index.cfm?pageid=429 |title=Sinews of Peace (Iron Curtain) |accessdate=2007-02-26 |last=Churchill |first=Winston |publisher=Churchill Centre |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207054810/http://www.winstonchurchill.org/i4a/pages/index.cfm?pageid=429 |archivedate=7 February 2007 }}</ref><ref name= \"Kultura\"/>\n\n==Vision for Europe==\n[[File:Krakow-Jozef Retinger plaque.jpg|thumb|right|[[Krak\u00f3w]] plaque commemorating Retinger, \"great pioneer of European unity\".]]\nAfter World War II, Retinger feared another devastating war in Europe, this time fought between \"Russia\" and \"the Anglo-Saxons\".<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/> He became a leading advocate of [[European unification]] as a means of securing peace.<ref>{{cite web|author=Retinger, J. H.|title= The European Continent? Address given to the Royal Institute of Foreign Affairs in London|url=https://www.cvce.eu/content/publication/2008/2/19/534c684a-8924-445a-8181-58360f939f56/publishable_en.pdf|publisher=CVCE|date= 7 May 1946|access-date=2020-03-27}} Correction: although the original states Royal Institute of Foreign Affairs, it should read [[Royal Institute of International Affairs]], known today as \"[[Chatham House]]\", this is likely a copyediting error at CVCE (ed.).</ref> He helped found both the [[European Movement]] and the [[Council of Europe]], somewhat to the dismay of the philosopher Count [[Richard Coudenhove-Kalergi]], the post-[[World War I]] [[Anti-communism|anti-bolshevist]] founder of the [[Paneuropean Union]] movement.<ref name=\"wilford\"/>{{rp|pages=227\u2013228}}<ref>{{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1|page=165}}</ref> \n\nRetinger, with his connections in Holland, Belgium, and [[Switzerland]] (he was a friend of [[Denis de Rougemont]]), took his cue from [[Winston Churchill]]'s 1947 [[Zurich]] speech and found fertile ground with thirteen British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] members of Parliament who backed the idea of a loose European association of states. Working in particular with Britain's [[Duncan Sandys]], incidentally Churchill's son-in-law, he took on the lion's share of the work and became Honorary Secretary General of the [[European Movement]]. He organised the 1948 [[Congress of Europe|Hague Congress]] which brought together the two camps of those for a unified Europe and those in favour of a federal Europe.<ref name=\"Lane\"/> During the congress, Retinger networked assiduously among the delegates, who included the Vatican diplomat, [[Giovanni Montini]], the future [[Pope Paul VI]]. Ensuing discussions led eventually to the formation in 1951 of a [[European Coal and Steel Community]].<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>  \n\n===Creator of Bilderberg=== \nRetinger was the initiator and architect of the informal [[Bilderberg Group|Bilderberg]] conferences in 1952-54 and was their general secretary until his premature death in London in 1960. A founding member of the Bilderberg Group, later British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Foreign Secretary, [[Denis Healey]], described the secretive Bilderberg meetings as the \"brainchild\" of Retinger.<ref>{{cite web|title=Denis Healey on Bilderberg|url=https://www.worldsocialism.org/spgb/socialist-standard/2002/2000s/no-1175-july-2002/denis-healey-bilderberg/|publisher=worldsocialism.org|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Aubourg, Valerie|title=Organizing Atlanticism: the Bilderberg group and the Atlantic institute, 1952\u20131963|journal=[[Intelligence and National Security]]|volume=18, (2)|date=2003|pages= 92-105 |doi=10.1080/02684520412331306760}}</ref> Despite eschewing any distinctions or medals throughout his life, in 1958 he was nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.nobelprize.org/nomination/archive/show.php?id=15660 |title =Nomination for Nobel Peace Prize: Joseph Retinger |author =Nobelprize.org |publisher =Nobel Media AB 2014 |website = Nomination Database| date = |access-date = 2014-10-09}}</ref> He died in poverty of lung cancer.<ref name =\"BP\">{{cite web|title=J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|url=https://kangur.uek.krakow.pl//biblioteka/retinger/B.%20Podgorski%20-%20J.H.%20Retinger%201888-1960.pdf|lang=pl|page=53|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> He was buried at [[North Sheen Cemetery]] in the presence of five British cabinet ministers as well as of his two younger daughters who were finally reconciled with him.<ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\"/>{{rp|pages=16\u201322}} According to the oration of Sir [[Edward Beddington-Behrens]], Retinger not only had special access to [[10 Downing Street]] but also to the [[White House]].<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> \n[[File:Gr\u00f3b J\u00f3zefa Hieronima Retingera.jpg|thumb|right|Retinger's grave, [[North Sheen Cemetery]], London]]\nRetinger's long time personal assistant and the editor of his posthumous memoirs, John Pomian, actually {{Interlanguage link|Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz|pl}}, was another Polish emigr\u00e9 in London, later a director of the Heim gallery in London's [[St James's]], owned by the influential Polish art historian and philanthropist, [[Andrzej Ciechanowiecki]].<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://nekrologi.wyborcza.pl/0,11,,373783,Jan-Pomiana-B%C5%82awdziewicza-kondolencje.html | title =Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz | trans-title=Obituary of Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz|journal = Wyborcza.pl |date=2015| lang = pl | access-date = 2016-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRetinger married twice. In 1912 he wed the well-born Otolia Zubrzycka (divorced 1921, died 1984), with whom he had a daughter, Malina (later Puchalska). In 1926 he wed Stella Morel (died 1933), daughter of French-born pacifist and [[Dundee]] member of Parliament [[E.D. Morel]] and Mary, n\u00e9e Richardson, with whom he had two daughters, Maria (later Fforde) and Stasia (later French). \n\nDuring the Great War and after, Retinger appears to have fallen under the spell of several women, especially the American journalist [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]], a supposed lover of Joseph Conrad.<ref name= \"JM\">{{cite book|title=Joseph Conrad: A Biography|author= Meyers, Jeffrey|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|date= 2001|page=361|isbn=978-0-8154-11123}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Athens Observer|first=Donald E.|last=Wilkes|title=Jane Anderson: The Nazi Georgia Peach|url=http://digitalcommons.law.uga.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1019&context=fac_pm|date=May 18, 1995|page=5|accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref> Retinger's own liaison with Anderson brought about the breakdown of Retinger's marriage to Otolia and drove a wedge between him and his friend Conrad.<ref name= \"JM\"/>{{rp|page=293}} However Conrad biographer, John Stape, gives an alternative version for the cooling of relations between the two men, suggesting instead that as Retinger's enthusiasms were not shared by the novelist, shortly after the war, without his charming wife by his side, Retinger's proneness to exaggeration and tactlessness made him less socially acceptable.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Several Lives of Joseph Conrad|author= Stape, John|publisher=Random House|date= 2010|pages=187\u2013188|isbn=978-1409006824}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nOver sixty years after his death, the left-leaning Retinger continues to attract fascination and controversy with, on one hand, admirers of his political skill, his apparently selfless single-mindedness and his lasting institutional legacy in Europe and beyond.<ref>{{cite book|author=Wisnewski, Gerhard|title=The Bilderbergers Puppet-Masters of Power?: An Investigation into Claims of Conspiracy at the Heart of Politics, Business and the Media|translator=J. Collis|trans-title=Drahtzieher der Macht (2010)|date=2014|place=West Sussex|publisher=Clairview Books|isbn=978-1-90557075-1|pages=63\u201366}}</ref> {{Interlanguage link|Adam Pragier|pl}}, a notable Polish exile and political commentator, has described him as \"as a sort of adventurer, but in the good sense of the word\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Czas przesz\u0142y dokonany - Czasy i ludzie|author= Pragier, Adam|title=Czas przesz\u0142y dokonany, Part 1|series= volume 7 of 100-lecie Niepodleg\u0142o\u015bci - 100th anniversary of Polish independence|editors=Friszke, Andrzej and Peja\u015b, Ewa|location=Warsaw|publisher=[[Museum of Polish History]]|date= 2018|isbn=978-8-3652-4829-9|orig-year=First published by B. \u015awiderski in London 1966|page=852|trans-title=The Past Perfect - Lives and Times}}</ref> On the other hand, detractors impugn his influence due to alleged connections with deeply secret and malign factions for which there is so far no reliable evidence.<ref>{{cite journal|author=K\u0119der, Wojciech|title=Recenzje: Bogdan Podg\u00f3rski, J\u00f3zef Retinger prywatny polityk, Universitas, Krak\u00f3w 2013, ss. 417.\n|journal=Studia Sandomierskie 23|date= 2016|pages=303\u2013314|lang=pl|trans-title=Review of Bogdan Podg\u00f3rski, ''J\u00f3zef Retinger private politician''. Krak\u00f3w: Universitas. 2013, pages 417.|url=https://journals.indexcopernicus.com/api/file/viewByFileId/84684.pdf}}\n</ref><ref>{{Cite web|author=Cornell, Svante E|title=Erbakan, K\u0131sak\u00fcrek, and the Mainstreaming of Extremism in Turkey |publisher=[[Hudson Institute]]|date=2018 |url=https://www.hudson.org/research/14375-erbakan-k-sak-rek-and-the-mainstreaming-of-extremism-in-turkey|access-date=2020-04-03}} see fn. 19.</ref> He remains an enigma and probably the one significant contributor to post-war European peace without a monument.<ref name = \"BP\"/>{{rp|page=60}} \n\nIn 2000 [[The Daily Telegraph]]'s [[Ambrose Evans-Pritchard]] revealed from declassified US Government records that:\n{{blockquote|The leaders of the European Movement \u2013 Retinger, the visionary [[Robert Schuman]] and the former Belgian prime minister [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] \u2013 were all treated as hired hands by their American sponsors. The US role was handled as a covert operation. ACUE\u2019s funding came from the [[Ford Foundation|Ford]] and [[Rockefeller Foundation]]s as well as business groups with close ties to the US government.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/1356047/Euro-federalists-financed-by-US-spy-chiefs.html|title=Euro-federalists financed by US Spy Chief|author= Ambrose Evans-Pritchard|date=18 September 2000|publisher= The Daily Telegraph|author-link=Ambrose Evans-Pritchard}}</ref>}} The finding, in the context of the [[Cold War]], was subsequently analysed in greater detail by ''[[Le Figaro Magazine|Le Figaro]]'' commentator, {{Interlanguage link|R\u00e9mi Kauffer|fr}} in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kauffer, R\u00e9mi|title=Quand la CIA finan\u00e7ait la construction europ\u00e9enne - Par R\u00e9mi Kauffer, Source : Historia 2003|date=12 June 2019|url=http://www.comite-valmy.org/spip.php?article516|publisher=Comit\u00e9 Valmy|lang=fr|trans-title=When the CIA financed the construction of Europe by R\u00e9mi Kauffer, source: Historia 2003|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> However, as Hugh Wilford demonstrates, the initiative to win American backing for a \"United States of Europe\" did not come either from [[Allen Dulles]], deputy, then chief of the [[CIA]], nor from Senator [[William Fulbright]], chairman of the [[ACUE]], but from the lobbying Europeans themselves guided by disparate motives, namely Coudenhove-Kalergi and Retinger who eclipsed him due to his close connection with [[Winston Churchill]] on European matters.<ref name=\"wilford\"/> Retinger's plan was that the [[United States]] had to be integral to the political and economic support for a war damaged [[Western Europe]]. As \"head of casting\" for his project, he set about finding key Americans who would collaborate with him, among whom at that time was [[Charles Douglas Jackson]], [[Time Inc.|Time-Life]] publisher in the 1940s and one time head of propaganda at the [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Eisenhower]] White House.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Bilderberg Conspiracy: Inside the World\u2019s Most Powerful Secret Society|author=Jeffers, H. Paul|chapter= 1|publisher= Kensington Publishing Corp.|date= 2012|isbn= 978-0-8065-3595-1}}</ref> \n\nIn summary, Retinger was a figure who divided opinions, whose allegiances like his roots, have remained obscure and whose accounts of himself varied according to his audience, subverting his reliability as emerges among Conrad biographers and from numerous other sources, including that of Norbert W\u00f3jtowicz, of the Polish [[Institute of National Remembrance]], in his considered and annotated review of Marek Celt's 2006 posthumously published \"Z Retingerem do Warszawy i z powrotem. Raport z podziemia 1944\", [''To Warsaw with Retinger and Back. A Report from the Underground 1944''] edited by Wojciech Frazik.<ref>{{cite web|author= Norbert W\u00f3jtowicz|title=Recenzja: Marek Celt, Z Retingerem do Warszawy i z powrotem. Raport z Podziemia 1944, red. Wojciech Frazik, Wydawnictwo LTW, \u0141omianki 2006 |trans-title = Review of Marek Celt, To Warsaw with Retinger and Back. A Report from the Underground 1944, ed. Wojciech Frazik pub. LTW. \u0141omianki, 2006|url=http://www.polska1918-89.pl/pdf/marek-celt,-z-retingerem-do-warszawy-i-z-powrotem.-raport-z-podziemia-,5423.pdf|publisher=www.polska1918-89|lang=pl|access-date=2020-03-31}} The book was subsequently translated into English by Jan Chciuk-Celt and published by McFarland in 2013 as ''Parachuting into Poland, 1944: Memoir of a Secret Mission with Jozef Retinger'', {{ISBN|978-1-4766-03384}} \"Marek Celt\", the pseudonym of Tadeusz Chciuk, was the military courier who accompanied Retinger on his parachute mission to Poland in 1944. A bond of friendship developed between the two men and they collaborated again on supplying aid to Warsaw from London in 1945-6.</ref> Despite the perception of personality flaws, it does not alter Retinger's mature post-war European legacy.<ref>{{cite web|title= J\u00f3zef Retinger|publisher=bilderbergmeetings.co.uk|url= http://bilderbergmeetings.co.uk/jozef-retinger/|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n== Selected works==\nBy J. H. Retinger:\n* {{cite book|date= 1908|title=Le conte fantastique dans le romantisme fran\u00e7ais|place= Gen\u00e8ve|publisher= Slatkine Reprints, 1973|trans-title=Fantastical Tales in the French Romantic Tradition|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title=Histoire de la litt\u00e9rature fran\u00e7aise du romantisme \u00e0 nos jours|place= Paris|publisher=[[Bernard Grasset| B. Grasset]]|date= 1911|trans-title=The History of French Literature from Romanticism to the Present Day|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title= The Poles and Prussia|place=London|date=1913|url=https://explore.library.leeds.ac.uk/special-collections-explore/334918/the_poles_and_prussia?subject=%22Polish%20question%22&resultOffset=2}} available at University of Leeds Library\n* {{cite book|title=La Pologne et l'\u00c9quilibre europ\u00e9en|place= Paris|date= 1916|trans-title=Poland and the Stability of Europe|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title=Morones of Mexico; a history of the labour movement in that country|place=London|publisher= The Labour Pub. Co. Ltd.|date= 1926}}\n* {{cite book|title=Tierra mexicana; the history of land and agriculture in ancient and modern Mexico|place= London|publisher= N. Douglas|date= 1928}}\n* {{cite book|title=Polacy w cywilizacjach zagranicznych|trans-title= Poles in Foreign Civilizations|place=Warsaw|date= 1934|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite journal|title= Historja i polityka: Nowy czynnik w dyplomacji mi\u0119dzynarodowej|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie (50)|date= 4 December 1938|trans-title=History and Politics: A new factor in international diplomacy|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite journal|title= Historja i polityka: Zast\u00f3j w mi\u0119dzynarodowej dzia\u0142alno\u015bci Rosji|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie (51)|date= 11 December 1938|trans-title=History and Politics: Suspension of Russian activity in international relations|lang=pl}} \n* {{cite book|title=All about Poland: facts, figures, documents|place= London|publisher= Minerva Pub. Co.|date= 1941}}\n* {{cite book|title=Conrad and His Contemporaries |year=1942 |publisher=Roy |location=New York|orig-year=First published by Minerva, London, 1941}}\n*  {{cite book|title= The European Continent? Address given to the Royal Institute of International Affairs in London|url=https://www.cvce.eu/content/publication/2008/2/19/534c684a-8924-445a-8181-58360f939f56/publishable_en.pdf|date= 7 May 1946|place=London}}\n*  {{cite book|title=The Bilderberg Group|place= Hertfordshire, UK|date= 1959}}\n*  {{cite book|title=Under Polish eyes|place=United Kingdom|publisher= Joseph Conrad Society|date= 1975}}\n\nAbout Retinger:\n* {{cite journal|author=Poraj, Stanis\u0142aw|title= The knight among nations|journal= Tydzie\u0144 Literacki Polski Zbrojnej, 2 (24)|lang=pl|date= 19 June 1938}}\n* {{cite book|author=[[Denis de Rougemont|de Rougemont, Denis]]|date= 1961|title=A Biographical Sketch. In Tribute to a Great European|editor= Retinger, J.H.|pages=20\u201350|place= Geneva|publisher= Centre Europe\u00e9n de la Culture|lang=}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Siemaszko, Zbigniew Sebastian|date=1967|title= Retinger w Polsce 1944 r.|place=Paris|journal= Zeszyty Historyczne, 12|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|title=J\u00f3zef Retinger: Memoirs of an Eminence Grise|editor=Pomian, John|publisher= Sussex University Press/Chatto & Windus|date= 1972| isbn=0-85621-002-1|oclc=844436367}}.\n* {{cite book|author=[[Jan Nowak-Jeziora\u0144ski|Nowak, Jan]]|title= Kurier z Warszawy|place= London|publisher= Odnowa|date= 1978|lang=pl|isbn= 0-903705-37-0}}\n* {{cite book|publisher=[[Polski S\u0142ownik Biograficzny]]|title= J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|volume= XXXI|date= 1988-1989|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|title=In remembrance of Joseph Retinger 1988-1960, Initiator of the European League for Economic Cooperation|publisher= [[European League for Economic Cooperation]]|place= Brussels|date= 1996}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Grosbois, Thierry|date= 1999|title=L'action de J\u00f3zef Retinger en faveur de l'id\u00e9e europ\u00e9enne 1940-46|journal= Revue Europ\u00e9enne d'Histoire| volume= 6|issue= 34|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Kalicki, W\u0142odzimierz|date=2010|title=Gracz, kt\u00f3ry budowa\u0142 Europ\u0119|trans-title=The Player who built Europe|journal= Gazeta Wyborcza |issue=219|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|authors=\t[[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Marek Celt]], Jan Chciuk-Celt|title=Parachuting into Poland, 1944: Memoir of a Secret Mission with Jozef Retinger|publisher=McFarland|date= 2013|isbn=978-1-4766-03384}}\n* {{cite book|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|title= J\u00f3zef Retinger \u2013 prywatny polityk|trans-title=J\u00f3zef Retinger - a private politician|publisher= Universitas|date= 2013|lang=pl|isbn=97883-242-2351-0}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of governments in exile during World War II]]\n*[[European Movement]]\n*[[European Union]]\n*[[List of Poles#Diplomats|List of Poles]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal|author=Pragier, Adam|title=Nie by\u0142o k\u0142opotu z Polakami|trans-title=There was no Problem with the Poles|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci, Rok 10, Nr 21 (477)|lang=pl|date=1955-05-22|place=London|url=http://retropress.pl/wiadomosci/nie-bylo-klopotu-z-polakami/}}\n* {{cite book|author=Bines, Jeffrey|title=Poland's S.O.E: A British Perspective: the Story of the Polish Country Section of the Special Operations Executive 1940-1946 Including the British Military Mission Number Four to Poland 1939|publisher=Polish Underground Movement Study Trust|date= 2018|place=London|isbn=978-0-9928-03056}} \n* {{cite journal|author= Biskupski, M.B.|title=Spy, Patriot or Internationalist? The Early Career of J\u00f3zef Retinger, Polish Patriarch of European Union|journal=[[The Polish Review]]| volume= 43|date= 1998|issue=1| pages= 23\u201367}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Bu\u0142hak, W\u0142adys\u0142aw|title=The Foreign Office and the Special Operations Executive and the Expedition of J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger to Poland, April\u2013July 1944|journal=The Polish Review| volume= 61|date= 2016|issue=3| pages= 33\u201357|doi=10.5406/polishreview.61.3.0033}}\n* {{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=J\u00f3zef H. Retinger \u2013 pomys\u0142odawca i wsp\u00f3\u0142tw\u00f3rca Grupy Bilderbergu|trans-title=Joseph Retinger: Visionary Co-founder of the [[Bilderberg Group]]|lang=pl|journal= Studia polityczne|publisher= ISP PAN|volume= 10|date= 2000}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Dzia\u0142alno\u015b\u0107 J.H. Retingera na rzecz zjednoczonej Europy|trans-title=Joseph Retinger\u2019s Work for a United Europe|journal= Studia Europejskie|publisher= Centrum Europejskie Uniwersytetu Warszawskiego|volume=  16|date= 2000|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Dzia\u0142alno\u015b\u0107 J\u00f3zefa Hieronima Retingera na rzecz integracji europejskiej|lang=pl|trans-title= Joseph Retinger\u2019s Work for European Integration|publisher= Wydawnictwo Adam Marsza\u0142ek|place= Toru\u0144|date= 2008|isbn=978-83-7611-184-1}}\n* {{cite book|author= Hampson, Robert|title=Conrad's Secrets|publisher=\tPalgrave Macmillan|date= 2012|isbn=978-0-2305-0783-8}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Joseph Retinger's Vision of [a] United Europe After World War II: Central and Eastern European Question|journal= [[The Polish Review]]| volume= 60|date= 2015 |issue=4|pages= 49\u201366|doi=10.5406/polishreview.60.4.0049}}\n* {{cite book|author=Wisnewski, Gerhard|title=The Bilderbergers Puppet-Masters of Power?: An Investigation into Claims of Conspiracy at the Heart of Politics, Business and the Media|translator=J. Collis|trans-title=Drahtzieher der Macht (2010)|date=2014|place=West Sussex|publisher=Clairview Books|isbn=978-1-90557075-1|pages=63\u201366}}\n* {{cite book|title=Informal Alliance: The Bilderberg Group and Transatlantic Relations during the Cold War, 1952-1968|series=  Routledge Studies in Modern History|author=Gijswijt, Thomas W.|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date= 2018|isbn=978-1-3511-8102-0}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161027232624/http://home.teleport.com/~flyheart/retinger.htm Biography of Jozef Retinger]\n*[https://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/205254911 The Polish Soviet Relations During The Second World War, photographs held by the [[Imperial War Museum]] including of Dr. J\u00f3zef Retinger on 30.07.1941]\n*[http://www.jasperfforde.com/ten_things/ten_things8.html photograph of Retinger flanking Churchill at the Hague 1948, on Retinger's grandson's website]\n*[http://www.bilderberg.org/bildhist.htm#Memoirs Chapter 4, European Unity.] from ''Memoirs of An Eminence Grise'' by John Pomian,\n*[http://bilderbergmeetings.co.uk/jozef-retinger/ Bilderberg website on Retinger's life in brief]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Retinger, Jozef}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Poland to Russia]]\n[[Category:Council of Europe]]\n[[Category:Members of the Steering Committee of the Bilderberg Group]]\n[[Category:Polish politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Freemasons]]\n[[Category:European integration pioneers]]\n[[Category:Geopoliticians]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Polish diplomats]]\n[[Category:Polish spies]]\n[[Category:Secret Intelligence Service personnel]]\n[[Category:Special Operations Executive personnel]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish writers]]\n[[Category:Exophonic writers]]\n[[Category:Polish essayists]]\n[[Category:Male essayists]]\n[[Category:Polish political writers]]\n[[Category:Polish people of World War II]]\n[[Category:People of World War II]]\n[[Category:History of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Rusyn descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Polish diplomat and activist}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger\n|image             = File:Jozef Retinger.jpg\n|image_size        = \n|caption           = J\u00f3zef Retinger, recovering from a poisoning attempt c.1944<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n|birth_date        = {{birth date|1888|04|17|df=y}}\n|birth_place       = [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]]\n|death_date        = {{death date and age|df=yes|1960|06|12|1888|04|17}}\n|death_place       = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|citizenship       = Polish\n|nationality       = Polish\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = Economics, international relations, politics\n|work_institutions = [[Sorbonne University]] Phd, [[London School of Economics]], [[Polish government-in-exile]]\n|doctoral_advisor  =\n|doctoral_students =\n|known_for         = [[Bilderberg Group]], [[European Movement International]]\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo =\n|influences        = [[Jesuits]], [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]]\n|influenced        = [[Joseph Conrad]], foundation of [[European Union]], the [[Bilderberg Group]]\n|prizes            = [[Nobel Peace Prize]] Nomination 1958\n|footnotes         =\n|signature         =\n}}\n'''J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger''' ([[Krak\u00f3w]], 17 April 1888 {{spaced ndash}} 12 June 1960, [[London]]; [[World War II]] [[nom de guerre|noms de guerre]] ''Salamandra'', \"Salamander\", and ''Brzoza'', \"Birch Tree\") was a [[Poles|Polish]] diplomat, international political adviser and activist, and writer.<ref name = \"JR\">{{cite book|title=Joseph Retinger - Memoirs of an Eminence Grise|editor=John Pomian|publisher=Sussex University Press/ Chatto & Windus|date= 1972|url=https://ia800905.us.archive.org/5/items/MemoirsOfAnEminenceGrise1972/Memoirs%20of%20an%20Eminence%20Grise%2C%201972.pdf}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War I]], Retinger was politically active in [[Austria-Hungary]] and Russia on behalf of the Polish independence movement. After the [[Russian Revolution]], he had to retreat to [[Central America]], where he became an economic adviser. After the outbreak of  [[World War II]], he was principal adviser to the [[Polish government-in-exile]].<ref name=\"Oleks\">{{cite web|title=The Most Mysterious Man in 20th-Century Politics|author=Oleksiak, Wojciech|publisher=Culture.pl|date=2016-12-14|url=https://culture.pl/en/article/the-most-mysterious-man-in-20th-century-politics|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> A Freemason with a reputation as a [[grey eminence]], he went on to cofound the [[European Movement]], which led to establishment of the [[European Union]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pieczewski|first1=Andrzej|title=Joseph Retinger's conception of and contribution to the early process of European integration|journal=European Review of History|date=11 Aug 2010|volume=17|issue=4|pages=581\u2013604|doi=10.1080/13507486.2010.495766}}</ref> and was instrumental in forming the [[Bilderberg Group]]. In 1958 he was nominated for the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Emilian Czyrnia\u0144ski.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Emilian Czyrnia\u0144ski]], Retinger's maternal grandfather, 1878 photo by [[Walery Rzewuski]]]]\n[[File:Wierchy-1925---W\u0142adys\u0142aw-Zamoyski-(1853-1924).png|thumb|150px|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]] (1853-1924)]]\n[[File:Misa Sert.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Misia Sert|Misia Godebska Sert]], Retinger's Parisian cousin]]\nJ\u00f3zef Retinger was born in [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Poland]] (then part of [[Austria-Hungary]]), the youngest of five children: his father had a daughter, Aniela, from a first marriage to Helena Jawornicka.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\">{{cite web|title=J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|url=https://kangur.uek.krakow.pl//biblioteka/retinger/B.%20Podgorski%20-%20J.H.%20Retinger%201888-1960.pdf|lang=pl|page=5|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> His mother was Maria Krystyna [[Emil Czyrnia\u0144ski|Czyrnia\u0144ska]], daughter of a [[Greek Catholic Church|Greek Catholic]] [[Lemkos|Lemko]] professor of chemistry at the [[Jagiellonian University]]. His father, J\u00f3zef Stanis\u0142aw Retinger, was the personal legal counsel and successful adviser to French-born Count [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]]. Retinger's great grandfather, Filip Rettinger, was a Jewish tailor from [[Tarn\u00f3w]] who with his family converted to Catholicism in 1827.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Sypek, Antoni|title=\u017bydowskie konwersje na chrze\u015bcija\u0144stwo w Tarnowie, w latach 1785-1900|journal= Rocznik Tarnowski|date= 2013| page= 128|trans-title= Jewish conversions to christianity in Tarn\u00f3w in 1785-1900}}</ref> When his lawyer grandson died, Count Zamoyski took the promising youngster, J\u00f3zef, into his household and paid for him to attend the [[Bart\u0142omiej Nowodworski High School]] in Krak\u00f3w. Retinger's eldest brother, Emil, became a commander in the [[Polish Navy]], while his son, {{Interlanguage link|Witold Retinger|pl}}, was stationed in the [[United Kingdom]] during [[World War II]] (1943-45), as a member then leader of [[No. 308 Polish Fighter Squadron|Squadron 308]] of the [[Polish Air Forces in France and Great Britain|Polish Air Force]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafweb.org/Squadrons/Sqn300-318.htm|title=History of No.'s 300\u2013318 Squadrons at RAF Web|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Retinger's brother, Juliusz, taught [[physiological chemistry]] at the [[University of Chicago]] and [[University of Wilno]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Polish Biographical Dictionary|title-link= Polish Biographical Dictionary|volume= 127|page= 152|lang=pl}}</ref> Retinger himself initially considered a career in the priesthood, but three months in the Jesuit [[novitiate]] in [[Rome]] confirmed he would not be suited to the life.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n\nFurther financed by Count Zamoyski in 1906, Retinger entered simultaneously the [[Ecole des sciences politiques]] and the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] in [[Paris]] and two years later, aged twenty, became the youngest person ever to earn a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in literature from there.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> While in the French capital, armed with introductions from Zamoyski and his own relative, the salonni\u00e8re and pianist [[Misia Sert]], he moved in intellectual circles and was befriended by among others, [[Andr\u00e9 Gide]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Mauriac]], [[Bernard Grasset]], [[Jean Giraudoux]], [[Erik Satie]] and [[Maurice Ravel]]. His early literary ambitions were stopped in their tracks when he presented his first novel, ''\"Les Souffleurs\"'' to Andr\u00e9 Gide for his opinion. Gide told him: ''Joseph, you will never be a writer.''<ref name = \"JR\"/>{{rp|pages=11\u201313}} \n\nHe next went to [[Munich]] to study [[comparative psychology]] for a year. From there, encouraged by Zamoyski, in 1910 he moved to [[England]], where he entered the [[London School of Economics]] for a year's study and began a lobbying operation on behalf of the Polish cause and its populations scattered across three ailing empires. Formally he became Director of the London Office of the Polish National Committee (1912\u20131914).<ref>{{cite web|title=Jozef Retinger - cv|url=https://www.cvce.eu/en/obj/joseph_retinger-en-9d454c22-957c-49ef-8c7b-be5f98d676fc.htmlE|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|first1=Wojciech|last1=Roszkowski|first2=Jan|last2=Kofman|title=Biographical Dictionary of Central and Eastern Europe in the Twentieth Century|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date=2016|isbn=9781317475934|chapter-url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=RnKlDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA2377|access-date=2017-07-25|chapter=Retinger J\u00f3zef}}</ref> During this time he continued to move in \u00e9lite circles and  thanks to an introduction by [[Arnold Bennett]] whom he had met in Paris, Retinger developed a close friendship with his older Polish compatriot, the already well established novelist, [[Joseph Conrad]].<ref name=\":0\"/> Retinger urged Conrad to visit Poland, and on 28 July 1914, the day [[World War I]] broke out, Retinger, his wife Otolia, and Conrad, his wife, and their two sons arrived in Krak\u00f3w, the two men's childhood stamping grounds (they were alumni of the same [[secondary school]]). Due to the closeness of the Russian border (Russia was then allied to Great Britain), the Conrads soon sought greater safety in the [[Tatra Mountains]] resort of [[Zakopane]].<ref>[[Zdzis\u0142aw Najder]], ''Joseph Conrad: A Life'', Rochester, New York, Camden House, 2007, {{ISBN|978-1-57113-347-2}}, pp. 459\u201363.</ref> Retinger would write about Conrad in his 1943 book, ''Conrad and His Contemporaries''. Historian [[Norman Davies]] suggests that it was probably Conrad who introduced the \"polyglot and polymath\" Retinger to the British intelligence services.<ref name=\"Davies\">{{cite book|author=Davies, Norman|title=Rising '44: The Battle for Warsaw|title-link=Rising '44|year=2003|place= London|publisher= Pan Books|isbn=0-333-90568-7| page= 53}}</ref> Later Retinger became a personal friend of Major-General Sir [[Colin Gubbins]], wartime head of [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]], and after the war an [[Special Intelligence Service|MI6]] \"asset\".<ref name=\"wilford\">{{cite book|title=The CIA, the British Left and the Cold War: Calling the Tune? Studies in Intelligence|author= Wilford, Hugh|publisher=Routledge|date= 2013|page=242|isbn=978-1135294779}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dorril, Stephen|title= A Critical Review: MI6: Fifty years of special operations. Doctoral thesis|publisher= University of Huddersfield|date=2010|url=http://eprints.hud.ac.uk/id/eprint/9763/1/sdorrilfinalthesis.pdf|page=27}}</ref>\n\n===World War I===\n[[File:Joseph Conrad author.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Joseph Conrad]]]]\nWith the clouds of war closing in, the project of writing a play together with Conrad based on the latter's novel, ''[[Nostromo]]'' had to be abandoned as both men hurriedly left Austria Hungary. Retinger would have been eligible for military call up in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]], but no mention of this is made by his biographers. Instead, he put aside literary endeavours and once more assumed the role of a political lobbyist for Poland, publishing pamphlets and travelling between London, Paris and [[New York City|New York]], aided by Conrad in London.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=10}} In the first years of the war, this was not on the agenda of the major powers. Retinger looked instead for other potential alliances and political leverage which led to meetings with leading [[Zionism|Zionists]] of the time, including [[Chaim Weizmann]], [[Vladimir Zhabotinski]] and [[Nahum Sokolow]] who were seeking international recognition and rights for the [[Jewish diaspora]].<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=11}} In 1916 guided by Zamoyski and with the approval of [[Herbert Asquith]], [[David Lloyd George]] and [[Georges Clemenceau]] with his old Parisian connections, [[Prince Sixtus of Bourbon-Parma|Sixtus]] and [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Xavier de Bourbon Parme]], the Duchess of Montebello and Marquis [[Boni de Castellane]], as well as Zamoyski's friend the Polish [[General of the Jesuits]], [[Wlodimir Led\u00f3chowski|W\u0142odzimierz Led\u00f3chowski]], Retinger became a \"courier\" in the secretive European dynastic negotiation suing for peace with Austria.<ref name= \"Kultura\">{{cite journal|author=Jele\u0144ski, K.A.|title=Prekursor anachroniczny|journal=[[Kultura|Kultura Paryska]]|location=Paris|date=1961|lang=pl|trans-title= Anachronistic Precursor (Obituary)|pages=190-193|url=http://static.kulturaparyska.com/attachments/51/96/79311ebf90d26ec65a78e3b802589c43f76cb880.pdf#page=97}}</ref> It became known as the ''[[Sixtus Affair]]'' but was a failure, due to Germany's refusal to cooperate thus making Austria more dependent on it.<ref>{{cite book|title=Informal Alliance: The Bilderberg Group and Transatlantic Relations during the Cold War, 1952-1968|series=  Routledge Studies in Modern History|author=Gijswijt, Thomas W.|chapter=J\u00f3zef Retinger - Informal diplomat|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date= 2018|isbn=978-1-3511-8102-0}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1 = Demblin, August | author2 = Demblin, Alexander | title = Minister gegen Kaiser : Aufzeichnungen eines \u00f6sterreichisch-ungarischen Diplomaten \u00fcber Aussenminister Czernin und Kaiser Karl |lang= de| date = 1997 | publisher = B\u00f6hlau | place = Vienna | isbn = 3-205-98762-4 | trans-title=Minister versus Kaiser: The designs of an Austro-Hungarian Diplomat to outwit Foreign Minister Czernin and [[Charles I of Austria|Kaiser Charles]]}}</ref> In 1917 he met [[Boy Capel|Arthur \"Boy\" Capel]], the half-French dilettante, polo player and \"sponsor\" of [[Coco Chanel]]. Capel is said to have planted in Retinger's mind the idea of a world federal government based on an Anglo-French alliance.<ref>{{cite journal|author= Biskupski, M. B.|title= Spy, Patriot or Internationalist? The Early Career of J\u00f3zef Retinger, Polish Patriarch of the European Union|journal= The Polish Review, Vol. 43, No. 1|date= 1998|pages= 23\u201367}}</ref> After concerns for his personal safety due to his \"political meddling\" in Austria-Hungary and in the emergent [[Soviet Union]], in 1918 Retinger was banned from France, and sought sanctuary in [[Spain]] for several months.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=12}}\n\n==Mexican years==\n[[File:Jane Anderson 1917.JPG|thumb|left|150px|US journalist [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]] 1917]] \nHe travelled on to [[Cuba]] and then to [[Mexico]], where he became an unofficial political adviser to union organizer [[Luis Morones]] whom he fortuitously met crossing the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]], and to President [[Plutarco El\u00edas Calles]].<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/><ref name=\"Oleks\"/> A glimpse of Retinger, newly divorced and love lorn for the American journalist, [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]], appears in the biography of another American woman, the communist sympathiser [[Katherine Anne Porter]], a member of the Morones circle. In it he is described as a \"Polish intriguer\" and \"British Marxist\". In 1921 while on an obscure mission to the [[United States]] to buy saddles, Retinger was arrested and imprisoned in [[Laredo, Texas|Laredo]] and Porter was despatched from Mexico to get him released.<ref name= \"Stout\">{{cite book|title=Katherine Anne Porter: A Sense of the Times - Minds of the new South|author=Stout, Janis P.|publisher=University of Virginia Press|date= 1995|pages=47\u201351|isbn= 978-0-813915685}}</ref> That same year Retinger had proposed that Katherine Porter and her friend Mary Doherty accompany him to Europe to do \"collaborative work\", an offer that was spurned.<ref name= \"Stout\"/>{{rp|pages=94-95}} Retinger helped advance Mexico's nationalization of its oil industry in 1928.<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\">{{cite journal|author=Ethridge, Marcus E.|title= Review of M.B.B. Biskupski, \"War and Diplomacy in East and West: A Biography of J\u00f3zef Retinger\", London, Routledge, 2017, ISBN: 978-1-138-21845-1|journal= [[The Polish Review]]| volume= 64|date= 2019|issue= 1| page= 95|doi= 10.5406/polishreview.64.1.0094}} Ethridge's full review is on pp. 94\u201395</ref> His activities in Mexico lasted a total of almost seven years and only ended with Calles's fall from power in 1936. They inspired Retinger to write three volumes on the tumultuous events of that Latin American republic.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/> The Mexican years were punctuated by trips back to Europe where he took on the role of Representative in the United Kingdom of the Polish Socialist Party (1924\u20131928). In 1926 he married his second wife, Stella, with whom he travelled to Mexico on one occasion. After her death in 1933 his two daughters were left in the care of their maternal grandmother and were estranged from him until the 1950s.\n\nIn the rest of the interwar period, he published many contributions in periodicals, such as the Polish ''Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie'' (Literary News), on literary and political subjects.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n\n==Building blocks on the table==\n[[File:W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski, 1923.jpg|thumb|150px|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]], Polish prime minister in 1923]]\nDuring [[World War II]], Retinger who was in [[London]], was involved in arranging for Polish troops to be transferred to Britain from France. He was bidden by Winston Churchill personally to escort [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]] by plane to England from France which had just capitulated to the invading Germans.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=16}} He became principal adviser and confidant to the Prime Minister of the [[Polish Government in Exile]] now re-established in London.<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>{{rp|page= 95}}<ref>{{cite web|title=London Gazette|date=1942-12-04|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/35811/page/5301/data.pdf|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> In fact, their political relationship went back to 1916 and was strengthened during [[Wladyslaw Sikorski]]'s earlier brief stint as prime minister, 1922-23 in newly independent Poland, and came to greater fruition when both men were later in exile in London.<ref name=\"Lane\">{{cite book|title=Poland and European Integration: The Ideas and Movements of Polish Exiles in the West, 1939\u201391|author1=Lane, Thomas |author2=Wolanski, Marian|publisher=Springer|date= 2009|page=18|isbn=978-0-2302-71784}}</ref>\n\nSikorski's dependence on Retinger was the greater as he did not have mastery of [[English language|English]]. At this time Retinger was despatched to talk with other exiled government representatives in London, who included [[Marcel-Henri Jaspar]], [[Paul Van Zeeland]], [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] in preparation for a post-war geopolitical landscape.<ref>{{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1|page=455}}</ref> He went on to posit a \"Sikorski Plan\" consisting of two stages, the first of which was signed in January 1942 and proposed a Polish-Czech confederation.<ref>{{cite book|author=Walter Lipgens|title=Documents on the history of European integration: Plans for European union in Great Britain and in exile, 1939\u20131945 (including 107 documents in their original languages on 3 microfiches)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X3TsVCAt9F4C&pg=PA648|accessdate=10 August 2011|year=1985|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-009724-5|page=648}}</ref> The idea was to expand it into a [[wikt:Central Europe|Central Europe]]an confederation with Poland and [[Lithuania]], [[Czechoslovakia]] as its nucleus around which would be grouped [[Romania]], [[Hungary]], Yugoslavia and [[Greece]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Schmidt, Andrea|title=From Intermarium to the Three Seas Initiative: The Implications of the Polish Orientation Over the Central and Eastern European Region on Hungarian Policy in Baltic-Black Sea Regionalisms: Patchworks and Networks at Europe's Eastern Margins|editor1=Bogdanova, Olga |editor2=Makarychev, Andrey|publisher=Springer Nature|date= 2019|page=157|isbn= 978-3-0302-48789}}</ref> The agenda behind this was to create a common political blue-print for smaller countries abutting larger European powers and became the basis of a Belgian-Dutch union which would mirror the Polish-Czech arrangement.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Together and Alone in Allied London: Czechoslovak, Norwegian and Polish Governments-in-Exile, 1940\u20131945|author=Jakubec, Pavol|journal=[[International History Review]]|date=2019|doi=10.1080/07075332.2019.1600156}}</ref>\n\nThis scheme of Retinger's caused problems between London and [[Moscow]]. In order not to tread on Soviet toes, the British altered their position and refused to back Sikorski's negotiations with the eight smaller European states. In his speech on the Council of Europe, [[Winston Churchill]] [https://www.winstonchurchill.org/resources/speeches/1941-1945-war-leader/national-address/ BBC radio broadcast] on 21 March 1943 referred to the necessity of smaller nations forming groupings, but that it was too early to go into detail. The most Retinger was able to achieve was to push through the [[Sikorski-Mayski Agreement]], signed on 30 July 1941, which provided for the formation of the [[Anders' army]], thus ridding Stalin of the immediate human problem posed by the hundreds of thousands of Polish [[Prisoner of war|POW]]s and deportees from the [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u201345)|Soviet occupied]] [[Kresy Zachodnie|Kresy]] regions of the former [[Second Polish Republic]], who after an arduous odyssey across thousands of miles would eventually end up as the [[United Kingdom]]'s human problem.<ref>{{cite book|author=Anders, Lt.-General W\u0142adys\u0142aw|title= An Army in Exile|publisher= MacMillan & Co. Ltd|date=1949|page=73}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Polish Underground Army, the Western Allies, and the Failure of Strategic Unity in World War II|author=Peszke, Michael Alfred|publisher=McFarland|date= 2015|isbn=978-1-4766-10276|page=70}}</ref> This trade-off adumbrated the [[Tehran Conference|Tehran]] and [[Yalta Conference]]s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Identity in Flux. The Polish Community in Britain|author=Sword, Keith|place=London|publisher=School of Slavonic and East European Studies - SSEES Occasional Papers No. 36| date=1996|isbn=0-903425-60-2|pages=24\u201330|url=https://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/id/eprint/10078280/1/SSEES0012.pdf|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Brushes with death==\nRetinger narrowly avoided perishing in the sea off [[Gibraltar]] with [[Wladyslaw Sikorski's death controversy|W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]], in July 1943, but for the fact that he was not needed to accompany the premier on a troop inspection in the Middle East and would be better employed in London. The spare seat on the plane went to Sikorski's daughter who died with her father.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> Retinger was devastated by this turn of events. His relationship with Sikorski's successor, [[Stanislaw Mikolajczyk]] was much more ambivalent, but he obtained his consent for a special mission to Poland under [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]] in April 1944.<ref>Bu\u0142hak, W\u0142adys\u0142aw. \"The Foreign Office and the [[Special Operations Executive]] and the Expedition of J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger to Poland, April\u2013July 1944\", ''[[The Polish Review]]'', vol. 61, no. 3, 2016, pp. 33\u201357.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Members of the Polish Government, Prime Minister's Office|publisher=the Gazette|location=Edinburgh|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/Edinburgh/issue/16118/page/134/data.pdf|page=184|date=1944-04-21|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nWith an SOE brief and without prior training, Retinger, aged 56, parachuted into [[German-occupied Poland|occupied Poland]] with 2nd Lt. [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt]], (see [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt#Operation \"Salamander\"|Operation Salamander]]), to meet with Polish underground figures, to deliver money to the Polish underground, and to \"explain to his fellow Poles in the homeland 'how are we going to lose this war'\".<ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\">{{cite book|last1=Eringer|first1=Robert|author-link=Robert Eringer|title=The Global Manipulators|publisher=Pentacle Books|asin=B00546KTEM|oclc=26551991}}</ref>{{rp|pages=16\u201322}} <ref name = \"JR\"/>{{rp|page=265}}<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>  Following at least one assassination attempt on him, Retinger expressed his frustration thus:\n\n{{blockquote|You know why I came.  The [Underground] [[Government Delegation for Poland|Delegate]] knows as well.... They know that I only want to convince them that it will be necessary in the future to cooperate with the Communists, because no English are coming here, only Russians.  If we do not get along with them somehow, it will be a terrible tragedy, because we well know what [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]] and the [[NKVD]] [Interior Ministry of the Soviet Union] are. And it's about trying to make people here understand this fact. And they want to murder me!}}<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>\n\nThe latter quip was a reference to elements in the [[Polish Underground Army]], the [[Armia Krajowa|AK]] who were convinced Retinger was not serving the interests of his country and should therefore be \"removed\". One apparent attempt to liquidate him in Poland was on the grounds of a \"death sentence\" to be carried out on the alleged orders of general [[Kazimierz Sosnkowski]]. It was foiled by the intervention of an old friend and [[Armia Krajowa|AK fighter]], Tadeusz Gebethner.<ref>{{cite web|title=The story of Tadeusz Gebethner|url=https://sprawiedliwi.org.pl/en/stories-of-rescue/story-tadeusz-gebethner|publisher=sprawiedliwi.org.pl |access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> There was also an attempt during his visit in occupied Poland to poison him, which failed. On his return to London, he spent some time in the [[Dorchester Hotel]] in London's [[Park Lane, London|Park Lane]] recovering from his ordeal of the trip, which left him lame in one leg for the rest of his life, possibly due to the [[Polyneuritis]] brought on by the poison. His first visitor at the Dorchester was Sir [[Anthony Eden]], the foreign secretary.<ref name=\"Davies\"/><ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\"/>\n\nImmediately after the war, in 1945-6 Retinger travelled to [[Warsaw]] with emergency aid for the capital's population. It consisted largely of tons of British and US Army surplus, such as equipment, blankets and field-kitchens.<ref name= \"Kultura\"/> When his erstwhile military escort from \"operation Salamander\", [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Tadeusz Chciuk]] and his new wife, Ewa, were arrested in Poland as subversives by the Polish Communist security service, Retinger allegedly appealed over their heads directly to [[Vyacheslav Molotov|Molotov]] in [[Moscow]] to have them released. Apparently the personal intervention succeeded. In 1948 the Chciuks became refugees in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jozef Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Chciuk-Celt, Jan|url=http://pdf.amazingdiscoveries.org/References/RB/275%20PDFs/jozef-hieronim-retinger-slide-79.pdf|access-date=2020-03-03}} Jan Chciuk-Celt is the younger son of Tadeusz Chciuk, Retinger's military courier during \"Operation Saamander\" and was a co-author and editor of his father's war memoirs.</ref><ref>{{cite book|authors=[[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Marek Celt]], Jan Chciuk-Celt|title=Parachuting into Poland, 1944: Memoir of a Secret Mission with Jozef Retinger|publisher=McFarland|page=17|date= 2013|isbn=978-1-4766-03384}}</ref>\n\n===Unwanted intrusion===\nDark days followed World War II when tensions rose between former Western and Eastern allies and in April 1946 Retinger's flat in [[Bayswater]], West London, was broken into and his and his secretary's files ransacked by persons unknown. He reported the matter to [[Scotland Yard]], but the [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]] were not overly bothered. As a result, Retinger escalated his complaint and ended up being interviewed by the Britain's security services. His view was that the newly communist embassy of the [[Polish People's Republic]] were responsible for the break-in.<ref>{{cite book|author=Moss, Eloise|title=Night Raiders: Burglary and the Making of Modern Urban Life in London, 1860-1968|publisher=Oxford University Press|date= 2019|pages=186-87|isbn=978-0-1925-7677-4}}</ref>\n\nFrom the moment Winston Churchill had made his \"[[Iron Curtain]]\" speech in [[Fulton, Missouri]], in April 1946, Retinger turned his efforts to a modified European project he had harboured for decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.winstonchurchill.org/i4a/pages/index.cfm?pageid=429 |title=Sinews of Peace (Iron Curtain) |accessdate=2007-02-26 |last=Churchill |first=Winston |publisher=Churchill Centre |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207054810/http://www.winstonchurchill.org/i4a/pages/index.cfm?pageid=429 |archivedate=7 February 2007 }}</ref><ref name= \"Kultura\"/>\n\n==Vision for Europe==\n[[File:Krakow-Jozef Retinger plaque.jpg|thumb|right|[[Krak\u00f3w]] plaque commemorating Retinger, \"great pioneer of European unity\".]]\nAfter World War II, Retinger feared another devastating war in Europe, this time fought between \"Russia\" and \"the Anglo-Saxons\".<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/> He became a leading advocate of [[European unification]] as a means of securing peace.<ref>{{cite web|author=Retinger, J. H.|title= The European Continent? Address given to the Royal Institute of Foreign Affairs in London|url=https://www.cvce.eu/content/publication/2008/2/19/534c684a-8924-445a-8181-58360f939f56/publishable_en.pdf|publisher=CVCE|date= 7 May 1946|access-date=2020-03-27}} Correction: although the original states Royal Institute of Foreign Affairs, it should read [[Royal Institute of International Affairs]], known today as \"[[Chatham House]]\", this is likely a copyediting error at CVCE (ed.).</ref> He helped found both the [[European Movement]] and the [[Council of Europe]], somewhat to the dismay of the philosopher Count [[Richard Coudenhove-Kalergi]], the post-[[World War I]] [[Anti-communism|anti-bolshevist]] founder of the [[Paneuropean Union]] movement.<ref name=\"wilford\"/>{{rp|pages=227\u2013228}}<ref>{{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1|page=165}}</ref> \n\nRetinger, with his connections in Holland, Belgium, and [[Switzerland]] (he was a friend of [[Denis de Rougemont]]), took his cue from [[Winston Churchill]]'s 1947 [[Zurich]] speech and found fertile ground with thirteen British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] members of Parliament who backed the idea of a loose European association of states. Working in particular with Britain's [[Duncan Sandys]], incidentally Churchill's son-in-law, he took on the lion's share of the work and became Honorary Secretary General of the [[European Movement]]. He organised the 1948 [[Congress of Europe|Hague Congress]] which brought together the two camps of those for a unified Europe and those in favour of a federal Europe.<ref name=\"Lane\"/> During the congress, Retinger networked assiduously among the delegates, who included the Vatican diplomat, [[Giovanni Montini]], the future [[Pope Paul VI]]. Ensuing discussions led eventually to the formation in 1951 of a [[European Coal and Steel Community]].<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>  \n\n===Creator of Bilderberg=== \nRetinger was the initiator and architect of the informal [[Bilderberg Group|Bilderberg]] conferences in 1952-54 and was their general secretary until his premature death in London in 1960. A founding member of the Bilderberg Group, later British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Foreign Secretary, [[Denis Healey]], described the secretive Bilderberg meetings as the \"brainchild\" of Retinger.<ref>{{cite web|title=Denis Healey on Bilderberg|url=https://www.worldsocialism.org/spgb/socialist-standard/2002/2000s/no-1175-july-2002/denis-healey-bilderberg/|publisher=worldsocialism.org|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Aubourg, Valerie|title=Organizing Atlanticism: the Bilderberg group and the Atlantic institute, 1952\u20131963|journal=[[Intelligence and National Security]]|volume=18, (2)|date=2003|pages= 92-105 |doi=10.1080/02684520412331306760}}</ref> Despite eschewing any distinctions or medals throughout his life, in 1958 he was nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.nobelprize.org/nomination/archive/show.php?id=15660 |title =Nomination for Nobel Peace Prize: Joseph Retinger |author =Nobelprize.org |publisher =Nobel Media AB 2014 |website = Nomination Database| date = |access-date = 2014-10-09}}</ref> He died in poverty of lung cancer.<ref name =\"BP\">{{cite web|title=J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|url=https://kangur.uek.krakow.pl//biblioteka/retinger/B.%20Podgorski%20-%20J.H.%20Retinger%201888-1960.pdf|lang=pl|page=53|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> He was buried at [[North Sheen Cemetery]] in the presence of five British cabinet ministers as well as of his two younger daughters who were finally reconciled with him.<ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\"/>{{rp|pages=16\u201322}} According to the oration of Sir [[Edward Beddington-Behrens]], Retinger not only had special access to [[10 Downing Street]] but also to the [[White House]].<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> \n[[File:Gr\u00f3b J\u00f3zefa Hieronima Retingera.jpg|thumb|right|Retinger's grave, [[North Sheen Cemetery]], London]]\nRetinger's long time personal assistant and the editor of his posthumous memoirs, John Pomian, actually {{Interlanguage link|Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz|pl}}, was another Polish emigr\u00e9 in London, later a director of the Heim gallery in London's [[St James's]], owned by the influential Polish art historian and philanthropist, [[Andrzej Ciechanowiecki]].<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://nekrologi.wyborcza.pl/0,11,,373783,Jan-Pomiana-B%C5%82awdziewicza-kondolencje.html | title =Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz | trans-title=Obituary of Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz|journal = Wyborcza.pl |date=2015| lang = pl | access-date = 2016-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRetinger married twice. In 1912 he wed the well-born Otolia Zubrzycka (divorced 1921, died 1984), with whom he had a daughter, Malina (later Puchalska). In 1926 he wed Stella Morel (died 1933), daughter of French-born pacifist and [[Dundee]] member of Parliament [[E.D. Morel]] and Mary, n\u00e9e Richardson, with whom he had two daughters, Maria (later Fforde) and Stasia (later French). \n\nDuring the Great War and after, Retinger appears to have fallen under the spell of several women, especially the American journalist [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]], a supposed lover of Joseph Conrad.<ref name= \"JM\">{{cite book|title=Joseph Conrad: A Biography|author= Meyers, Jeffrey|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|date= 2001|page=361|isbn=978-0-8154-11123}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Athens Observer|first=Donald E.|last=Wilkes|title=Jane Anderson: The Nazi Georgia Peach|url=http://digitalcommons.law.uga.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1019&context=fac_pm|date=May 18, 1995|page=5|accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref> Retinger's own liaison with Anderson brought about the breakdown of Retinger's marriage to Otolia and drove a wedge between him and his friend Conrad.<ref name= \"JM\"/>{{rp|page=293}} However Conrad biographer, John Stape, gives an alternative version for the cooling of relations between the two men, suggesting instead that as Retinger's enthusiasms were not shared by the novelist, shortly after the war, without his charming wife by his side, Retinger's proneness to exaggeration and tactlessness made him less socially acceptable.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Several Lives of Joseph Conrad|author= Stape, John|publisher=Random House|date= 2010|pages=187\u2013188|isbn=978-1409006824}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nOver sixty years after his death, the left-leaning Retinger continues to attract fascination and controversy with, on one hand, admirers of his political skill, his apparently selfless single-mindedness and his lasting institutional legacy in Europe and beyond.<ref>{{cite book|author=Wisnewski, Gerhard|title=The Bilderbergers Puppet-Masters of Power?: An Investigation into Claims of Conspiracy at the Heart of Politics, Business and the Media|translator=J. Collis|trans-title=Drahtzieher der Macht (2010)|date=2014|place=West Sussex|publisher=Clairview Books|isbn=978-1-90557075-1|pages=63\u201366}}</ref> {{Interlanguage link|Adam Pragier|pl}}, a notable Polish exile and political commentator, has described him as \"as a sort of adventurer, but in the good sense of the word\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Czas przesz\u0142y dokonany - Czasy i ludzie|author= Pragier, Adam|title=Czas przesz\u0142y dokonany, Part 1|series= volume 7 of 100-lecie Niepodleg\u0142o\u015bci - 100th anniversary of Polish independence|editors=Friszke, Andrzej and Peja\u015b, Ewa|location=Warsaw|publisher=Muzeum Historii Polski (Museum of Polish History)|date= 2018|isbn=978-8-3652-4829-9|orig-year=First published by B. \u015awiderski in London 1966|page=852|trans-title=The Past Perfect - Lives and Times}}</ref> On the other hand, detractors impugn his influence due to alleged connections with deeply secret and malign factions for which there is so far no reliable evidence.<ref>{{cite journal|author=K\u0119der, Wojciech|title=Recenzje: Bogdan Podg\u00f3rski, J\u00f3zef Retinger prywatny polityk, Universitas, Krak\u00f3w 2013, ss. 417.\n|journal=Studia Sandomierskie 23|date= 2016|pages=303\u2013314|lang=pl|trans-title=Review of Bogdan Podg\u00f3rski, ''J\u00f3zef Retinger private politician''. Krak\u00f3w: Universitas. 2013, pages 417.|url=https://journals.indexcopernicus.com/api/file/viewByFileId/84684.pdf}}\n</ref><ref>{{Cite web|author=Cornell, Svante E|title=Erbakan, K\u0131sak\u00fcrek, and the Mainstreaming of Extremism in Turkey |publisher=[[Hudson Institute]]|date=2018 |url=https://www.hudson.org/research/14375-erbakan-k-sak-rek-and-the-mainstreaming-of-extremism-in-turkey|access-date=2020-04-03}} see fn. 19.</ref> He remains an enigma and probably the one significant contributor to post-war European peace without a monument.<ref name = \"BP\"/>{{rp|page=60}} \n\nIn 2000 [[The Daily Telegraph]]'s [[Ambrose Evans-Pritchard]] revealed from declassified US Government records that:\n{{blockquote|The leaders of the European Movement \u2013 Retinger, the visionary [[Robert Schuman]] and the former Belgian prime minister [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] \u2013 were all treated as hired hands by their American sponsors. The US role was handled as a covert operation. ACUE\u2019s funding came from the [[Ford Foundation|Ford]] and [[Rockefeller Foundation]]s as well as business groups with close ties to the US government.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/1356047/Euro-federalists-financed-by-US-spy-chiefs.html|title=Euro-federalists financed by US Spy Chief|author= Ambrose Evans-Pritchard|date=18 September 2000|publisher= The Daily Telegraph|author-link=Ambrose Evans-Pritchard}}</ref>}} The finding, in the context of the [[Cold War]], was subsequently analysed in greater detail by ''[[Le Figaro Magazine|Le Figaro]]'' commentator, {{Interlanguage link|R\u00e9mi Kauffer|fr}} in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kauffer, R\u00e9mi|title=Quand la CIA finan\u00e7ait la construction europ\u00e9enne - Par R\u00e9mi Kauffer, Source : Historia 2003|date=12 June 2019|url=http://www.comite-valmy.org/spip.php?article516|publisher=Comit\u00e9 Valmy|lang=fr|trans-title=When the CIA financed the construction of Europe by R\u00e9mi Kauffer, source: Historia 2003|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> However, as Hugh Wilford demonstrates, the initiative to win American backing for a \"United States of Europe\" did not come either from [[Allen Dulles]], deputy, then chief of the [[CIA]], nor from Senator [[William Fulbright]], chairman of the [[ACUE]], but from the lobbying Europeans themselves guided by disparate motives, namely Coudenhove-Kalergi and Retinger who eclipsed him due to his close connection with [[Winston Churchill]] on European matters.<ref name=\"wilford\"/> Retinger's plan was that the [[United States]] had to be integral to the political and economic support for a war damaged [[Western Europe]]. As \"head of casting\" for his project, he set about finding key Americans who would collaborate with him, among whom at that time was [[Charles Douglas Jackson]], [[Time Inc.|Time-Life]] publisher in the 1940s and one time head of propaganda at the [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Eisenhower]] White House.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Bilderberg Conspiracy: Inside the World\u2019s Most Powerful Secret Society|author=Jeffers, H. Paul|chapter= 1|publisher= Kensington Publishing Corp.|date= 2012|isbn= 978-0-8065-3595-1}}</ref> \n\nIn summary, Retinger was a figure who divided opinions, whose allegiances like his roots, have remained obscure and whose accounts of himself varied according to his audience, subverting his reliability as emerges among Conrad biographers and from numerous other sources, including that of Norbert W\u00f3jtowicz, of the Polish [[Institute of National Remembrance]], in his considered and annotated review of Marek Celt's 2006 posthumously published \"Z Retingerem do Warszawy i z powrotem. Raport z podziemia 1944\", [''To Warsaw with Retinger and Back. A Report from the Underground 1944''] edited by Wojciech Frazik.<ref>{{cite web|author= Norbert W\u00f3jtowicz|title=Recenzja: Marek Celt, Z Retingerem do Warszawy i z powrotem. Raport z Podziemia 1944, red. Wojciech Frazik, Wydawnictwo LTW, \u0141omianki 2006 |trans-title = Review of Marek Celt, To Warsaw with Retinger and Back. A Report from the Underground 1944, ed. Wojciech Frazik pub. LTW. \u0141omianki, 2006|url=http://www.polska1918-89.pl/pdf/marek-celt,-z-retingerem-do-warszawy-i-z-powrotem.-raport-z-podziemia-,5423.pdf|publisher=www.polska1918-89|lang=pl|access-date=2020-03-31}} The book was subsequently translated into English by Jan Chciuk-Celt and published by McFarland in 2013 as ''Parachuting into Poland, 1944: Memoir of a Secret Mission with Jozef Retinger'', {{ISBN|978-1-4766-03384}} \"Marek Celt\", the pseudonym of Tadeusz Chciuk, was the military courier who accompanied Retinger on his parachute mission to Poland in 1944. A bond of friendship developed between the two men and they collaborated again on supplying aid to Warsaw from London in 1945-6.</ref> Despite the perception of personality flaws, it does not alter Retinger's mature post-war European legacy.<ref>{{cite web|title= J\u00f3zef Retinger|publisher=bilderbergmeetings.co.uk|url= http://bilderbergmeetings.co.uk/jozef-retinger/|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n== Selected works==\nBy J. H. Retinger:\n* {{cite book|date= 1908|title=Le conte fantastique dans le romantisme fran\u00e7ais|place= Gen\u00e8ve|publisher= Slatkine Reprints, 1973|trans-title=Fantastical Tales in the French Romantic Tradition|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title=Histoire de la litt\u00e9rature fran\u00e7aise du romantisme \u00e0 nos jours|place= Paris|publisher=[[Bernard Grasset| B. Grasset]]|date= 1911|trans-title=The History of French Literature from Romanticism to the Present Day|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title= The Poles and Prussia|place=London|date=1913|url=https://explore.library.leeds.ac.uk/special-collections-explore/334918/the_poles_and_prussia?subject=%22Polish%20question%22&resultOffset=2}} available at University of Leeds Library\n* {{cite book|title=La Pologne et l'\u00c9quilibre europ\u00e9en|place= Paris|date= 1916|trans-title=Poland and the Stability of Europe|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title=Morones of Mexico; a history of the labour movement in that country|place=London|publisher= The Labour Pub. Co. Ltd.|date= 1926}}\n* {{cite book|title=Tierra mexicana; the history of land and agriculture in ancient and modern Mexico|place= London|publisher= N. Douglas|date= 1928}}\n* {{cite book|title=Polacy w cywilizacjach zagranicznych|trans-title= Poles in Foreign Civilizations|place=Warsaw|date= 1934|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite journal|title= Historja i polityka: Nowy czynnik w dyplomacji mi\u0119dzynarodowej|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie (50)|date= 4 December 1938|trans-title=History and Politics: A new factor in international diplomacy|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite journal|title= Historja i polityka: Zast\u00f3j w mi\u0119dzynarodowej dzia\u0142alno\u015bci Rosji|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie (51)|date= 11 December 1938|trans-title=History and Politics: Suspension of Russian activity in international relations|lang=pl}} \n* {{cite book|title=All about Poland: facts, figures, documents|place= London|publisher= Minerva Pub. Co.|date= 1941}}\n* {{cite book|title=Conrad and His Contemporaries |year=1942 |publisher=Roy |location=New York|orig-year=First published by Minerva, London, 1941}}\n*  {{cite book|title= The European Continent? Address given to the Royal Institute of International Affairs in London|url=https://www.cvce.eu/content/publication/2008/2/19/534c684a-8924-445a-8181-58360f939f56/publishable_en.pdf|date= 7 May 1946|place=London}}\n*  {{cite book|title=The Bilderberg Group|place= Hertfordshire, UK|date= 1959}}\n*  {{cite book|title=Under Polish eyes|place=United Kingdom|publisher= Joseph Conrad Society|date= 1975}}\n\nAbout Retinger:\n* {{cite journal|author=Poraj, Stanis\u0142aw|title= The knight among nations|journal= Tydzie\u0144 Literacki Polski Zbrojnej, 2 (24)|lang=pl|date= 19 June 1938}}\n* {{cite book|author=[[Denis de Rougemont|de Rougemont, Denis]]|date= 1961|title=A Biographical Sketch. In Tribute to a Great European|editor= Retinger, J.H.|pages=20\u201350|place= Geneva|publisher= Centre Europe\u00e9n de la Culture|lang=}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Siemaszko, Zbigniew Sebastian|date=1967|title= Retinger w Polsce 1944 r.|place=Paris|journal= Zeszyty Historyczne, 12|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|title=J\u00f3zef Retinger: Memoirs of an Eminence Grise|editor=Pomian, John|publisher= Sussex University Press/Chatto & Windus|date= 1972| isbn=0-85621-002-1|oclc=844436367}}.\n* {{cite book|author=[[Jan Nowak-Jeziora\u0144ski|Nowak, Jan]]|title= Kurier z Warszawy|place= London|publisher= Odnowa|date= 1978|lang=pl|isbn= 0-903705-37-0}}\n* {{cite book|publisher=[[Polski S\u0142ownik Biograficzny]]|title= J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|volume= XXXI|date= 1988-1989|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|title=In remembrance of Joseph Retinger 1988-1960, Initiator of the European League for Economic Cooperation|publisher= [[European League for Economic Cooperation]]|place= Brussels|date= 1996}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Grosbois, Thierry|date= 1999|title=L'action de J\u00f3zef Retinger en faveur de l'id\u00e9e europ\u00e9enne 1940-46|journal= Revue Europ\u00e9enne d'Histoire| volume= 6|issue= 34|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Kalicki, W\u0142odzimierz|date=2010|title=Gracz, kt\u00f3ry budowa\u0142 Europ\u0119|trans-title=The Player who built Europe|journal= Gazeta Wyborcza |issue=219|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|authors=\t[[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Marek Celt]], Jan Chciuk-Celt|title=Parachuting into Poland, 1944: Memoir of a Secret Mission with Jozef Retinger|publisher=McFarland|date= 2013|isbn=978-1-4766-03384}}\n* {{cite book|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|title= J\u00f3zef Retinger \u2013 prywatny polityk|trans-title=J\u00f3zef Retinger - a private politician|publisher= Universitas|date= 2013|lang=pl|isbn=97883-242-2351-0}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of governments in exile during World War II]]\n*[[European Movement]]\n*[[European Union]]\n*[[List of Poles#Diplomats|List of Poles]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal|author=Pragier, Adam|title=Nie by\u0142o k\u0142opotu z Polakami|trans-title=There was no Problem with the Poles|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci, Rok 10, Nr 21 (477)|lang=pl|date=1955-05-22|place=London|url=http://retropress.pl/wiadomosci/nie-bylo-klopotu-z-polakami/}}\n* {{cite book|author=Bines, Jeffrey|title=Poland's S.O.E: A British Perspective: the Story of the Polish Country Section of the Special Operations Executive 1940-1946 Including the British Military Mission Number Four to Poland 1939|publisher=Polish Underground Movement Study Trust|date= 2018|place=London|isbn=978-0-9928-03056}} \n* {{cite journal|author= Biskupski, M.B.|title=Spy, Patriot or Internationalist? The Early Career of J\u00f3zef Retinger, Polish Patriarch of European Union|journal=[[The Polish Review]]| volume= 43|date= 1998|issue=1| pages= 23\u201367}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Bu\u0142hak, W\u0142adys\u0142aw|title=The Foreign Office and the Special Operations Executive and the Expedition of J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger to Poland, April\u2013July 1944|journal=The Polish Review| volume= 61|date= 2016|issue=3| pages= 33\u201357|doi=10.5406/polishreview.61.3.0033}}\n* {{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=J\u00f3zef H. Retinger \u2013 pomys\u0142odawca i wsp\u00f3\u0142tw\u00f3rca Grupy Bilderbergu|trans-title=Joseph Retinger: Visionary Co-founder of the [[Bilderberg Group]]|lang=pl|journal= Studia polityczne|publisher= ISP PAN|volume= 10|date= 2000}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Dzia\u0142alno\u015b\u0107 J.H. Retingera na rzecz zjednoczonej Europy|trans-title=Joseph Retinger\u2019s Work for a United Europe|journal= Studia Europejskie|publisher= Centrum Europejskie Uniwersytetu Warszawskiego|volume=  16|date= 2000|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Dzia\u0142alno\u015b\u0107 J\u00f3zefa Hieronima Retingera na rzecz integracji europejskiej|lang=pl|trans-title= Joseph Retinger\u2019s Work for European Integration|publisher= Wydawnictwo Adam Marsza\u0142ek|place= Toru\u0144|date= 2008|isbn=978-83-7611-184-1}}\n* {{cite book|author= Hampson, Robert|title=Conrad's Secrets|publisher=\tPalgrave Macmillan|date= 2012|isbn=978-0-2305-0783-8}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Joseph Retinger's Vision of [a] United Europe After World War II: Central and Eastern European Question|journal= [[The Polish Review]]| volume= 60|date= 2015 |issue=4|pages= 49\u201366|doi=10.5406/polishreview.60.4.0049}}\n* {{cite book|author=Wisnewski, Gerhard|title=The Bilderbergers Puppet-Masters of Power?: An Investigation into Claims of Conspiracy at the Heart of Politics, Business and the Media|translator=J. Collis|trans-title=Drahtzieher der Macht (2010)|date=2014|place=West Sussex|publisher=Clairview Books|isbn=978-1-90557075-1|pages=63\u201366}}\n* {{cite book|title=Informal Alliance: The Bilderberg Group and Transatlantic Relations during the Cold War, 1952-1968|series=  Routledge Studies in Modern History|author=Gijswijt, Thomas W.|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date= 2018|isbn=978-1-3511-8102-0}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161027232624/http://home.teleport.com/~flyheart/retinger.htm Biography of Jozef Retinger]\n*[https://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/205254911 The Polish Soviet Relations During The Second World War, photographs held by the [[Imperial War Museum]] including of Dr. J\u00f3zef Retinger on 30.07.1941]\n*[http://www.jasperfforde.com/ten_things/ten_things8.html photograph of Retinger flanking Churchill at the Hague 1948, on Retinger's grandson's website]\n*[http://www.bilderberg.org/bildhist.htm#Memoirs Chapter 4, European Unity.] from ''Memoirs of An Eminence Grise'' by John Pomian,\n*[http://bilderbergmeetings.co.uk/jozef-retinger/ Bilderberg website on Retinger's life in brief]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Retinger, Jozef}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Poland to Russia]]\n[[Category:Council of Europe]]\n[[Category:Members of the Steering Committee of the Bilderberg Group]]\n[[Category:Polish politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Freemasons]]\n[[Category:European integration pioneers]]\n[[Category:Geopoliticians]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Polish diplomats]]\n[[Category:Polish spies]]\n[[Category:Secret Intelligence Service personnel]]\n[[Category:Special Operations Executive personnel]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish writers]]\n[[Category:Exophonic writers]]\n[[Category:Polish essayists]]\n[[Category:Male essayists]]\n[[Category:Polish political writers]]\n[[Category:Polish people of World War II]]\n[[Category:People of World War II]]\n[[Category:History of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Rusyn descent]]\n", "name_user": "Po Mieczu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eControversy:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C3%B3zef_Retinger"}
{"title_page": "Burj el-Shemali", "text_new": "{{pp-30-500|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Burj El Shimali\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Governorates of Lebanon|Governorate]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Tyre District]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{Flag|Lebanon}}\n| subdivision_name1               = [[South Governorate]]\n| native_name_lang                = ar\n| subdivision_type2               = [[Districts of Lebanon|District]]\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| official_name                   = \n| pushpin_map                     = Lebanon\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|33|15|47|N|35|14|20|E|display=inline,title}}\n| image_map                       = \n| image_skyline                   = BurjAlShimali-Tower 23092019RomanDeckert.jpg\n| settlement_type                 = Town\n| native_name                     = {{lang|ar| \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0631\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0645\u0627\u0644\u064a}}\n| image_caption                   = The Burj \u2013 \"Tower\" \u2013 of Burj El Shimali\n| area_total_ha                   = 1069\n| elevation_m                     = 62\n}}\n{{Other uses|Burj (disambiguation){{!}}Burj}}\n'''Burj el-Shemali''' (Arabic: \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0631\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0645\u0627\u0644\u064a) is a [[Municipality|municpality]] located some 86 km south of Beirut and 3 km east of the [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]]/Sour peninsula, merging into its urban area. It is part of the [[Tyre Union of Municipalities]] within the [[Tyre District]] of the [[South Governorate]] of [[Lebanon]].  \n\nIt is particularly known for hosting the second-largest of the twelve [[Palestinian refugee camps]] in the country as a ''[[de facto]]'' [[Autonomy|autonomous]] [[Enclave and exclave|exclave]] effectively out of the reach of Lebanese officials: The camp is ruled by Popular Committees of Palestinian parties under the leadership of the [[Palestine Liberation Organization|Palestinian Liberation Organisation]] (PLO) which is de facto recognised by the municipality through some degree of coordination and cooperation.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Suleiman|first=Jaber|url=https://www.academia.edu/37289610|title=Lebanese- Palestinian Relations: Apolitical, Human Rights, and Security Perspective|journal=Policy Dialogue Series: Lebanese- Palestinian Relations|publisher=Common Space Initiative for Shared Knowledge and Consensus Building|year=2017|location=Beirut|pages=27|format=PDF}}</ref> The [[UNRWA|United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East]] (UNRWA) has the mandate to provide basic services, assisted by local and international NGOs. The [[Lebanese Armed Forces]] control entry and exit through the camp's main gate.<ref name=\":3\" />  \n\n== Name ==\nBurj el-Shemali \u2013 also transliterated into the spellings of \"Borj\" or \"Bourj\" combined with a version of \"Shimali\", \"Shamali\", ''\"''Shem\u00e2ly''\",'' \"Chemali\", \"Chamali\", or \"Chmali\" with or without the article \"el\", \"al\", \"esh\", or \"ash\" \u2013  is commonly translated as \"Northern Tower\", as done by [[Edward Henry Palmer|E. H. Palmer]] in the 1881 [[PEF Survey of Palestine|''Survey of Western Palestine'' (SWP)]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Palmer|first=E.H.|url=https://archive.org/details/surveyofwesternp00conduoft|title=The Survey of Western Palestine: Arabic and English Name Lists Collected During the Survey by Lieutenants Conder and Kitchener, R. E. Transliterated and Explained by E.H. Palmer.|publisher=Committee of the [[Palestine Exploration Fund]]|year=1881|isbn=|location=London|pages=4}}</ref>\n\nThe settlement is named after a medieval tower on its main hill that overlooks Tyre.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Badawi|first=Ali Khalil|title=TYRE|publisher=Al-Athar Magazine|year=2018|isbn=|edition=4th|location=Beirut|pages=5, 7, 30, 136\u2013137}}</ref> The Arabic word \"Burj\" reportedly originated from the [[Ancient Greek]] \"pyrgos\".<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/4847281|title=Arabic Etymological Dictionary|last=Rajki|first=Andras|date=2005|website=Academia.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Territory ==\nBurj el-Shemali reportedly covers an area of 1.069 [[hectare]], rising to an [[elevation]] of more than 60 metres on a hill overlooking Tyre/Sour [[peninsula]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.localiban.org/borj-ech-chemali-3539|title=Borj Ech Chemali|last=Tohm\u00e9|first=Joseph|last2=Aouad|first2=Michel|date=23 October 2015|website=localiban|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nTogether with the built-up areas of three adjacent municipalities \u2013 Sour on the peninsula and the coastal areas to the West, [[Abbasiyet Sour]] to the North, and [[Ain Baal]] to the South-East \u2013 the urban part of Burj el-Shemali has integrated into one greater metropolitan Tyre. There are also unpopulated [[Agricultural land|agricultural lands]], especially in its Northern and Southern parts.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nMost reports about the size of the Palestinian camp give a fgure of about 135,000 square meters<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|url=https://placesjournal.org/article/camp-code/?cn-reloaded=1|title=Camp Code \u2013 How to navigate a refugee settlement|last=Martinez Mansell|first=Claudia|date=April 2016|journal=Places Journal|doi=10.22269/160405|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":8\" />, which means that it covers just a tiny fraction of the municipality's overall territory.<ref name=\":4\" /> It is less dense than other refugee camps in Lebanon<ref name=\":5\" />, but still one of the [[Population density|world's most densely populated areas]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Viaro|first=Alain|url=https://www.academia.edu/24548140|title=Assessment of Housing Conditions of Palestine Refugees|last2=Rueff|first2=Henri|publisher=UNRWA \u2013 Near East Project|year=2007|isbn=|location=|pages=18, 22|format=PDF}}</ref> The land is reportedly \"''rented by the Lebanese government for 99 years.''\"<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Ancient Times ===\n[[File:RomanTerracottaMaskOfSatyr-BurjAlShimali NationalMuseumOfBeirut RomanDeckert06102019.jpg|thumb|Mask of a [[Satyr]] from Burj el-Shemali, Roman period, on display at the [[National Museum of Beirut]]]]\nAccording to [[Ali Khalil Badawi|Ali Badawi]], the long-time chief-archaeologist for Southern Lebanon at the Directorate-General of Antiquities, it can be generally assumed that all villages around Tyre were established already during [[Prehistory|prehistoric times]] like the [[Neolithic|neolithic age]] (5.000 BCE).<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n[[Phoenicia|Phoenician]] [[Stele|stelas]] and other artefacts found in Burj el-Shemali give evidence that the place was used in the 5th to 4th century BCE for funerary purposes.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=A visit to the Museum... The short guide of the National Museum of Beirut, Lebanon|publisher=Ministry of Culture/Directorate General of Antiquities|year=2008|isbn=978-9953-0-0038-1|location=Beirut|pages=39}}</ref> If there were settlements during that time, they were probably demolished by the army of [[Alexander the Great]], who had all the coastal villages destroyed and the building materials used to connect the island of Tyre with a mole during the siege of 332 BCE.<ref name=\":1\" /> There are indications though of settlements at Burj el-Shemali dating back at least to the first century BCE.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Tyr \u2013 L'histoire d'une Ville|last=Badawi|first=Ali Khalil|publisher=Municipalit\u00e9 de Tyr / Tyre Municipality / Baladia Sour|year=2008|isbn=|location=Tyre/Sour/Tyr|pages=124|language=French}}</ref> \n\nDuring [[Roman Empire|Roman]] times, parts of Burj el-Shemali continued to be used as a [[necropolis]]. A number of its [[Hypogeum|hypogea]] - underground tombs - with [[Roman Empire|Roman]]-era [[Fresco|frescos]] are on display at the [[National Museum of Beirut|National Museum]] in [[Beirut]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The remains of a [[Byzantine Empire|Roman-Byzantine]] road are preserved underneath the modern main road.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n=== Medieval Times ===\nIt is not clear whether Burj el-Shemali continued to be settled and/or used as a fuenrary place after the Arab armies defeated the Byzantine empire in the region and took over Tyre in 635 CE for half a millenium of Islamic rule.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nWhen the Tyre was taken over by a [[Francia|Frankish]] army in the aftermath of the [[First Crusade]], the new rulers constructed a fortified tower on the hill of Burj el-Shemali overlooking the [[peninsula]] of Tyre. The village then adapted its name from that tower. There are also remains of another Crusader tower known as Al-Burj Al-Qobli in the Southern part of town. Like in acient times, the lands of Burj el-Shemali were used as cemeteries in medieval periods.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Ottoman Times ===\n[[File:BurjAlShimali-Tower-view-on-Tyre 23092019RomanDeckert.jpg|thumb|View from the Burj over Tyre]]\nAlthough the [[Ottoman Empire]] conquered the [[Levant]] in 1516, [[Jabal Amel]] (modern-day [[Southern Lebanon]]) remained mostly untouched for almost another century. When the Ottoman leadership at the [[Sublime Porte]] appointed the [[Druze]] leader [[Fakhr-al-Din II|Fakhreddine II]] of the Maan family to administer the area at the beginning of the 17th century, the [[Emir]] encouraged many [[Lebanese Shia Muslims|Metwali]] \u2013 the discriminated [[Shia Islam|Shia]] Muslims of what is now Lebanon \u2013 to settle to the East of Tyre to secure the road to [[Damascus]]. He thus also laid the foundation of the Lebanese part of modern Burj el-Shemali [[Demography|demographics]] as a predominantly Shiite place.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=Smit|first=Ferdinand|url=https://www.academia.edu/12778980|title=The battle for South Lebanon: Radicalisation of Lebanon's Shi'ites 1982\u20131985|publisher=Bulaaq, Uitgeverij|year=2006|isbn=978-9054600589|location=Amsterdam|pages=36, 90, 134, 150, 157, 220, 232, 269, 295|format=PDF}}</ref> \n\nIn 1881, the [[London]]-based [[Palestine Exploration Fund]]'s [[PEF Survey of Palestine|''Survey of Western Palestine'' (SWP)]] described it as <blockquote>\"''A large village built of stone, containing about 300 Metawileh, placed on a low [[ridge]], with [[Ficus|figs]], [[Olive|olives]], and [[arable land]] around. There are two good [[Spring (hydrology)|springs]] near.''\"</blockquote>and further noted that it was <blockquote>\"''a village with a similar tower of drafted [[masonry]] (as that of [[Borj Rahal]]). The hill is crowned by a stronghold, the vaults of which, slightly ogival, do not appear older than the Crusaders, but it was constructed of older blocks, some in drafted masonry and others completely smoothed. About a mile to the south-west of this hill is a subterranean series of tombs, each containing several ranges of [[Loculus (architecture)|loculi]], which was explored by [[Ernest Renan|Renan]].''\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Conder|first=Claude Reignier|url=https://ia600207.us.archive.org/21/items/surveyofwesternp01conduoft/surveyofwesternp01conduoft.pdf|title=The Survey of Western Palestine: Memoirs of the Topography, Orography, Hydrography, and Archaeology|last2=Kitchener|first2=Horatio Herbert|publisher=Committee of the Palestine Exploration Fund|year=1881|isbn=|volume=1|location=London|pages=48, 58|author-link=Claude Reignier Conder|author-link2=Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Modern Times ===\n==== Post-Independence (since 1943) ====\n{{Multiple image\n| align = \n| direction = vertical\n| total_width = \n| image1 = Palestinian refugees.jpg\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Refugees in Galilee.jpg\n| caption2 = \n| footer = Palestinian refugees making their way from [[Galilee]] to Lebanon in October\u2013November 1948\n}}[[File:Mount Canaan iv.jpg|left|thumb|View of Safed from Mount Canaan, taken in April or May 1948 during [[Operation Yiftach]]]]\nFollowing Lebanese independence from France on 22 November 1943, Southern Lebanon enjoyed less than five years of peace. The border with British-ruled [[Mandatory Palestine]] was still open during those times, and many [[Palestinian Jews|Palestianian Jews]] used to spend holidays in Tyre, while vice versa many Southern Lebanese would travel freely to [[Haifa]] and [[Tel Aviv]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hirst|first=David|title=Beware of Small States: Lebanon, Battleground of the Middle East.|publisher=Faber and Faber|year=2010|isbn=9780571237418|location=London|pages=30\u201331, 42}}</ref>\n\nHowever, when the state of [[Israel]] was declared in May 1948, an estimated 127,000 Palestinians fled to Lebanon alone until the end of that year.<ref name=\":10\" /> Confronted with this exodus \u2013 also known as the '''[[1948 Palestinian exodus|Nakba]]''' \u2013 a camp of tents was set up in Burj El Shimali, reportedly by the [[International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies|League of Red Cross Societies]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Sfeir|first=Jihane|url=https://www.academia.edu/10925357|title=L'exil Palestinien au Liban. 1947\u20131951|publisher=IFPO/Karthala/|year=2008|isbn=|location=Paris, Beirut|pages=65, 275|language=French}}</ref> The refugees were mainly from [[Hawla]], [[Lubya|Lubieh]], [[Sepphoris|Saffuri]], [[Tiberias]]<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.unrwa.org/where-we-work/lebanon/burj-shemali-camp|title=Burj Shemali Camp|last=|first=|date=|website=United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East (UNRWA)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 September 2019}}</ref>, and [[Safed]], where they mostly led agricultural existences.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|last=Martinez Mansell|first=Claudia|url=https://www.academia.edu/41442938|title=A View from Above \u2013 Balloon Mapping Bourj Al Shamali|last2=Dakhloul|first2=Mustapha|last3=Ismail|first3=Firas|work=This Is Not an Atlas \u2013 A Global Collection of Counter-Cartographies|publisher=transcript Verlag|year=2018|isbn=978-3-8394-4519-8|editor-last=Halder|editor-first=Severin|location=Bielefeld|pages=54\u201356}}</ref> Residents suffered from miserable conditions as the camp was initially only meant to be temporary and to serve as a transit point from which the refugees were relocated to camps in [[Sidon]] and [[Bekaa]].<ref name=\":6\" /> \n\nMany of them seem to have moved back to Burj el-Shemali once the current \"''footprint''\" was established in 1955.<ref name=\":5\" /> At that time UNRWA started providing humanitarian assistance \u2013 infrastructure services ([[water]], [[sewage]], [[electricity]], [[Road|road networks]] and shelter), [[school]] [[education]] and [[health care]] \u2013 to the residents of the camp.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/unrwa/refugees/lebanon/shemali.html|title=Archived copy|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090421060238/http://www.un.org/unrwa/refugees/lebanon/shemali.html|archivedate=2009-04-21|accessdate=2009-03-29}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, more Palestinian refugees settled in the area of [[Maachouk]] \u2013 1 km to the West of Burj El Shemali \u2013  on agricultural lands owned by the Lebanese State as a neighbourhood rather than a camp. Its eastern side, which is an [[Industry|industrial]] zone, as well as the main road's southern side with many [[Commerce|commercial]] activities fall within the jurisdiction of Burj el-Shemali municipality which demonstrates the [[arbitrariness]] of many boundaries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/UN-Habitat_2017.05.04_NPS_Maachouk.pdf|title=Maachouk Neighbourhood Profile & Strategy, Tyre, Lebanon|last=Harake|first=Dani|last2=Kuwalti|first2=Riham|date=31 May 2017|website=reliefweb|publisher=UN HABITAT Lebanon|pages=2\u20133, 25\u201326|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Tyrian public expressed [[solidarity]] with the [[Palestinian nationalism|Palestinian cause]] in that early post-independence era, especially thanks to the politics of Tyre's long-time Imam and social-reformer [[Abd al-Husayn Sharaf al-Din al-Musawi|Abdulhussein Sharafeddin]], who had given shelter to the [[Grand Mufti of Jerusalem]] [[Amin al-Husseini]] shortly after the beginning of the [[1936\u20131939 Arab revolt in Palestine]].<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite book|last=Abisaab|first=Rula Jurdi|title=The Shi'ites of Lebanon: Modernism, Communism, and Hizbullah's Islamists|last2=Abisaab|first2=Malek|publisher=Syracuse University Press|year=2017|isbn=9780815635093|location=New York|pages=9\u201311, 16\u201317, 24, 107}}</ref> After Sharafeddin's death in 1957 the balance of power in Southern Lebanon and the whole country gradually started to shift though with the arrival of a newcomer to the political scene:\n\nIn 1959, the [[Iran]]-born Shiite cleric [[Sayyid|Sayed]] [[Musa al-Sadr|Musa Sadr]] moved to Tyre to succeed the late Sharafeddin. As \"''one of his first significant acts''\" he established a [[Vocational education|vocational training]] center in Burj el-Shemali that became \"''an important symbol of his leadership''\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Norton|first=Augustus Richard|title=Amal and the Shi'a: Struggle for the Soul of Lebanon|publisher=University of Texas Press|year=1987|isbn=978-0292730403|location=Austin|pages=39}}</ref> Reportedly, one of the first directors of the institute was a [[Maronites|Maronite]], while its [[Iraq]]-born Shiite principal started military trainings for Shia youth with support from Palestinian fighers at the camp.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Chehabi|first=Houchang|url=https://www.academia.edu/8529108|title=Distant Relations: Iran and Lebanon in the Last 500 Years|publisher=I.B. Tauris|year=2006|isbn=|location=London|pages=192\u2013193}}</ref>\n\nBy 1968, there were 7,159 registered Palestinian refugees in the camp of Burj el-Seimali.<ref name=\":9\" /> At the same time, during the course of the decade, Greater Tyre metropolitan area, including Burj el-Shemali, increasingly became subject to a [[Urbanization|rural-to-urban movement]] that has been ongoing ever since and resulted in growing settlements around the camp.<ref name=\":4\" />[[File:Musa al-Sadr & Mostafa Chamran (2).jpg|thumb|Al-Sadr (centre, in black) with Mostafa Chamran, left|alt=]]\n\nThe [[solidarity]] of the Lebanese Tyrians with the Palestinians was especially demonstrated in January 1969 through a [[general strike]] to demand the repulsion of Israeli attacks on Palestinian targets in Beirut.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|last=Goria|first=Wade R.|title=Sovereignty and Leadership in Lebanon, 1943\u201376|publisher=Ithaca Press|year=1985|isbn=978-0863720314|location=London|pages=90, 179, 222}}</ref> However, this sentiment changed during the first half of the 1970s when the local population got increasingly caught up in the [[crossfire]] between the [[Palestinian insurgency in South Lebanon]] and [[Reprisal|reprisals]] from Israel's [[counter-insurgency]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gharbieh|first=Hussein M.|url=http://etheses.dur.ac.uk/1521/|title=Political awareness of the Shi'ites in Lebanon: the role of Sayyid 'Abd al-Husain Sharaf al-Din and Sayyid Musa al-Sadr|publisher=Centre for Middle Eastern and Islamic Studies, University of Durham|year=1996|isbn=|location=Durham|pages=|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, Sadr founded ''[[Amal Movement|Harakat al-Mahroumin]]'' (\"Movement of the Deprived\") and one year later \u2013 shortly before the beginning of the [[Lebanese Civil War]] \u2013 its ''de facto'' military wing: ''Afwaj al-Muqawama al-Lubnaniyya'' (Amal).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Deeb|first=Marius|date=1988|title=Shi'a Movements in Lebanon: their Formation, Ideology, Social Basis, and Links with Iran and Syria|url=|journal=Third World Quarterly|volume=10|issue=2|pages=685|doi=10.1080/01436598808420077}}</ref> The Iranian director of Sadr's technical school, [[Mostafa Chamran]], who was married to Amal activist [[Ghada Ja'bar]]<ref name=\":10\" />, became a major instructor of [[Guerrilla warfare|guerilla warfare]]. The US-trained [[physicist]] went on to become the first defense minister of [[History of the Islamic Republic of Iran|post-revolutionary Iran]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bonsen|first=Sabrina|title=Martyr Cults and Political Identities in Lebanon: \"Victory or Martyrdom\" in the Struggle of the Amal Movement|publisher=Springer Nature|year=2019|isbn=978-3-658-28098-7|location=Wiesbaden|pages=214, 248}}</ref> Military training and weaponry for Amal fighters was still mainly provided by Palestinian militants, but Sadr increasingly distanced himself from them as the situation escalated into a civil war:\n\n===== Lebanese Civil War (1975-1990) =====\nIn January 1975, a unit of the [[Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine]] (PFLP) attacked the Tyre barracks of the Lebanese Army.<ref name=\":10\" /> While the assault was denounced by the PLO as \"''a premeditated and reckless act''\"<ref name=\":12\" />, it launched in March a commando of its own eight to sail from the coast of Tyre to Tel Aviv to mount the [[Savoy Hotel attack]], during which eight civilian [[Hostage|Hostages]] and three Israeli soldiers were killed as well as seven of the eight attackers.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nisan|first=Mordechai|title=Politics and War in Lebanon: Unraveling the Enigma|publisher=Transaction Publishers|year=2015|isbn=978-1412856676|location=New Brunswick / London|pages=55}}</ref> Five months later Israel attacked Tyre \"''from land, sea and air''\" in a series of assaults over some weeks.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Odeh|first=B.J.|title=Lebanon: Dynamics of Conflict \u2013 A Modern Political History|publisher=Zed Books|year=1985|isbn=978-0862322120|location=London|pages=45, 141\u2013142, 144}}</ref> \n\nThen, in 1976, local commanders of the PLO took over the municipal government of Tyre with support from their allies of the [[Lebanese Arab Army]].<ref name=\":12\" /> They occupied the army barracks, set up roadblocks and started collecting customs at the port. However, the new rulers quickly lost support from the Lebanese-Tyrian population because of their \"''[[Arbitrariness|arbitrary]] and often brutal behavior''\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Schiff|first=Ze'ev|title=Israel's Lebanon War|last2=Ya'ari|first2=Ehud|publisher=Simon and Schuster|year=1985|isbn=978-0671602161|location=New York|pages=79\u201380, 139}}</ref>  Even Tyre's veteran politician [[Jafar Sharafeddin]], whose family has promoted freedom for the Palestinians over generations, was quoted as criticising the PLO for \"''its violations and [[sabotage]] of the Palestinian cause''\" during that time.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nAfter Sadr mysteriously disappeared following a visit to Libyan leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] on 31 August 1978, discontent within the Shiite population about the suffering from the conflict between Israel and the Palestinian factions grew, especially following the Israeli [[1978 South Lebanon conflict|Operation Litani]] in March of that year. Within this context, tensions between Amal and the Palestinian militants escalated into violent clashes in many villages of Southern Lebanon, including the Tyre area.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Abraham|first=Antoine J.|title=The Lebanon War|publisher=Praeger|year=1996|isbn=978-0275953898|location=Westport, Conn.|pages=123}}</ref> The heaviest such incident took place in April 1982, when the PLO ([[Fatah|Fateh]]) bombarded Amal's Technical Institute in Burj El Shimali for ten hours.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite journal|last=Siklawi|first=Rami|date=Winter 2012|title=The Dynamics of the Amal Movement in Lebanon 1975\u201390|url=|journal=Arab Studies Quarterly|volume=34|issue=1|pages=4\u201326|jstor=41858677}}</ref>\n\n====== 1982 Israeli invasion ======\n\nFollowing the [[1982 Lebanon War|1982 Israeli Invasion]], the Palestinian refugee camp in Burj el-Shemali \u2013 according to UNRWA \u2013 \"''was badly damaged''\".<ref name=\":2\" /> An international commission to enquire into reported violations of [[international law]] by Israel during its invasion found that Israeli forces had destroyed 35 percent of the houses in the camp.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kaufman|first=Asher|url=https://www.academia.edu/5561720|title=Forgetting the Lebanon War? On Silence, Denial and Selective Remembrance of the First Lebanon War|publisher=Cambrige University Press|year=2010|isbn=978-0521196581|editor-last=Ben-Ze\u2019ev|editor-first=Efrat|location=Cambridge|pages=205|format=PDF|editor-last2=Ginio|editor-first2=Ruth|editor-last3=Winter|editor-first3=Jay}}</ref> Much of the destruction was done ''\"systematically''\" by the [[Israel Defense Forces]] (IDF) after the actual combat with Palestinian fighters had stopped.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gilmour|first=David|title=Lebanon: The Fractured Country|publisher=Martin Robertson|year=1983|isbn=978-0312477394|location=Oxford|pages=178\u2013179}}</ref> At the same time, the IDF set up a large compound right next to the Amal technical training center founded by Musa Sadr:<blockquote>\"''The centre doubled as office of the Amal leader in South Lebanon, [[Dawud Sulayman Dawud]], nicknamed 'David David' because of his alleged readiness to negotiate with Israel. He was a native of [[Tarbikha]], one of the five Shi'ite villages in northern Galilee, which were depoluated in October/November 1948, and his Lebanese opponents often called him a Palestinian. Dawud and other Amal leaders did not avoid discreet contacts with Israelis, but refused open clientship. The IDF soon lost patience and arrested thirteen Amal leaders as early as the summer of 1982.''\"<ref name=\":10\" /></blockquote>The situation soon escalated further: On 11 November 1982, a [[Suicide attack|suicide-attack]] with an [[Car bomb|explosive-laden car]] destroyed the Israeli military and intelligence headquarters in Tyre. As many as ninety soldiers, officers, and spies were killed as well as an unknown number of Lebanese and Palestinians [[Detention (imprisonment)|detainees]].<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite book|last=Hamzeh|first=Ahmad Nizar|title=In the Path of Hizbullah|publisher=Syracuse University Press|year=2004|isbn=978-0815630531|location=New York|pages=11, 82, 130, 133}}</ref> As initially nobody claimed responsibility for the assault, Amal came under suspicion as well. In May 1983, the IDF searched the training center and reportedly opened fire on a group of pupils in the schoolyard, killing one boy and wounding nine. Dawud called for mourning strike and threatened resistance.<ref name=\":10\" /> \n\nThen, in November 1983, another suicide-attack on the new Israeli headquarters in Tyre killed 29 Israeli soldiers and officers, wounding another thirty.<ref name=\":14\" /> 32 Lebanese and Palestinians died as well, most of them detainees. Only in 1985 was responsibility assumed for both attacks by an organisation that would go on to become a major player: [[Hezbollah]].<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n====== 1985 Amal takeover ======\n\nMeanwhile, in February 1985, an Amal member from Tyre launched a [[Suicide attack|suicide-attack]] on an IDF convoy in Burj El Shimali<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bonsen|first=Sabrina|title=Martyr Cults and Political Identities in Lebanon: \"Victory or Martyrdom\" in the Struggle of the Amal Movement|publisher=Springer Nature|year=2019|isbn=978-3-658-28098-7|location=Wiesbaden|pages=214, 248}}</ref>, injuring ten soldiers. \"''Israeli reprisals in the area east of Tyre killed fifteen and wounded dozens''.\" The IDF particularly retaliated against Amal's technical training center and Southern Headquarters in Burj el-Shemali, \"''igniting a new circle of violence.''\" Under the growing pressure the Israeli forces withdrew from Greater Tyre area by the end of April 1985 and Amal took over power there: <blockquote>\"''The priority of Amal remained to prevent the return of any armed Palestinian presence to the South, primarily because this might provoke renewed Israeli intervention in recently evacuated areas. The approximately 60,000 Palestinian refugees in the camps around Tyre (al-Bass, Rashidiya, Burj al-Shimali) were cut off from the outside world, although Amal never succeeded in fully controlling the camps themselves. In the Sunni 'canton' of Sidon, the armed PLO returned in force.''\"<ref name=\":10\" /></blockquote>It is not known how much the refugee camp in Burj el-Shemali and the surrounding areas were affected, when tensions between Amal and Palestinian militants escalated again and eventually exploded by September 1986 into \"''the war of the camps''\", which is considered as \"''one of the most brutal episodes in a brutal civil war''\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hudson|first=Michael C.|date=1997|title=Palestinians and Lebanon: The Common Story|url=https://mideast-africa.tau.ac.il/sites/humanities.tau.ac.il/files/media_server/mideast_africa/%D7%9C%D7%91%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%9F/%D7%93%D7%99%D7%9C%D7%9E%D7%95%D7%AA%20%D7%9E%D7%95%D7%91%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%AA%20%D7%91%D7%9E%D7%A2%D7%A8%D7%9B%D7%AA%20%D7%94%D7%9C%D7%91%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%99%D7%AA5pdf.pdf|journal=Journal of Refugee Studies|volume=10|issue=3|pages=243\u2013260|doi=10.1093/jrs/10.3.243|via=}}</ref> Clearly, it was once more the population of Rashidieh that bore the brunt of killing and destruction, when a group of Palestinians fired on an Amal patrol there. After one month of siege, Amal attacked the refugee camp in the South of Tyre<ref name=\":13\" />, reportedly assisted by its allies from the [[Progressive Socialist Party]], [[As-Sa'iqa|As-Saiqa]] and \"[[Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine \u2013 General Command]]\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Arsan|first=Andrew|title=Lebanon: A Country in Fragments|publisher=C Hurst & Co Publishers Ltd|year=2018|isbn=978-1849047005|location=London|pages=266}}</ref> Fighting spread and continued for one month. By that time some 7,000 refugees in the Tyre area were displaced once more.<ref name=\":13\" /> It may be assumed that Burj el-Shemali was less affected, since many of its residents were Shiites.<ref name=\":8\" /> However, there was at least one very prominent casualty from Burj el-Shemali: Amal's leader for Southern Lebanon Dawud Dawud, who was killed in renewed clashed between Amal and Hezbollah in 1988.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n===== Post-Civil War (since 1991) =====\nAfter the end of Lebanon's devastating civil war through the [[Taif Agreement]] in 1990, units of the Lebanese Army deployed along the coastal highway and around the Palestinian refugee camps of Tyre, including Burj el-Shemali.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Barak|first=Oren|title=The Lebanese Army: A National Institution in a Divided Society|publisher=State University of New York Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0-7914-9345-8|location=Albany|pages=67, 180}}</ref> Nevertheless, the camp saw an informal building boom in the course of the decade, as Palestinians living abroad invested money to improve their family houses or to build their own retirement homes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sheikh|first=Hassan Ismae\u2019l|date=May-June 2009|title=An Urbanity of Exile: Palestinian Refugee Camps|url=|journal=A10: New European Architecture|volume=27|pages=60-62|via=}}</ref>\n\nin 1994 many residents of the camp in Burj el-Shemali seem to have benefited from an exceptional process of [[Naturalization|naturalisation]]: while Lebanese [[citizenship]] - along with many [[Fundamental rights|basic rights]] - has generally been denied to Palestinian refugees, the government in Beirut now granted passports to refugees and their descendants from the seven predominantly [[Shia villages in Palestine|Shia Villages in Palestine]]. They had been given citizenship of [[Greater Lebanon]] by [[French colonial empire|France]] in 1921, but were attached to [[British Empire|British]] [[Mandatory Palestine]] two years later by the [[Paulet-Newcombe Agreement|Paulet-Newcombe commission]]. In the 1948 Nakba, many fled to the greater Tyre area, where they apparently settled in Burj el Shemali camp as well.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\n====== 2006 War between Israel and Hezbollah ======\nDuring Israel's invasion in the [[2006 Lebanon War]], Burj El Shimali was severely hit again: \n\n- on July 9th, the Plastimed and Plastic Medical Component Factories were struck in an assault by the [[Israeli Air Force]] (IAF);\n\n\u2013 on July 16th, five civilians were killed by in another IAF attack on a former soap factory, including two children;\n\n\u2013 on August 13th, another five civilians were killed by an IAF missile, amongst them three children and one [[Sri Lanka|Sri Lankan]] maid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2007/09/05/why-they-died/civilian-casualties-lebanon-during-2006-war|title=Why They Died: Civilian Casualties in Lebanon during the 2006 War\"|last=|first=|date=5 September 2007|website=Human Rights Watch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====== Post-2006 War ======\nAccording to a 2014 study paper, the majority of Palestinian refugees in Burj el-Shemali supported Fatah. However, it noted that there was \u2013 unlike in the other Tyrian camp of [[Rashidieh]] \u2013 also a considerable presence of [[Hamas]]. In addition, the [[Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine]] (PFLP), the [[Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine]] (DFLP), and the [[Islamic Jihad Movement in Palestine]] were represented in the Popular Committees that rule the camp.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rosalux.de/fileadmin/rls_uploads/pdfs/Studien/Studien_Flucht_Vertreibung.pdf|title=Flucht und Vertreibung im Syrien-Konflikt \u2013 Eine Analyse zur Situation von Fl\u00fcchtlingen in Syrien und im Libanon|last=|first=|date=July 2014|website=Rosa-Luxemburg-Stiftung|pages=28|language=German|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 2016, the mayor of Burj el-Shemali was [[Hajj Ali Dib]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/UN-Habitat_2017.05.22_CP_Tyre_web.pdf|title=TYRE CITY PROFILE|last=Maguire|first=Suzanne|last2=Majzoub|first2=Maya|date=2016|editor-last=Osseiran|editor-first=Tarek|website=reliefweb|publisher=UN HABITAT Lebanon|pages=13\u201318; 26|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n== Demographics ==\n\n=== Lebanese part of the town ===\nThere are no official figures for the Lebanese and Non-Lebanese population in the Lebanese-ruled part of Burj el-Shemali. \n\n=== Palestinian Refugee Camp ===\n[[File:Mansell-camp-code-18-1024x1024.jpg|thumb|Balloon mapping of the camp during a 2015 project of the NGO Greening Bourj Al Shamali, photo by Claudia Martinez Mansell]]\nBy 1982 the number of registered refugees in the camp had gone up to 11,256 from 7,159 in 1968.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|last=Brynen|first=Rex|title=Sanctuary And Survival: The PLO In Lebanon|publisher=Westview Press|year=1990|isbn=978-0813379197|location=Boulder|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the camp had 19,074 registered [[refugees]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/unrwa/refugees/lebanon.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-04-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409202113/http://www.un.org/unrwa/refugees/lebanon.html |archivedate=2008-04-09 }}</ref> As of June 2018, this number had grown to 24,929. This increase is mainly attributable to the arrival of many [[Syrian people|Syrian]] refugees and \u2013 especially \u2013 Palestinian refugees from Syria (PRS) after the beginning of the [[Syrian civil war]] in 2011.<ref name=\":2\" /> The already overcrowded living conditions have further deteriorated with the plight these twice-over refugees.<ref name=\":7\" /> UNRWA describes the situation as follows:<blockquote>\"''There is a very high incidence of [[thalassemia]] and [[sickle cell disease]] ([[genetic disorder]]) among Burj Shemali inhabitants and the camp is one of the poorest camps in Lebanon. [[Unemployment]] is extremely high, with seasonal agricultural work the most common source of income for both men and women.''\"<ref name=\":2\" /></blockquote>However, the second, third and fourth generation refugees have lost the [[Subsistence agriculture|subsistence agricultural]] existences of their ancestors from Palestine due to the very limited space and denial of land-ownership.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nForeigners need a permit from the [[military intelligence]] to enter the camp:<blockquote>\"''The permit system deters curious strangers and helps authorities monitor the population. It also makes the camp feel like an open-air [[prison]].''\"<ref name=\":5\" /></blockquote>In contrast to such clear-cut borders, other boundaries are much more blurred and fluid:\n\nIn 2017 at least, one [[Naturalization|naturalised]] Palestinian in Burj el Shemali camp was a member of the municipal council<ref>{{Cite book|last=Stel|first=Nora|url=https://www.academia.edu/31538902|title=Governing the Gatherings \u2013 The Interaction of Lebanese State Institutions and Palestinian Authorities in the Hybrid Political Order of South Lebanon's Informal Palestinian Settlements|publisher=|year=2017|isbn=|location=Utrecht|pages=217|format=PDF}}</ref>, as he probably originated from one of the seven predominantly Shi'ite villages in Palestine (see above).<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite journal|last=NISHIKIDA|first=Aiko|date=July 2009|title=Palestinians from the \"Seven Villages\":Their Legal Status and Social Condition|url=https://www.asafas.kyoto-u.ac.jp/kias/1st_period/contents/pdf/kb3_1/15nishikida.pdf|journal=Kyoto Bulletin of Islamic Area Studies|volume=3-1|pages=220\u2013231|via=}}</ref> A 1998 fact-finding mission of the [[Danish Immigration Service]] even was told by various sources that many residents at Burj el Shemali camp were Shiites and had been granted Lebanese nationality in 1994.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyidanmark.dk/-/media/Files/US/Landerapporter/Factfindingmission_Lebanon_1998.pdf?la=en-GB&hash=E4C43FEDE9F92ED581945E636DD2B84B01FEB97E|title=Report on fact-finding mission to Lebanon 2 \u2013 18 May 1998|last=|first=|date=1 June 1998|website=newtodenmark.dk|publisher=The Danish Immigration Service|page=57|format=PDF|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> However, a lot of them seem to have moved out of the camp since then. Their number reportedly went down in the following years to just \"''a few''\" Shiite families and only one Christian family still living in the camp by 2016.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nRemarkably, one neighborhood inside the camp is known as [[Morocco]], referring to the North African origin of the residents, whose ancestors moved to historic Palestine during the Ottoman Empire.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Gallery ==\n\n=== Exhibits at the National Museum of Beirut ===\n\n==== Funerary items ====\n<gallery>\nFile:BurjAlShimali LimestoneStele 5-4cBCE NationalMuseumOfBeirut RomanDeckert03102019.jpg|[[Limestone]] [[stele]], 5th to 4th century BCE\nFile:BurjAlShimali Relief IronAge-III NationalMuseumOfBeirut RomanDeckert03102019.jpg|Relief depicting a deceased person with a sheathed body, 550-333 BCE\nFile:BurjAlShemali RomanTombWithFrescoes NationalMuseumOfBeirut RomanDeckert03102019.jpg|Roman tomb with frescoes from the 2nd century CE\n</gallery>\n\n==== Mask of a Satyr ====\n<gallery>\nFile:RomanTerracottaMaskOfSatyr-BurjElShemali NationalMuseumOfBeirut RomanDeckert 06102019.jpg\nFile:RomanTerracottaMaskOfSatyr BurjElShemali NationalMuseumOfBeirut RomanDeckert06102019.jpg\nFile:RomanTerracottaMask Satyr BurjAlShimali NationalMuseumOfBeirut RomanDeckert06102019.jpg\nFile:RomanTerracottaMaskOfSatyr-BurjElShemali NationalMuseumOfBeirut RomanDeckert06102019.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n=== Crusader tower ===\n<gallery>\nFile:BurjAlShimali-TowerSide Lebanon-23092019RomanDeckert.jpg\nFile:BurjAlShimaliTowerLebanon 23092019RomanDeckert.jpg\nFile:BurjAlShimali-TowerInside Lebanon-23092019RomanDeckert.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.unrwa.org/where-we-work/lebanon/burj-shemali-camp Burj Shemali Camp],  from [[UNWRA]]\n\n{{Palestinian refugee camps}}\n{{Tyre District}}\n[[Category:Palestinian refugee camps in Lebanon]]\n\n\n{{Palestine-stub}}\n{{Lebanon-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{pp-30-500|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Burj El Shimali\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Governorates of Lebanon|Governorate]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Tyre District]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{Flag|Lebanon}}\n| subdivision_name1               = [[South Governorate]]\n| native_name_lang                = ar\n| subdivision_type2               = [[Districts of Lebanon|District]]\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| official_name                   = \n| pushpin_map                     = Lebanon\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|33|15|47|N|35|14|20|E|display=inline,title}}\n| image_map                       = \n| image_skyline                   = BurjAlShimali-Tower 23092019RomanDeckert.jpg\n| settlement_type                 = Town\n| native_name                     = {{lang|ar| \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0631\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0645\u0627\u0644\u064a}}\n| image_caption                   = The Burj \u2013 \"Tower\" \u2013 of Burj El Shimali\n| area_total_ha                   = 1069\n| elevation_m                     = 62\n}}\n{{Other uses|Burj (disambiguation){{!}}Burj}}\n'''Burj el-Shemali''' (Arabic: \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0631\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0645\u0627\u0644\u064a) is a [[Municipality|municpality]] located some 86 km south of Beirut and 3 km east of the [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]]/Sour peninsula, merging into its urban area. It is part of the [[Tyre Union of Municipalities]] within the [[Tyre District]] of the [[South Governorate]] of [[Lebanon]].  \n\nIt is particularly known for hosting the second-largest of the twelve [[Palestinian refugee camps]] in the country as a ''[[de facto]]'' [[Autonomy|autonomous]] [[Enclave and exclave|exclave]] effectively out of the reach of Lebanese officials: The camp is ruled by Popular Committees of Palestinian parties under the leadership of the [[Palestine Liberation Organization|Palestinian Liberation Organisation]] (PLO) which is de facto recognised by the municipality through some degree of coordination and cooperation.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Suleiman|first=Jaber|url=https://www.academia.edu/37289610|title=Lebanese- Palestinian Relations: Apolitical, Human Rights, and Security Perspective|journal=Policy Dialogue Series: Lebanese- Palestinian Relations|publisher=Common Space Initiative for Shared Knowledge and Consensus Building|year=2017|location=Beirut|pages=27|format=PDF}}</ref> The [[UNRWA|United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East]] (UNRWA) has the mandate to provide basic services, assisted by local and international NGOs. The [[Lebanese Armed Forces]] control entry and exit through the camp's main gate.<ref name=\":3\" />  \n\n== Name ==\nBurj el-Shemali \u2013 also transliterated into the spellings of \"Borj\" or \"Bourj\" combined with a version of \"Shimali\", \"Shamali\", ''\"''Shem\u00e2ly''\",'' \"Chemali\", \"Chamali\", or \"Chmali\" with or without the article \"el\", \"al\", \"esh\", or \"ash\" \u2013  is commonly translated as \"Northern Tower\", as done by [[Edward Henry Palmer|E. H. Palmer]] in the 1881 [[PEF Survey of Palestine|''Survey of Western Palestine'' (SWP)]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Palmer|first=E.H.|url=https://archive.org/details/surveyofwesternp00conduoft|title=The Survey of Western Palestine: Arabic and English Name Lists Collected During the Survey by Lieutenants Conder and Kitchener, R. E. Transliterated and Explained by E.H. Palmer.|publisher=Committee of the [[Palestine Exploration Fund]]|year=1881|isbn=|location=London|pages=4}}</ref>\n\nThe settlement is named after a medieval tower on its main hill that overlooks Tyre.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Badawi|first=Ali Khalil|title=TYRE|publisher=Al-Athar Magazine|year=2018|isbn=|edition=4th|location=Beirut|pages=5, 7, 30, 136\u2013137}}</ref> The Arabic word \"Burj\" reportedly originated from the [[Ancient Greek]] \"pyrgos\".<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/4847281|title=Arabic Etymological Dictionary|last=Rajki|first=Andras|date=2005|website=Academia.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Territory ==\nBurj el-Shemali reportedly covers an area of 1.069 [[hectare]], rising to an [[elevation]] of more than 60 metres on a hill overlooking Tyre/Sour [[peninsula]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.localiban.org/borj-ech-chemali-3539|title=Borj Ech Chemali|last=Tohm\u00e9|first=Joseph|last2=Aouad|first2=Michel|date=23 October 2015|website=localiban|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nTogether with the built-up areas of three adjacent municipalities \u2013 Sour on the peninsula and the coastal areas to the West, [[Abbasiyet Sour]] to the North, and [[Ain Baal]] to the South-East \u2013 the urban part of Burj el-Shemali has integrated into one greater metropolitan Tyre. There are also unpopulated [[Agricultural land|agricultural lands]], especially in its Northern and Southern parts.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nMost reports about the size of the Palestinian camp give a fgure of about 135,000 square meters<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|url=https://placesjournal.org/article/camp-code/?cn-reloaded=1|title=Camp Code \u2013 How to navigate a refugee settlement|last=Martinez Mansell|first=Claudia|date=April 2016|journal=Places Journal|doi=10.22269/160405|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":8\" />, which means that it covers just a tiny fraction of the municipality's overall territory.<ref name=\":4\" /> It is less dense than other refugee camps in Lebanon<ref name=\":5\" />, but still one of the [[Population density|world's most densely populated areas]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Viaro|first=Alain|url=https://www.academia.edu/24548140|title=Assessment of Housing Conditions of Palestine Refugees|last2=Rueff|first2=Henri|publisher=UNRWA \u2013 Near East Project|year=2007|isbn=|location=|pages=18, 22|format=PDF}}</ref> The land is reportedly \"''rented by the Lebanese government for 99 years.''\"<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Ancient Times ===\n[[File:RomanTerracottaMaskOfSatyr-BurjAlShimali NationalMuseumOfBeirut RomanDeckert06102019.jpg|thumb|Mask of a [[Satyr]] from Burj el-Shemali, Roman period, on display at the [[National Museum of Beirut]]]]\nAccording to [[Ali Khalil Badawi|Ali Badawi]], the long-time chief-archaeologist for Southern Lebanon at the Directorate-General of Antiquities, it can be generally assumed that all villages around Tyre were established already during [[Prehistory|prehistoric times]] like the [[Neolithic|neolithic age]] (5.000 BCE).<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n[[Phoenicia|Phoenician]] [[Stele|stelas]] and other artefacts found in Burj el-Shemali give evidence that the place was used in the 5th to 4th century BCE for funerary purposes.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=A visit to the Museum... The short guide of the National Museum of Beirut, Lebanon|publisher=Ministry of Culture/Directorate General of Antiquities|year=2008|isbn=978-9953-0-0038-1|location=Beirut|pages=39}}</ref> If there were settlements during that time, they were probably demolished by the army of [[Alexander the Great]], who had all the coastal villages destroyed and the building materials used to connect the island of Tyre with a mole during the siege of 332 BCE.<ref name=\":1\" /> There are indications though of settlements at Burj el-Shemali dating back at least to the first century BCE.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Tyr \u2013 L'histoire d'une Ville|last=Badawi|first=Ali Khalil|publisher=Municipalit\u00e9 de Tyr / Tyre Municipality / Baladia Sour|year=2008|isbn=|location=Tyre/Sour/Tyr|pages=124|language=French}}</ref> \n\nDuring [[Roman Empire|Roman]] times, parts of Burj el-Shemali continued to be used as a [[necropolis]]. A number of its [[Hypogeum|hypogea]] - underground tombs - with [[Roman Empire|Roman]]-era [[Fresco|frescos]] are on display at the [[National Museum of Beirut|National Museum]] in [[Beirut]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The remains of a [[Byzantine Empire|Roman-Byzantine]] road are preserved underneath the modern main road.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n=== Medieval Times ===\nIt is not clear whether Burj el-Shemali continued to be settled and/or used as a fuenrary place after the Arab armies defeated the Byzantine empire in the region and took over Tyre in 635 CE for half a millenium of Islamic rule.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nWhen the Tyre was taken over by a [[Francia|Frankish]] army in the aftermath of the [[First Crusade]], the new rulers constructed a fortified tower on the hill of Burj el-Shemali overlooking the [[peninsula]] of Tyre. The village then adapted its name from that tower. There are also remains of another Crusader tower known as Al-Burj Al-Qobli in the Southern part of town. Like in acient times, the lands of Burj el-Shemali were used as cemeteries in medieval periods.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Ottoman Times ===\n[[File:BurjAlShimali-Tower-view-on-Tyre 23092019RomanDeckert.jpg|thumb|View from the Burj over Tyre]]\nAlthough the [[Ottoman Empire]] conquered the [[Levant]] in 1516, [[Jabal Amel]] (modern-day [[Southern Lebanon]]) remained mostly untouched for almost another century. When the Ottoman leadership at the [[Sublime Porte]] appointed the [[Druze]] leader [[Fakhr-al-Din II|Fakhreddine II]] of the Maan family to administer the area at the beginning of the 17th century, the [[Emir]] encouraged many [[Lebanese Shia Muslims|Metwali]] \u2013 the discriminated [[Shia Islam|Shia]] Muslims of what is now Lebanon \u2013 to settle to the East of Tyre to secure the road to [[Damascus]]. He thus also laid the foundation of the Lebanese part of modern Burj el-Shemali [[Demography|demographics]] as a predominantly Shiite place.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=Smit|first=Ferdinand|url=https://www.academia.edu/12778980|title=The battle for South Lebanon: Radicalisation of Lebanon's Shi'ites 1982\u20131985|publisher=Bulaaq, Uitgeverij|year=2006|isbn=978-9054600589|location=Amsterdam|pages=36, 90, 134, 150, 157, 220, 232, 269, 295|format=PDF}}</ref> \n\nIn 1881, the [[London]]-based [[Palestine Exploration Fund]]'s [[PEF Survey of Palestine|''Survey of Western Palestine'' (SWP)]] described it as <blockquote>\"''A large village built of stone, containing about 300 Metawileh, placed on a low [[ridge]], with [[Ficus|figs]], [[Olive|olives]], and [[arable land]] around. There are two good [[Spring (hydrology)|springs]] near.''\"</blockquote>and further noted that it was <blockquote>\"''a village with a similar tower of drafted [[masonry]] (as that of [[Borj Rahal]]). The hill is crowned by a stronghold, the vaults of which, slightly ogival, do not appear older than the Crusaders, but it was constructed of older blocks, some in drafted masonry and others completely smoothed. About a mile to the south-west of this hill is a subterranean series of tombs, each containing several ranges of [[Loculus (architecture)|loculi]], which was explored by [[Ernest Renan|Renan]].''\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Conder|first=Claude Reignier|url=https://ia600207.us.archive.org/21/items/surveyofwesternp01conduoft/surveyofwesternp01conduoft.pdf|title=The Survey of Western Palestine: Memoirs of the Topography, Orography, Hydrography, and Archaeology|last2=Kitchener|first2=Horatio Herbert|publisher=Committee of the Palestine Exploration Fund|year=1881|isbn=|volume=1|location=London|pages=48, 58|author-link=Claude Reignier Conder|author-link2=Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Modern Times ===\n==== Post-Independence (since 1943) ====\n{{Multiple image\n| align = \n| direction = vertical\n| total_width = \n| image1 = Palestinian refugees.jpg\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Refugees in Galilee.jpg\n| caption2 = \n| footer = Palestinian refugees making their way from [[Galilee]] to Lebanon in October\u2013November 1948\n}}[[File:Mount Canaan iv.jpg|left|thumb|View of Safed from Mount Canaan, taken in April or May 1948 during [[Operation Yiftach]]]]\nFollowing Lebanese independence from France on 22 November 1943, Southern Lebanon enjoyed less than five years of peace. The border with British-ruled [[Mandatory Palestine]] was still open during those times, and many [[Palestinian Jews|Palestianian Jews]] used to spend holidays in Tyre, while vice versa many Southern Lebanese would travel freely to [[Haifa]] and [[Tel Aviv]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hirst|first=David|title=Beware of Small States: Lebanon, Battleground of the Middle East.|publisher=Faber and Faber|year=2010|isbn=9780571237418|location=London|pages=30\u201331, 42}}</ref>\n\nHowever, when the state of [[Israel]] was declared in May 1948, an estimated 127,000 Palestinians fled to Lebanon alone until the end of that year.<ref name=\":10\" /> Confronted with this exodus \u2013 also known as the '''[[1948 Palestinian exodus|Nakba]]''' \u2013 a camp of tents was set up in Burj El Shimali, reportedly by the [[International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies|League of Red Cross Societies]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Sfeir|first=Jihane|url=https://www.academia.edu/10925357|title=L'exil Palestinien au Liban. 1947\u20131951|publisher=IFPO/Karthala/|year=2008|isbn=|location=Paris, Beirut|pages=65, 275|language=French}}</ref> The refugees were mainly from [[Hawla]], [[Lubya|Lubieh]], [[Sepphoris|Saffuri]], [[Tiberias]]<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.unrwa.org/where-we-work/lebanon/burj-shemali-camp|title=Burj Shemali Camp|last=|first=|date=|website=United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East (UNRWA)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 September 2019}}</ref>, and [[Safed]], where they mostly led agricultural existences.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|last=Martinez Mansell|first=Claudia|url=https://www.academia.edu/41442938|title=A View from Above \u2013 Balloon Mapping Bourj Al Shamali|last2=Dakhloul|first2=Mustapha|last3=Ismail|first3=Firas|work=This Is Not an Atlas \u2013 A Global Collection of Counter-Cartographies|publisher=transcript Verlag|year=2018|isbn=978-3-8394-4519-8|editor-last=Halder|editor-first=Severin|location=Bielefeld|pages=54\u201356}}</ref> Residents suffered from miserable conditions as the camp was initially only meant to be temporary and to serve as a transit point from which the refugees were relocated to camps in [[Sidon]] and [[Bekaa]].<ref name=\":6\" /> \n\nMany of them seem to have moved back to Burj el-Shemali once the current \"''footprint''\" was established in 1955.<ref name=\":5\" /> At that time UNRWA started providing humanitarian assistance \u2013 infrastructure services ([[water]], [[sewage]], [[electricity]], [[Road|road networks]] and shelter), [[school]] [[education]] and [[health care]] \u2013 to the residents of the camp.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/unrwa/refugees/lebanon/shemali.html|title=Archived copy|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090421060238/http://www.un.org/unrwa/refugees/lebanon/shemali.html|archivedate=2009-04-21|accessdate=2009-03-29}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, more Palestinian refugees settled in the area of [[Maachouk]] \u2013 1 km to the West of Burj El Shemali \u2013  on agricultural lands owned by the Lebanese State as a neighbourhood rather than a camp. Its eastern side, which is an [[Industry|industrial]] zone, as well as the main road's southern side with many [[Commerce|commercial]] activities fall within the jurisdiction of Burj el-Shemali municipality which demonstrates the [[arbitrariness]] of many boundaries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/UN-Habitat_2017.05.04_NPS_Maachouk.pdf|title=Maachouk Neighbourhood Profile & Strategy, Tyre, Lebanon|last=Harake|first=Dani|last2=Kuwalti|first2=Riham|date=31 May 2017|website=reliefweb|publisher=UN HABITAT Lebanon|pages=2\u20133, 25\u201326|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Tyrian public expressed [[solidarity]] with the [[Palestinian nationalism|Palestinian cause]] in that early post-independence era, especially thanks to the politics of Tyre's long-time Imam and social-reformer [[Abd al-Husayn Sharaf al-Din al-Musawi|Abdulhussein Sharafeddin]], who had given shelter to the [[Grand Mufti of Jerusalem]] [[Amin al-Husseini]] shortly after the beginning of the [[1936\u20131939 Arab revolt in Palestine]].<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite book|last=Abisaab|first=Rula Jurdi|title=The Shi'ites of Lebanon: Modernism, Communism, and Hizbullah's Islamists|last2=Abisaab|first2=Malek|publisher=Syracuse University Press|year=2017|isbn=9780815635093|location=New York|pages=9\u201311, 16\u201317, 24, 107}}</ref> After Sharafeddin's death in 1957 the balance of power in Southern Lebanon and the whole country gradually started to shift though with the arrival of a newcomer to the political scene:\n\nIn 1959, the [[Iran]]-born Shiite cleric [[Sayyid|Sayed]] [[Musa al-Sadr|Musa Sadr]] moved to Tyre to succeed the late Sharafeddin. As \"''one of his first significant acts''\" he established a [[Vocational education|vocational training]] center in Burj el-Shemali that became \"''an important symbol of his leadership''\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Norton|first=Augustus Richard|title=Amal and the Shi'a: Struggle for the Soul of Lebanon|publisher=University of Texas Press|year=1987|isbn=978-0292730403|location=Austin|pages=39}}</ref> Reportedly, one of the first directors of the institute was a [[Maronites|Maronite]], while its [[Iraq]]-born Shiite principal started military trainings for Shia youth with support from Palestinian fighers at the camp.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Chehabi|first=Houchang|url=https://www.academia.edu/8529108|title=Distant Relations: Iran and Lebanon in the Last 500 Years|publisher=I.B. Tauris|year=2006|isbn=|location=London|pages=192\u2013193}}</ref>\n\nBy 1968, there were 7,159 registered Palestinian refugees in the camp of Burj el-Seimali.<ref name=\":9\" /> At the same time, during the course of the decade, Greater Tyre metropolitan area, including Burj el-Shemali, increasingly became subject to a [[Urbanization|rural-to-urban movement]] that has been ongoing ever since and resulted in growing settlements around the camp.<ref name=\":4\" />[[File:Musa al-Sadr & Mostafa Chamran (2).jpg|thumb|Al-Sadr (centre, in black) with Mostafa Chamran, left|alt=]]\n\nThe [[solidarity]] of the Lebanese Tyrians with the Palestinians was especially demonstrated in January 1969 through a [[general strike]] to demand the repulsion of Israeli attacks on Palestinian targets in Beirut.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|last=Goria|first=Wade R.|title=Sovereignty and Leadership in Lebanon, 1943\u201376|publisher=Ithaca Press|year=1985|isbn=978-0863720314|location=London|pages=90, 179, 222}}</ref> However, this sentiment changed during the first half of the 1970s when the local population got increasingly caught up in the [[crossfire]] between the [[Palestinian insurgency in South Lebanon]] and [[Reprisal|reprisals]] from Israel's [[counter-insurgency]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gharbieh|first=Hussein M.|url=http://etheses.dur.ac.uk/1521/|title=Political awareness of the Shi'ites in Lebanon: the role of Sayyid 'Abd al-Husain Sharaf al-Din and Sayyid Musa al-Sadr|publisher=Centre for Middle Eastern and Islamic Studies, University of Durham|year=1996|isbn=|location=Durham|pages=|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, Sadr founded ''[[Amal Movement|Harakat al-Mahroumin]]'' (\"Movement of the Deprived\") and one year later \u2013 shortly before the beginning of the [[Lebanese Civil War]] \u2013 its ''de facto'' military wing: ''Afwaj al-Muqawama al-Lubnaniyya'' (Amal).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Deeb|first=Marius|date=1988|title=Shi'a Movements in Lebanon: their Formation, Ideology, Social Basis, and Links with Iran and Syria|url=|journal=Third World Quarterly|volume=10|issue=2|pages=685|doi=10.1080/01436598808420077}}</ref> The Iranian director of Sadr's technical school, [[Mostafa Chamran]], who was married to Amal activist [[Ghada Ja'bar]]<ref name=\":10\" />, became a major instructor of [[Guerrilla warfare|guerilla warfare]]. The US-trained [[physicist]] went on to become the first defense minister of [[History of the Islamic Republic of Iran|post-revolutionary Iran]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bonsen|first=Sabrina|title=Martyr Cults and Political Identities in Lebanon: \"Victory or Martyrdom\" in the Struggle of the Amal Movement|publisher=Springer Nature|year=2019|isbn=978-3-658-28098-7|location=Wiesbaden|pages=214, 248}}</ref> Military training and weaponry for Amal fighters was still mainly provided by Palestinian militants, but Sadr increasingly distanced himself from them as the situation escalated into a civil war:\n\n===== Lebanese Civil War (1975-1990) =====\nIn January 1975, a unit of the [[Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine]] (PFLP) attacked the Tyre barracks of the Lebanese Army.<ref name=\":10\" /> While the assault was denounced by the PLO as \"''a premeditated and reckless act''\"<ref name=\":12\" />, it launched in March a commando of its own eight to sail from the coast of Tyre to Tel Aviv to mount the [[Savoy Hotel attack]], during which eight civilian [[Hostage|Hostages]] and three Israeli soldiers were killed as well as seven of the eight attackers.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nisan|first=Mordechai|title=Politics and War in Lebanon: Unraveling the Enigma|publisher=Transaction Publishers|year=2015|isbn=978-1412856676|location=New Brunswick / London|pages=55}}</ref> Five months later Israel attacked Tyre \"''from land, sea and air''\" in a series of assaults over some weeks.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Odeh|first=B.J.|title=Lebanon: Dynamics of Conflict \u2013 A Modern Political History|publisher=Zed Books|year=1985|isbn=978-0862322120|location=London|pages=45, 141\u2013142, 144}}</ref> \n\nThen, in 1976, local commanders of the PLO took over the municipal government of Tyre with support from their allies of the [[Lebanese Arab Army]].<ref name=\":12\" /> They occupied the army barracks, set up roadblocks and started collecting customs at the port. However, the new rulers quickly lost support from the Lebanese-Tyrian population because of their \"''[[Arbitrariness|arbitrary]] and often brutal behavior''\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Schiff|first=Ze'ev|title=Israel's Lebanon War|last2=Ya'ari|first2=Ehud|publisher=Simon and Schuster|year=1985|isbn=978-0671602161|location=New York|pages=79\u201380, 139}}</ref>  Even Tyre's veteran politician [[Jafar Sharafeddin]], whose family has promoted freedom for the Palestinians over generations, was quoted as criticising the PLO for \"''its violations and [[sabotage]] of the Palestinian cause''\" during that time.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nAfter Sadr mysteriously disappeared following a visit to Libyan leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] on 31 August 1978, discontent within the Shiite population about the suffering from the conflict between Israel and the Palestinian factions grew, especially following the Israeli [[1978 South Lebanon conflict|Operation Litani]] in March of that year. Within this context, tensions between Amal and the Palestinian militants escalated into violent clashes in many villages of Southern Lebanon, including the Tyre area.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Abraham|first=Antoine J.|title=The Lebanon War|publisher=Praeger|year=1996|isbn=978-0275953898|location=Westport, Conn.|pages=123}}</ref> The heaviest such incident took place in April 1982, when the PLO ([[Fatah|Fateh]]) bombarded Amal's Technical Institute in Burj El Shimali for ten hours.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite journal|last=Siklawi|first=Rami|date=Winter 2012|title=The Dynamics of the Amal Movement in Lebanon 1975\u201390|url=|journal=Arab Studies Quarterly|volume=34|issue=1|pages=4\u201326|jstor=41858677}}</ref>\n\n====== 1982 Israeli invasion ======\n\nFollowing the [[1982 Lebanon War|1982 Israeli Invasion]], the Palestinian refugee camp in Burj el-Shemali \u2013 according to UNRWA \u2013 \"''was badly damaged''\".<ref name=\":2\" /> An international commission to enquire into reported violations of [[international law]] by Israel during its invasion found that Israeli forces had destroyed 35 percent of the houses in the camp.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kaufman|first=Asher|url=https://www.academia.edu/5561720|title=Forgetting the Lebanon War? On Silence, Denial and Selective Remembrance of the First Lebanon War|publisher=Cambrige University Press|year=2010|isbn=978-0521196581|editor-last=Ben-Ze\u2019ev|editor-first=Efrat|location=Cambridge|pages=205|format=PDF|editor-last2=Ginio|editor-first2=Ruth|editor-last3=Winter|editor-first3=Jay}}</ref> Much of the destruction was done ''\"systematically''\" by the [[Israel Defense Forces]] (IDF) after the actual combat with Palestinian fighters had stopped.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gilmour|first=David|title=Lebanon: The Fractured Country|publisher=Martin Robertson|year=1983|isbn=978-0312477394|location=Oxford|pages=178\u2013179}}</ref> At the same time, the IDF set up a large compound right next to the Amal technical training center founded by Musa Sadr:<blockquote>\"''The centre doubled as office of the Amal leader in South Lebanon, [[Dawud Sulayman Dawud]], nicknamed 'David David' because of his alleged readiness to negotiate with Israel. He was a native of [[Tarbikha]], one of the five Shi'ite villages in northern Galilee, which were depoluated in October/November 1948, and his Lebanese opponents often called him a Palestinian. Dawud and other Amal leaders did not avoid discreet contacts with Israelis, but refused open clientship. The IDF soon lost patience and arrested thirteen Amal leaders as early as the summer of 1982.''\"<ref name=\":10\" /></blockquote>The situation soon escalated further: On 11 November 1982, a [[Suicide attack|suicide-attack]] with an [[Car bomb|explosive-laden car]] destroyed the Israeli military and intelligence headquarters in Tyre. As many as ninety soldiers, officers, and spies were killed as well as an unknown number of Lebanese and Palestinians [[Detention (imprisonment)|detainees]].<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite book|last=Hamzeh|first=Ahmad Nizar|title=In the Path of Hizbullah|publisher=Syracuse University Press|year=2004|isbn=978-0815630531|location=New York|pages=11, 82, 130, 133}}</ref> As initially nobody claimed responsibility for the assault, Amal came under suspicion as well. In May 1983, the IDF searched the training center and reportedly opened fire on a group of pupils in the schoolyard, killing one boy and wounding nine. Dawud called for mourning strike and threatened resistance.<ref name=\":10\" /> \n\nThen, in November 1983, another suicide-attack on the new Israeli headquarters in Tyre killed 29 Israeli soldiers and officers, wounding another thirty.<ref name=\":14\" /> 32 Lebanese and Palestinians died as well, most of them detainees. Only in 1985 was responsibility assumed for both attacks by an organisation that would go on to become a major player: [[Hezbollah]].<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n====== 1985 Amal takeover ======\n\nMeanwhile, in February 1985, an Amal member from Tyre launched a [[Suicide attack|suicide-attack]] on an IDF convoy in Burj El Shimali<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bonsen|first=Sabrina|title=Martyr Cults and Political Identities in Lebanon: \"Victory or Martyrdom\" in the Struggle of the Amal Movement|publisher=Springer Nature|year=2019|isbn=978-3-658-28098-7|location=Wiesbaden|pages=214, 248}}</ref>, injuring ten soldiers. \"''Israeli reprisals in the area east of Tyre killed fifteen and wounded dozens''.\" The IDF particularly retaliated against Amal's technical training center and Southern Headquarters in Burj el-Shemali, \"''igniting a new circle of violence.''\" Under the growing pressure the Israeli forces withdrew from Greater Tyre area by the end of April 1985 and Amal took over power there: <blockquote>\"''The priority of Amal remained to prevent the return of any armed Palestinian presence to the South, primarily because this might provoke renewed Israeli intervention in recently evacuated areas. The approximately 60,000 Palestinian refugees in the camps around Tyre (al-Bass, Rashidiya, Burj al-Shimali) were cut off from the outside world, although Amal never succeeded in fully controlling the camps themselves. In the Sunni 'canton' of Sidon, the armed PLO returned in force.''\"<ref name=\":10\" /></blockquote>It is not known how much the refugee camp in Burj el-Shemali and the surrounding areas were affected, when tensions between Amal and Palestinian militants escalated again and eventually exploded by September 1986 into \"''the war of the camps''\", which is considered as \"''one of the most brutal episodes in a brutal civil war''\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hudson|first=Michael C.|date=1997|title=Palestinians and Lebanon: The Common Story|url=https://mideast-africa.tau.ac.il/sites/humanities.tau.ac.il/files/media_server/mideast_africa/%D7%9C%D7%91%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%9F/%D7%93%D7%99%D7%9C%D7%9E%D7%95%D7%AA%20%D7%9E%D7%95%D7%91%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%AA%20%D7%91%D7%9E%D7%A2%D7%A8%D7%9B%D7%AA%20%D7%94%D7%9C%D7%91%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%A0%D7%99%D7%AA5pdf.pdf|journal=Journal of Refugee Studies|volume=10|issue=3|pages=243\u2013260|doi=10.1093/jrs/10.3.243|via=}}</ref> Clearly, it was once more the population of Rashidieh that bore the brunt of killing and destruction, when a group of Palestinians fired on an Amal patrol there. After one month of siege, Amal attacked the refugee camp in the South of Tyre<ref name=\":13\" />, reportedly assisted by its allies from the [[Progressive Socialist Party]], [[As-Sa'iqa|As-Saiqa]] and \"[[Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine \u2013 General Command]]\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Arsan|first=Andrew|title=Lebanon: A Country in Fragments|publisher=C Hurst & Co Publishers Ltd|year=2018|isbn=978-1849047005|location=London|pages=266}}</ref> Fighting spread and continued for one month. By that time some 7,000 refugees in the Tyre area were displaced once more.<ref name=\":13\" /> It may be assumed that Burj el-Shemali was less affected, since many of its residents were Shiites.<ref name=\":8\" /> However, there was at least one very prominent casualty from Burj el-Shemali: Amal's leader for Southern Lebanon Dawud Dawud, who was killed in renewed clashed between Amal and Hezbollah in 1988.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n===== Post-Civil War (since 1991) =====\nAfter the end of Lebanon's devastating civil war through the [[Taif Agreement]] in 1990, units of the Lebanese Army deployed along the coastal highway and around the Palestinian refugee camps of Tyre, including Burj el-Shemali.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Barak|first=Oren|title=The Lebanese Army: A National Institution in a Divided Society|publisher=State University of New York Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0-7914-9345-8|location=Albany|pages=67, 180}}</ref> Nevertheless, the camp saw an informal building boom in the course of the decade, as Palestinians living abroad invested money to improve their family houses or to build their own retirement homes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sheikh|first=Hassan Ismae\u2019l|date=May-June 2009|title=An Urbanity of Exile: Palestinian Refugee Camps|url=|journal=A10: New European Architecture|volume=27|pages=60-62|via=}}</ref>\n\nin 1994 many residents of the camp in Burj el-Shemali seem to have benefited from an exceptional process of [[Naturalization|naturalisation]]: while Lebanese [[citizenship]] - along with many [[Fundamental rights|basic rights]] - has generally been denied to Palestinian refugees, the government in Beirut now granted passports to refugees and their descendants from the seven predominantly [[Shia villages in Palestine|Shia Villages in Palestine]]. They had been given citizenship of [[Greater Lebanon]] by [[French colonial empire|France]] in 1921, but were attached to [[British Empire|British]] [[Mandatory Palestine]] two years later by the [[Paulet-Newcombe Agreement|Paulet-Newcombe commission]]. In the 1948 Nakba, many fled to the greater Tyre area, where they apparently settled in Burj el Shemali camp as well.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\n====== 2006 War between Israel and Hezbollah ======\nDuring Israel's invasion in the [[2006 Lebanon War]], Burj El Shimali was severely hit again: \n\n- on July 9th, the Plastimed and Plastic Medical Component Factories were struck in an assault by the [[Israeli Air Force]] (IAF);\n\n\u2013 on July 16th, five civilians were killed by in another IAF attack on a former soap factory, including two children;\n\n\u2013 on August 13th, another five civilians were killed by an IAF missile, amongst them three children and one [[Sri Lanka|Sri Lankan]] maid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2007/09/05/why-they-died/civilian-casualties-lebanon-during-2006-war|title=Why They Died: Civilian Casualties in Lebanon during the 2006 War\"|last=|first=|date=5 September 2007|website=Human Rights Watch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====== Post-2006 War ======\nAccording to a 2014 study paper, the majority of Palestinian refugees in Burj el-Shemali supported Fatah. However, it noted that there was \u2013 unlike in the other Tyrian camp of [[Rashidieh]] \u2013 also a considerable presence of [[Hamas]]. In addition, the [[Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine]] (PFLP), the [[Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine]] (DFLP), and the [[Islamic Jihad Movement in Palestine]] were represented in the Popular Committees that rule the camp.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rosalux.de/fileadmin/rls_uploads/pdfs/Studien/Studien_Flucht_Vertreibung.pdf|title=Flucht und Vertreibung im Syrien-Konflikt \u2013 Eine Analyse zur Situation von Fl\u00fcchtlingen in Syrien und im Libanon|last=|first=|date=July 2014|website=Rosa-Luxemburg-Stiftung|pages=28|language=German|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 2016, the mayor of Burj el-Shemali was [[Hajj Ali Dib]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/UN-Habitat_2017.05.22_CP_Tyre_web.pdf|title=TYRE CITY PROFILE|last=Maguire|first=Suzanne|last2=Majzoub|first2=Maya|date=2016|editor-last=Osseiran|editor-first=Tarek|website=reliefweb|publisher=UN HABITAT Lebanon|pages=13\u201318; 26|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n== Demographics ==\n\n=== Lebanese part of the town ===\nThere are no official figures for the Lebanese and Non-Lebanese population in the Lebanese-ruled part of Burj el-Shemali. \n\n=== Palestinian Refugee Camp ===\n[[File:Mansell-camp-code-18-1024x1024.jpg|thumb|Balloon mapping of the camp during a 2015 project of the NGO Greening Bourj Al Shamali, photo by Claudia Martinez Mansell]]\nBy 1982 the number of registered refugees in the camp had gone up to 11,256 from 7,159 in 1968.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|last=Brynen|first=Rex|title=Sanctuary And Survival: The PLO In Lebanon|publisher=Westview Press|year=1990|isbn=978-0813379197|location=Boulder|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the camp had 19,074 registered [[refugees]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/unrwa/refugees/lebanon.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-04-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409202113/http://www.un.org/unrwa/refugees/lebanon.html |archivedate=2008-04-09 }}</ref> As of June 2018, this number had grown to 24,929. This increase is mainly attributable to the arrival of many [[Syrian people|Syrian]] refugees and \u2013 especially \u2013 Palestinian refugees from Syria (PRS) after the beginning of the [[Syrian civil war]] in 2011.<ref name=\":2\" /> The already overcrowded living conditions have further deteriorated with the plight these twice-over refugees.<ref name=\":7\" /> UNRWA describes the situation as follows:<blockquote>\"''There is a very high incidence of [[thalassemia]] and [[sickle cell disease]] ([[genetic disorder]]) among Burj Shemali inhabitants and the camp is one of the poorest camps in Lebanon. [[Unemployment]] is extremely high, with seasonal agricultural work the most common source of income for both men and women.''\"<ref name=\":2\" /></blockquote>However, the second, third and fourth generation refugees have lost the [[Subsistence agriculture|subsistence agricultural]] existences of their ancestors from Palestine due to the very limited space and denial of land-ownership.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nForeigners need a permit from the [[military intelligence]] to enter the camp:<blockquote>\"''The permit system deters curious strangers and helps authorities monitor the population. It also makes the camp feel like an open-air [[prison]].''\"<ref name=\":5\" /></blockquote>In contrast to such clear-cut borders, other boundaries are much more blurred and fluid:\n\nIn 2017 at least, one [[Naturalization|naturalised]] Palestinian in Burj el Shemali camp was a member of the municipal council<ref>{{Cite book|last=Stel|first=Nora|url=https://www.academia.edu/31538902|title=Governing the Gatherings \u2013 The Interaction of Lebanese State Institutions and Palestinian Authorities in the Hybrid Political Order of South Lebanon's Informal Palestinian Settlements|publisher=|year=2017|isbn=|location=Utrecht|pages=217|format=PDF}}</ref>, as he probably originated from one of the seven predominantly Shi'ite villages in Palestine (see above).<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite journal|last=NISHIKIDA|first=Aiko|date=July 2009|title=Palestinians from the \"Seven Villages\":Their Legal Status and Social Condition|url=https://www.asafas.kyoto-u.ac.jp/kias/1st_period/contents/pdf/kb3_1/15nishikida.pdf|journal=Kyoto Bulletin of Islamic Area Studies|volume=3-1|pages=220\u2013231|via=}}</ref> A 1998 fact-finding mission of the [[Danish Immigration Service]] even was told by various sources that many residents at Burj el Shemali camp were Shiites and had been granted Lebanese nationality in 1994.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyidanmark.dk/-/media/Files/US/Landerapporter/Factfindingmission_Lebanon_1998.pdf?la=en-GB&hash=E4C43FEDE9F92ED581945E636DD2B84B01FEB97E|title=Report on fact-finding mission to Lebanon 2 \u2013 18 May 1998|last=|first=|date=1 June 1998|website=newtodenmark.dk|publisher=The Danish Immigration Service|page=57|format=PDF|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> However, a lot of them seem to have moved out of the camp since then. Their number reportedly went down in the following years to just \"''a few''\" Shiite families and only one Christian family still living in the camp by 2016.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nRemarkably, one neighborhood inside the camp is known as [[Morocco]], referring to the North African origin of the residents, whose ancestors moved to historic Palestine during the Ottoman Empire.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Gallery ==\n\n=== Exhibits at the National Museum of Beirut ===\n\n==== Funerary items ====\n<gallery>\nFile:BurjAlShimali LimestoneStele 5-4cBCE NationalMuseumOfBeirut RomanDeckert03102019.jpg|[[Limestone]] [[stele]], 5th to 4th century BCE\nFile:BurjAlShimali Relief IronAge-III NationalMuseumOfBeirut RomanDeckert03102019.jpg|Relief depicting a deceased person with a sheathed body, 550-333 BCE\nFile:BurjAlShemali RomanTombWithFrescoes NationalMuseumOfBeirut RomanDeckert03102019.jpg|Roman tomb with frescoes from the 2nd century CE\n</gallery>\n\n==== Mask of a Satyr, Roman period ====\n<gallery>\nFile:RomanTerracottaMaskOfSatyr-BurjElShemali NationalMuseumOfBeirut RomanDeckert 06102019.jpg\nFile:RomanTerracottaMaskOfSatyr BurjElShemali NationalMuseumOfBeirut RomanDeckert06102019.jpg\nFile:RomanTerracottaMask Satyr BurjAlShimali NationalMuseumOfBeirut RomanDeckert06102019.jpg\nFile:RomanTerracottaMaskOfSatyr-BurjElShemali NationalMuseumOfBeirut RomanDeckert06102019.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n=== The tower ===\n<gallery>\nFile:BurjAlShimali-TowerSide Lebanon-23092019RomanDeckert.jpg\nFile:BurjAlShimaliTowerLebanon 23092019RomanDeckert.jpg\nFile:BurjAlShimali-TowerInside Lebanon-23092019RomanDeckert.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.unrwa.org/where-we-work/lebanon/burj-shemali-camp Burj Shemali Camp],  from [[UNWRA]]\n\n{{Palestinian refugee camps}}\n{{Tyre District}}\n[[Category:Palestinian refugee camps in Lebanon]]\n\n\n{{Palestine-stub}}\n{{Lebanon-stub}}\n", "name_user": "RomanDeckert", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMask of a Satyr, Roman period", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burj_el-Shemali"}
{"title_page": "The Twilight Zone (2019 TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 American web television series}}\n{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Twilight Zone\n| image                    = Twilight zone 2019 logo.jpg\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Anthology series|Anthology]]\n*[[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]\n*[[Fantasy]]\n*[[Horror fiction|Horror]]\n*[[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]]\n*[[Science fiction]]\n}}\n| creator                  = [[Rod Serling]]\n| developer                = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Simon Kinberg]]\n*[[Jordan Peele]]\n*Marco Ramirez\n}}\n| narrated                 = Jordan Peele\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Marco Beltrami]]\n* Brandon Roberts\n* [[Marius Constant]] {{Small|(original theme)}}\n}}\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1\n| num_episodes             = 10\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n*Simon Kinberg\n*Jordan Peele\n*Win Rosenfeld\n*Audrey Chon\n*Carolyn Serling\n*Rick Berg\n*[[Greg Yaitanes]]\n*[[Glen Morgan]]\n}}\n| producer                 = \n| cinematography           = {{Plainlist|\n*Mathias Herndl\n*[[Craig Wrobleski]]\n}}\n| location                 = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]]\n| editor                   = Scott Turner\n| runtime                  = 37\u201356 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n*[[CBS Television Studios]]\n*{{nowrap|[[Monkeypaw Productions]]}}\n*[[Genre Films]]\n}}\n| network                  = [[CBS All Access]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2019|4|1}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|present}}\n| preceded_by              = {{nowrap|''[[The Twilight Zone (2002 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'' (2002\u201303)}}\n| website                  = https://www.cbs.com/shows/the-twilight-zone/\n| website_title            = Official website\n}}\n'''''The Twilight Zone''''' is an American [[Anthology series|anthology]] [[web television]] series developed by [[Simon Kinberg]], [[Jordan Peele]], and Marco Ramirez, based on the [[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|original 1959 television series]] created by [[Rod Serling]]. The series premiered on April 1, 2019, on [[CBS All Access]]. Peele serves as the narrator of this incarnation, in addition to executive producing through [[Monkeypaw Productions]]. On April 29, 2019, the series was renewed for a second season.\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nOn December 19, 2012, it was announced that [[Bryan Singer]] had finalized a deal to develop, executive produce, and potentially direct a third revival of ''The Twilight Zone'' for [[CBS Television Studios]]. Additionally, at the time of the announcement, the production had yet to hire a writer, begun being shopped to networks and was still finalizing a deal with the Serling estate.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|title=Bryan Singer To Spearhead \u2018Twilight Zone\u2019 Series Reboot For CBS TV Studios|url=https://deadline.com/2012/12/bryan-singer-to-spearhead-twilight-zone-series-reboot-for-cbs-tv-studios-391732/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=August 22, 2018|date=December 19, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013014429/https://deadline.com/2012/12/bryan-singer-to-spearhead-twilight-zone-series-reboot-for-cbs-tv-studios-391732/|archive-date=October 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Goldberg|first1=Lesley|title='X-Men's' Bryan Singer Prepping 'Twilight Zone' Reboot|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/twilight-zone-bryan-singer-405478|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=August 22, 2018|date=August 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923200542/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/twilight-zone-bryan-singer-405478|archive-date=September 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 7, 2013, it was reported that a writer was in negotiations to join the series.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cornet|first1=Roth|title=What's Happening with Bryan Singer's Planned Twilight Zone Series Reboot?|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/03/08/whats-happening-with-bryan-singers-planned-twilight-zone-series-reboot|website=[[IGN]]|accessdate=August 22, 2018|date=March 7, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923163345/http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/03/08/whats-happening-with-bryan-singers-planned-twilight-zone-series-reboot|archive-date=September 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> By 2016, [[Simon Kinberg]] and [[Craig Sweeny]] had joined the production and CBS was weighing whether to shop the project to other networks or streaming services or to place it on their own [[CBS All Access]]. Kinberg eventually left the project to write and direct the film ''[[Dark Phoenix (film)|Dark Phoenix]]'' and Singer and Sweeny soon dropped out as well.<ref name=\"CBSAllAccess\">{{cite web|last1=Steinberg|first1=Brian|last2=Holloway|first2=Daniel|title=CBS Will Revive \u2018Twilight Zone\u2019 on All Access Streaming Service|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/cbs-twilight-zone-all-access-streaming-1202605761/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=August 22, 2018|date=November 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180806180933/https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/cbs-twilight-zone-all-access-streaming-1202605761/|archive-date=August 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn November 2, 2017, it was announced that CBS was redeveloping the revival for their streaming service CBS All Access. Additionally, it was reported that [[Jordan Peele]] was in talks to executive produce the series through his production company [[Monkeypaw Productions]] and that Marco Ramirez was in talks to serve as showrunner.<ref name=\"CBSAllAccess\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hayes|first1=Dade|last2=Hipes|first2=Patrick|title=\u2018Twilight Zone\u2019 Series Reboot in Works at CBS All Access|url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/twilight-zone-reboot-cbs-all-access-1202200631/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 22, 2018|date=November 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006195047/https://deadline.com/2017/11/twilight-zone-reboot-cbs-all-access-1202200631/|archive-date=October 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On December 6, 2017, it was announced that CBS had given the production a series order. Peele and Ramirez were confirmed to executive produce alongside Simon Kinberg, Win Rosenfeld, Audrey Chon, Carol Serling, and Rick Berg. Peele, Ramirez, and Kinberg were also set to collaborate on the series' premiere episode. Production companies involved with the series were slated to consist of CBS Television Studios, Monkeypaw Productions, and [[Genre Films]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: Jordan Peele, Simon Kinberg & Marco Ramirez Board Reboot On CBS All Access|url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/the-twilight-zone-jordan-peele-simon-kinberg-marco-ramirez-reboot-cbs-all-access-1202221147/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 22, 2018|date=December 6, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180806212321/https://deadline.com/2017/12/the-twilight-zone-jordan-peele-simon-kinberg-marco-ramirez-reboot-cbs-all-access-1202221147/|archive-date=August 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn August 6, 2018, it was confirmed that the first season would consist of ten episodes. Additionally, it was reported that the production had established a writers' room and completed concepts, outlines, and scripts for the first season in various stages of development. The series was not planned to have a formal showrunner but director [[Greg Yaitanes]] was set to be in charge of overseeing continuity among episodes.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|last2=Patten|first2=Dominic|title=CBS All Access Bosses On More \u2018Star Trek\u2019 Series, \u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019 Status, Stephen King & More \u2013 TCA|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/patrick-stewart-star-trek-franchise-expansion-plans-cbs-all-access-executives-interview-tca-1202440492/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 22, 2018|date=August 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821213223/https://deadline.com/2018/08/patrick-stewart-star-trek-franchise-expansion-plans-cbs-all-access-executives-interview-tca-1202440492/|archive-date=August 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 20, 2018, it was announced that, in addition to executive producing, Peele would serve as the series' narrator and host.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ramos|first1=Dino-Ray|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: Jordan Peele To Host & Narrate CBS All Access Reboot|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/jordan-peele-twilight-zone-cbs-all-access-rod-serling-1202468028/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=September 20, 2018|date=September 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920173153/https://deadline.com/2018/09/jordan-peele-twilight-zone-cbs-all-access-rod-serling-1202468028/|archive-date=September 20, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 2, 2018, it was announced via a promotional video for the series that Gerard McMurray was directing an episode with Mathias Herndl serving as his director of photography.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Foutch|first1=Haleigh|title=Watch: 'The Twilight Zone' Announces Start of Production, First Director with New Teaser|url=http://collider.com/the-twilight-zone-filming-video/#images|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|accessdate=October 8, 2018|date=October 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008095742/http://collider.com/the-twilight-zone-filming-video/#images#images|archive-date=October 8, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On November 15, 2018, it was reported that [[Alex Rubens]] would write an episode of the series.<ref name=\"RubensNanjiani\">{{cite web|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: Kumail Nanjiani To Star in Episode Of CBS All Access Reboot|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/the-twilight-zone-kumail-nanjiani-star-episode-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202502659/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=November 23, 2018|date=November 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181123154240/https://deadline.com/2018/11/the-twilight-zone-kumail-nanjiani-star-episode-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202502659/|archive-date=November 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn April 29, 2019, the series was renewed for a second season.<ref name=\"Season 2 Renewal\">{{cite web|title=CBS All Access Renews 'The Twilight Zone' for Season Two|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2019/04/29/cbs-all-access-renews-the-twilight-zone-for-season-two-700215/20190429cbs01/|work=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=April 29, 2019|accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nIn October 2018, it was announced that [[Sanaa Lathan]] and [[Adam Scott (actor)|Adam Scott]] had been cast in guest-starring roles; Lathan would appear in an episode titled \"Rewind\"<ref name=\"Rewind\">{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: Sanaa Lathan To Star In \"Rewind\" Episode in CBS All Access Series|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/the-twilight-zone-sanaa-lathan-star-season-1-cbs-all-access-series-1202480928/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=October 11, 2018|date=October 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011205338/https://deadline.com/2018/10/the-twilight-zone-sanaa-lathan-star-season-1-cbs-all-access-series-1202480928/|archive-date=October 11, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and Scott in an episode titled \"Nightmare at 30,000 Feet\", a remake of the original series episode \"[[Nightmare at 20,000 Feet]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Haring|first=Bruce|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019 Adds Adam Scott For \u2018Nightmare at 30,000 Feet\u2019 Episode|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/the-twilight-zone-adds-adam-scott-for-nightmare-at-30000-feet-episode-1202489947/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=October 26, 2018|date=October 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026184018/https://deadline.com/2018/10/the-twilight-zone-adds-adam-scott-for-nightmare-at-30000-feet-episode-1202489947/|archive-date=October 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On November 15, 2018, it was reported that [[Kumail Nanjiani]] had been cast in a guest starring role.<ref name=\"RubensNanjiani\"/> In December 2018, it was announced that [[John Cho]], [[Allison Tolman]], [[Jacob Tremblay]], Erica Tremblay, [[Steven Yeun]], and [[Greg Kinnear]] would appear in guest starring roles. Cho, Tolman, and the Tremblays would appear in an episode titled \"The Wunderkind\"<ref name=\"The Wunderkind\">{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: John Cho, Allison Tolman & Jacob Tremblay To Star in Episode Of CBS All Access Reboot|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/the-twilight-zone-john-cho-allison-tolman-jacob-tremblay-to-star-in-episode-of-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202512838/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 3, 2018|date=December 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204004224/https://deadline.com/2018/12/the-twilight-zone-john-cho-allison-tolman-jacob-tremblay-to-star-in-episode-of-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202512838/|archive-date=December 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and Yeun<ref>{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=Steven Yeun Joins \u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019; Miley Cyrus In \u2018Black Mirror\u2019|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/stevenyeun-the-twilight-zone-miley-cyrus-black-mirror-1202519043/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 12, 2018|date=December 12, 2018}}</ref> and Kinnear in an episode titled \"The Traveler\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: Greg Kinnear To Star in Episode Of CBS All Access Reboot|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/the-twilight-zone-greg-kinnear-star-episode-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202519719/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 13, 2018|date=December 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214132417/https://deadline.com/2018/12/the-twilight-zone-greg-kinnear-star-episode-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202519719/|archive-date=December 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2019, it was reported that [[DeWanda Wise]], [[Jessica Williams (actress)|Jessica Williams]], [[Lucinda Dryzek]], Jefferson White, Jonathan Whitesell, [[Taissa Farmiga]], [[Rhea Seehorn]], [[Luke Kirby]], [[Ike Barinholtz]], and [[Percy Hynes White]] had been cast in guest starring roles. Wise, Williams, Dryzek, White, and Whitesell would appear in one episode<ref>{{cite web|last=Boucher|first=Geoff|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: DeWanda Wise, Jessica Williams Recruited For Jordan Peele Sci-Fi Show|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/the-twilight-zone-jordan-peele-cbs-all-access-1202534823/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=January 14, 2019|date=January 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114221131/https://deadline.com/2019/01/the-twilight-zone-jordan-peele-cbs-all-access-1202534823/|archive-date=January 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> while Farmiga, Seehorn, Kirby, Barinholtz, and Hynes-White would be featured in another.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: Taissa Farmiga, Rhea Seehorn, Luke Kirby & Ike Barinholtz To Star in Episode Of CBS All Access Reboot|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/the-twilight-zone-taissa-farmiga-rhea-seehorn-luke-kirby-ike-barinholtz-star-episode-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202543926/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=January 28, 2019|date=January 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129122903/https://deadline.com/2019/01/the-twilight-zone-taissa-farmiga-rhea-seehorn-luke-kirby-ike-barinholtz-star-episode-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202543926/|archive-date=January 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On February 7, 2019, it was announced that [[Ginnifer Goodwin]], [[James Frain]], and [[Zabryna Guevara]] had been cast to guest star in an episode titled \"Point of Origin\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: Ginnifer Goodwin To Star in Episode Of CBS All Access Reboot|url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/the-twilight-zone-ginnifer-goodwin-star-episode-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202551972/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=February 7, 2019|date=February 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209124523/https://deadline.com/2019/02/the-twilight-zone-ginnifer-goodwin-star-episode-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202551972/|archive-date=February 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The full trailer revealed that [[Tracy Morgan]], [[Glenn Fleshler]] and [[Chris Diamantopoulos]] would make guest appearances with Morgan appearing alongside Nanjiani, Fleshler in \"Rewind\" alongside Lathan, and Diamantopoulos joining Scott in \"Nightmare at 30,000 Feet\".<ref name=\"TrailerCast\"/> It was revealed through the official Twitter page that [[Seth Rogen]] would appear in an episode.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=TheTwilightZone|number=1101581425789173761|date=March 1, 2019|title=Enter the fifth dimension with @SethRogen as we he will star in an upcoming episode of #TheTwilightZone. The new @CBSAllAccess Original Series premieres April 1.}}</ref> On March 8, 2019, it was announced [[Zazie Beetz]] and [[Betty Gabriel]] would appear in an episode,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/the-twilight-zone-zazie-beetz-and-betty-gabriel-step-into-cbs-all-access-anthology-1202572128/|title=The Twilight Zone: Zazie Beetz And Betty Gabriel Step Into CBS All-Access Anthology|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Geoff|last=Boucher|date=March 8, 2019|accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref> while [[Chris O'Dowd]] and [[Amy Landecker]] would appear in an episode titled \"The Blue Scorpion\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/the-twilight-zone-chris-odowd-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202578408/|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: Chris O\u2019Dowd To Star in Episode Of CBS All Access Reboot|work=Deadline Hollywood|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|date=March 19, 2019|accessdate=March 20, 2019}}</ref> On March 28, 2019, it was announced that [[Damson Idris]] would appear in an episode titled \"Replay\", which was previously titled \"Rewind\".<ref name=\"Replay\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/3/28/18285952/jordan-peele-twilight-zone-review-classic-episodes-connections/|title=Jordan Peele's Twilight Zone inverts classic episodes to tell urgent, new stories|website=Polygon|last=Frederick|first=Candice|date=March 28, 2019|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nPrincipal photography for season one began on October 1, 2018, in [[Vancouver]], British Columbia,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ramos|first1=Dino-Ray|title=Jordan Peele's \u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019 Begins Production, Celebrates 59 Years Of Iconic Sci-Fi Original|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/the-twilight-zone-production-jordan-peele-simon-kinberg-59-years-1202474946/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=October 2, 2018|date=October 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003004936/https://deadline.com/2018/10/the-twilight-zone-production-jordan-peele-simon-kinberg-59-years-1202474946/|archive-date=October 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and concluded on March 20, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mirchandani|first1=Amar|title=27 TV Shows Filming in Vancouver Right Now (December 2018)|url=https://604now.com/tv-shows-filming-vancouver-december-2018/|website=604 Now|accessdate=December 2, 2018|date=November 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202202629/https://604now.com/tv-shows-filming-vancouver-december-2018/|archive-date=December 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n===Season 1 (2019)===\n{{Episode table |background=#22202E |overall=5 |season=5 |title=18 |director=16 |writer=41 |airdate=15 |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = The Comedian\n| DirectedBy      = [[Owen Harris (director)|Owen Harris]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Alex Rubens]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|4|1}}\n| ShortSummary    = Struggling comedian Samir Wassan meets legendary comic J.C. Wheeler, who advises him to include personal material in his routines. After doing a successful routine centered around his dog, Samir returns home and discovers that not only did his dog vanish, but no one seems to remember that it ever existed. He then learns that jokes about the people in his life get laughs, but cause them to disappear from existence. After accidentally erasing his nephew, Devin, Samir starts erasing people he thinks the world would be better off without. His girlfriend, Rena, leaves him after the erasing of David Kendall causes her to go from a successful lawyer to a struggling [[Waiting staff|waitress]]. After another encounter with Wheeler, Samir continues abusing his power, going so far as erasing rival comic Didi Scott. Rena confronts him during a set with a journal containing names of those he's erased. Realizing what he has done, Samir erases himself from existence while everyone previously erased exists again. Didi, now a rising star, meets Wheeler following a set and asks for his advice.{{Episode cast}} [[Kumail Nanjiani]], [[Amara Karan]], Diarra Kilpatrick, [[Ryan Robbins]], [[Tracy Morgan]]<br>\nThe inspiration for this episode was \"[[Take My Life...Please!]]\" from the [[The Twilight Zone (1985 TV series)|1985 series]]. Rosie Knight of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' stated \"Samir's story appears to take a large influence from [...] ''[[Death Note]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Knight, Rosie|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/twilight-zone-comedian-nightmare-at-30000-feet-explained-1198347|title='The Twilight Zone' Takes on Classic Episode, Lust for Fame in CBS All Access Debut|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=2019-04-01|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| Title           = Nightmare at 30,000 Feet\n| DirectedBy      = [[Greg Yaitanes]]\n| WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=[[Simon Kinberg]], [[Jordan Peele]] and Marco Ramirez|t=Marco Ramirez|ex1label=Based on ''\"[[Nightmare at 20,000 Feet]]\"'' by|ex1=[[Richard Matheson]]}}\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|4|1}}\n| ShortSummary    = PTSD-afflicted journalist Justin Sanderson boards Northern Goldstar Airlines Flight 1015 from Washington, D.C. to Tel Aviv after accepting a job offer. Shortly before takeoff, Justin finds an MP3 player in his seat pocket and discovers it contains a podcast hosted by Rodman Edwards revolving around \"the mystery of Northern Goldstar Flight 1015\", which disappeared an hour into the flight. As the podcast accurately describes events involving his fellow passengers, Justin juggles controlling his nerves and confiding in Joe Beaumont, a former pilot who seems to be the only person who believes him and had lost his job for crashing a previous airplane. He tries using clues from the podcast to avert the disaster, but every attempt results in irritated crew and passengers. Joe then convinces Justin to help him gain access to the flight deck so he can land the plane safely in Canada. The two accomplish their mission, but Justin realizes from the podcast at the last minute that Joe is responsible for the crash. Waking up on an atoll, Justin learns via the podcast that everyone that survived was rescued months later while he is considered missing. The other survivors appear, surround Justin from all sides, and beat him to death as he claims that he was trying to save them. {{Episode cast}} [[Adam Scott (actor)|Adam Scott]], [[Chris Diamantopoulos]], [[Dan Carlin]], [[Katie Findlay]], [[Nicholas Lea]]\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| Title           = Replay\n| DirectedBy      = Gerard McMurray\n| WrittenBy       = [[Selwyn Seyfu Hinds]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|4|11}}\n| ShortSummary    = While at a roadside diner with her college-bound son Dorian, Nina Harrison discovers her old family camcorder has the power to [[Time travel|turn back time]] when she presses the rewind button and that she is the only one aware of its capabilities. The two encounter Lasky, a racist [[State police (United States)|state trooper]] who pulls them over for speeding before becoming violent with them. Nina rewinds time and convinces Dorian to pull over by claiming she doesn't feel well. This time however, Lasky holds them for not pulling over properly. Nina attempts to change time by first stopping at a motel and then trying to sympathize with Lasky at the diner, but both attempts end in Lasky harming or killing Dorian. Nina then visits her estranged brother Neil who not only believes her story, but helps her get Dorian to the college campus. When Lasky arrives with a group of state troopers, Nina, Neil, and the students stand their ground; prompting Lasky to leave. Ten years later, Dorian has become a father to daughter Trinity while Nina holds onto the camcorder. After Trinity accidentally breaks the camcorder, Dorian tells Nina to let go and leaves to run an errand as she and Trinity look on. As the credits begin to roll, the sound of a police siren is heard. {{Episode cast}} [[Sanaa Lathan]], [[Damson Idris]], [[Glenn Fleshler]], [[Steve Harris (actor)|Steve Harris]]\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| Title           = A Traveler\n| DirectedBy      = [[Ana Lily Amirpour]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Glen Morgan]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|4|18}}\n| ShortSummary    = Alaska police sergeant Yuka Mongoyak arranges for her brother, Jack, to be pardoned at [[Police captain|Captain]] Lane Pendleton's annual Christmas party, which she detests. At the height of the festivities, Yuka discovers another inmate has mysteriously appeared in the station's holding cells. The stranger, whose name is \"legally\" A. Traveler, claims he is an extreme tourist who has heard of Pendleton's \"famous\" parties. As Traveler becomes friendly with the guests, Yuka grows suspicious of his identity. Pendleton soon grows suspicious when Traveler reveals information he should have no way of knowing like the actions done by Mayor Matheson. When Yuka, Jack, and Pendleton spot antennas on Traveler's head, Traveler deflects their suspicions by claiming Pendleton is in league with the Russians. Pendleton then leaves to check on the shed powering the town while Traveler promises Yuka that she will be in charge and that \"[his] people\" will come and take over. Yuka proceeds to corner Pendleton and hold him at gunpoint as they witness UFOs descend from the sky. At the station, Jack shares a piece of pumpkin pie with Traveler, now in his true alien form, and states things would be better with them in charge.{{Episode cast}} [[Steven Yeun]], Marika Sila, [[Patrick Gallagher (actor)|Patrick Gallagher]], [[Eric Keenleyside]], [[Andrew Kavadas]], Gail Maurice, [[Greg Kinnear]]\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n| Title           = The Wunderkind\n| DirectedBy      = [[Richard Shepard]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Andrew Guest]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|4|25}}\n| ShortSummary    = [[Campaign manager]] Raff Hanks finds himself in a hospital and recounts the events leading up to his hospitalization to an orderly. Years earlier, Raff considered himself a wunderkind and had been a successful campaign manager. After he and his partner Maura fail to get then-sitting and unpopular President of the United States James Stevens reelected, Raff's career is ruined. While at the bar years later, Raff spots a news item about eleven-year-old YouTube star Oliver Foley announcing his candidacy for President. Seizing the opportunity to redeem himself, Raff convinces Oliver's parents about having him run. While the public supports Oliver, he struggles to answer questions about current issues and humiliates himself during a debate. Raff then bases Oliver's campaign around family after learning his dog is dying of cancer; resulting in Oliver winning the Iowa caucus and subsequently becoming President while his mother becomes the Vice President. Oliver takes control of the White House, prompting Raff to regret his actions. When Oliver catches wind of Raff's \"treason\", he reveals he lied about his dog dying to get votes before convincing the Secret Service to shoot Raff. In the present, Raff learns from the orderly that the surgeon operating on him is an apathetic child due to Oliver's having passed a law forbidding old doctors.{{Episode cast}} [[John Cho]], [[Jacob Tremblay]], [[Allison Tolman]], Kimberley Sustad, Lane Edwards, Erica Tremblay, [[John Larroquette]]\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 6\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n| Title           = Six Degrees of Freedom\n| DirectedBy      = [[Jakob Verbruggen]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Heather Anne Campbell]] and Glen Morgan\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|5|2}}\n| ShortSummary    = The crew of the Bradbury spacecraft, led by Alexa Brandt, decide to head for the planet [[Mars]] after a nuclear war breaks out on earth. The crew members soon begin to turn on one another, in spite of Brandt's attempts to convince them to come together under times of stress. However, she too begins to break, devastating fellow crew member Katherine Langford. One crewman, Jerry Pierson, goes crazy and starts rambling that they are being watched, to which the other crewmen don't believe him. Later on, he is seemingly killed after going out the airlock. The crew successfully lands on Mars. It is later revealed that Jerry had been taken away by aliens and that he was correct: aliens have been monitoring the crew trying to determine if they are worth saving and pass through the [[great filter]].{{Episode cast}} [[DeWanda Wise]], [[Jessica Williams (actress)|Jessica Williams]], Jefferson White, [[Lucinda Dryzek]], Jonathan Whitesell\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 7\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n| Title           = Not All Men\n| DirectedBy      = Christina Choe\n| WrittenBy       = Heather Anne Campbell\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|5|9}}\n| ShortSummary    = Reporter Annie Miller is invited by her co-worker Dylan to watch a meteor shower. During the event, Dylan picks up one of the rocks, causing his attitude to change. Annie leaves early after witnessing Dylan destroy his record player. The next day, Annie visits her sister Martha who is celebrating her birthday with her husband Mike, nephew Cole, and Phil. While having cake, they hear a neighbor scream about contaminated water before witnessing most of the town's men, including Mike, partake in violent acts; with Phil being killed in the process. Dylan appears and tries to strangle Annie before she gets free and knocks him back. Annie, Martha, and Cole are later rescued and taken to a quarantine center, where they learn that a virus infected the town's water supply and affected almost all of the men. Even though he had one of the meteors in his pocket, Cole is deemed healthy, as he was able to control his rage, and revealing that the meteorites were just a placebo for the men's violent behaviors. The three are eventually allowed to leave as the news blames the incident on road rage and late night crime sprees.{{Episode cast}} [[Taissa Farmiga]], [[Rhea Seehorn]], [[Percy Hynes White]], [[Luke Kirby]], [[Peter Kelamis]], [[Ike Barinholtz]]\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 8\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n| Title           = Point of Origin\n| DirectedBy      = Mathias Herndl\n| WrittenBy       = John Griffin\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|5|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = Wealthy socialite Eve Martin is approached by her [[Housekeeper (domestic worker)|housekeeper]] and [[nanny]] Anna Fuentas who asks if her grandson can use her address as she's an illegal immigrant from Guatemala. Eve agrees while she prepares for a party for new parents. However, Anna is taken by [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|ICE]]. While out grocery shopping with her daughters, Eve finds that her credit cards have been declined. In the parking lot, they are picked up by [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement#Homeland Security Investigations (HSI)|HSI]]. She and her husband William are interrogated by Agent Allandale. While her family is released, Eve remains in HSI custody so Allandale can figure out where she came from. The machine she is subjected to gives her the fake illusion that HSI later released her as well as visions of a ruined world. Eve is shocked to find out that Anna is an illegal alien from another dimension and that she is too. Eve and Anna manage to formulate an escape plan as they dodge HSI agents. While Anna goes in a different direction, Eve heads home where William says she can't be here. Agent Allandale arrives with the HSI agents. When Eve tells him to get out of her house, Allandale tells her to get out of \"his house.\" Eve is taken away by the HSI to be reimprisoned as William sheds a tear.{{Episode cast}} [[Ginnifer Goodwin]], [[James Frain]], Toby Levins, [[Zabryna Guevara]], [[Karin Konoval]], [[Michael Eklund]], Robert Mann\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 9\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 9\n| Title           = The Blue Scorpion\n| DirectedBy      = [[Craig William Macneill]]\n| WrittenBy       = Glen Morgan\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|5|23}}\n| ShortSummary    = Depressed anthropology professor Jeff Storck is about to divorce from his wife despite his pleas for counseling. On top of that, he finds that his father has apparently committed suicide. While in his dad\u2019s house, he finds a gun called the Blue Scorpion with a bullet with his name on it. At the funeral, Jeff questions why his father would kill himself. With all that's going on in his life, Jeff contemplates killing himself with the gun after testing it at a gun range. Meanwhile, Jeff\u2019s estranged wife has begun seeing another man, also named Jeff, which gets Jeff to thinking about killing the man due to his feelings for his wife. Jeff goes to her house and shoots at his wife\u2019s boyfriend. The bullet misses him, but hits and kills a burglar in the house, also named Jeff. In the aftermath of this after being praised for stopping the burglar, Jeff decides to rid himself of the gun that has caused him his misfortune. He throws it into the harbor and leaves. Later, the gun is found by two kids with the bullet now reading the name \u201cKyle\u201d after the kid who picked it up.{{Episode cast}} [[Chris O'Dowd]], [[Amy Landecker]], [[Alex Diakun]], [[James Morrison (actor)|James Morrison]], [[Adam Korson]], [[Luisa D'Oliveira]]\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 10\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 10\n| Title           = Blurryman\n| DirectedBy      = Simon Kinberg\n| WrittenBy       = Alex Rubens\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|5|30}}\n| ShortSummary    = After rewriting the opening narration for an episode of ''The Twilight Zone'' starring Seth Rogen and Betty Gabriel for Jordan Peele in this meta-fictional episode, screenwriter and ''Twilight Zone'' fan Sophie Gelson discovers someone changed it to be about her. She later notices a mysterious blurry figure appearing in the background of several scenes as well as scenes from previous episodes. While searching for Jordan, Sophie encounters the Blurryman, who chases her through the studio and triggers a flashback to her childhood. After a brief encounter with [[Jason Priestley]], she hands a new version of the narration to Jordan before finding herself in the world of the iconic episode \"[[Time Enough at Last]].\" When she finally encounters the Blurryman and agrees to hear it out, the Blurryman reveals himself as original series host [[Rod Serling]]. Claiming that they have \"a lot of work to do,\" Serling escorts Sophie through a door into the Twilight Zone.{{Episode cast}} [[Zazie Beetz]], [[Betty Gabriel]], Zibby Allen, Caitlin Stryker, [[Seth Rogen]]\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n}}\n\n===Season 2===\n<!--Per WP:TVUPCOMING, do not include 2020 until episodes have actually aired in 2020!-->\nThe season will consist of ten episodes.<ref name=\"TwilightZoneSeason2\" />\n{{Episode table |background=#3CB3C8 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=18 |director=16 |writer=41 |airdate=15 |released=y |airdateR=<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/01/the-twilight-zone-season-2-cast-list-jordan-peele-episode-1202202551/|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019 Season 2 Sets New Cast, Jordan Peele to Write New Episode|first=Ben|last=Travers|publisher=IndieWire|date=January 12, 2020|accessdate=January 13, 2020}}</ref> |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = \n| EpisodeNumber2  = \n| Title           = Downtime\n| RTitle          =<ref name=\"TwilightZoneSeason2\" />\n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = [[Jordan Peele]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020}}\n| ShortSummary    = {{Episode cast|hr=n}} [[Morena Baccarin]], [[Colman Domingo]], [[Tony Hale]]\n| LineColor       = 3CB3C8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = \n| EpisodeNumber2  = \n| Title           = The Who of You\n| RTitle          =<ref name=\"TwilightZoneSeason2\" />\n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = Win Rosenfeld\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020}}\n| ShortSummary    = {{Episode cast|hr=n}} [[Daniel Sunjata]], [[Ethan Embry]], [[Billy Porter (entertainer)|Billy Porter]]\n| LineColor       = 3CB3C8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = \n| EpisodeNumber2  = \n| Title           = A Human Face\n| RTitle          =<ref name=\"TwilightZoneSeason2\" />\n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = [[Alex Rubens]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020}}\n| ShortSummary    = {{Episode cast|hr=n}} [[Jenna Elfman]], [[Christopher Meloni]], [[Tavi Gevinson]]\n| LineColor       = 3CB3C8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = \n| EpisodeNumber2  = \n| Title           = 8\n| RTitle          =<ref name=\"TwilightZoneSeason2\" />\n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = [[Glen Morgan]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020}}\n| ShortSummary    = {{Episode cast|hr=n}} [[Joel McHale]]\n| LineColor       = 3CB3C8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = \n| EpisodeNumber2  = \n| Title           = Among the Untrodden\n| RTitle          =<ref name=\"TwilightZoneSeason2\" />\n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = [[Heather Anne Campbell]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020}}\n| ShortSummary    = {{Episode cast|hr=n}} Abbie Hern, Sophia Macy\n| LineColor       = 3CB3C8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = \n| EpisodeNumber2  = \n| Title           = Meet in the Middle\n| RTitle          =<ref name=\"TwilightZoneSeason2\">{{cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/gillian-jacobs-joel-mchale-billy-porter-tony-hale-an-1840959638/amp|title=Gillian Jacobs, Joel McHale, Billy Porter, Tony Hale, and more are headed to ''The Twilight Zone''|first=Sam|last=Barsanti|publisher=AV Club|date=January 12, 2020|accessdate=January 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = Emily C. Chang & Sarah Amini\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020}}\n| ShortSummary    = {{Episode cast|hr=n}} [[Jimmi Simpson]], [[Gillian Jacobs]]\n| LineColor       = 3CB3C8\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = \n| EpisodeNumber2  = \n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 3CB3C8\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = \n| EpisodeNumber2  = \n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 3CB3C8\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = \n| EpisodeNumber2  = \n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 3CB3C8\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = \n| EpisodeNumber2  = \n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 3CB3C8\n}}\n}}\n\n==Release==\nOn January 30, 2019, it was announced during the [[Television Critics Association]]'s annual winter press tour that the series would premiere on April 1, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019 Gets April Premiere Date On CBS All Access \u2013 TCA|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/the-twilight-zone-april-premiere-date-cbs-all-access-1202545867/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=January 30, 2019|date=January 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131010717/https://deadline.com/2019/01/the-twilight-zone-april-premiere-date-cbs-all-access-1202545867/|archive-date=January 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A black-and-white version of the first season was released on May 30, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2019/05/11/cbs-all-access-twilight-zone-black-and-white/ |title=CBS All Access will stream 'Twilight Zone' in black and white |website=Engadget |first=Jon |last=Fingas |date=May 11, 2019 |accessdate=May 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nOn February 3, 2019, a teaser trailer for the series aired during the telecast of [[Super Bowl LIII]]. The commercial played as though it was interrupting CBS' feed of the game and it featured host [[Jordan Peele]] standing in an empty [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: First Spot For Series Revival \"Disrupts\" Super Bowl Telecast|url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/the-twilight-zone-super-bowl-spot-jordan-peele-1202548668/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=February 3, 2019|date=February 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204012037/https://deadline.com/2019/02/the-twilight-zone-super-bowl-spot-jordan-peele-1202548668/|archive-date=February 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Another trailer was released on February 21.<ref name=\"TrailerCast\">{{cite web|last=Baysinger|first=Tim|title='Twilight Zone' Trailer: See Adam Scott, Sanaa Lathan and Tracy Morgan Enter The Fifth Dimension|url=https://www.thewrap.com/twilight-zone-trailer-see-adam-scott-sanaa-lathan-and-tracy-morgan-enter-the-fifth-dimension-video/|website=TheWrap|accessdate=February 21, 2019|date=February 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222013659/https://www.thewrap.com/twilight-zone-trailer-see-adam-scott-sanaa-lathan-and-tracy-morgan-enter-the-fifth-dimension-video/|archive-date=February 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\nOn the review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the first season holds an approval rating of 71% based on 86 reviews, with an average rating of 7.39/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''The Twilight Zone'' explores the strangeness of the modern world through Rod Serling's winning formula, creating a thought-provoking \u2013 if not always spine-tingling \u2013 showcase for Jordan Peele and his exceptional crop of collaborators.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_twilight_zone_2019/s01|title=The Twilight Zone: Season 1 (2019)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] assigned the first season a weighted average score of 60 out of 100 based on 37 critics, indicating \"generally positive reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-twilight-zone-2019/season-1|title=The Twilight Zone (2019) : Season 1|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[BBC]] gave it a positive review and said: \"It's possible that ... Rod Serling and Jordan Peele switched places. As co-creator and on-screen host of the new version, he [Peele] updates the series while capturing the original's essence.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20190401-the-twilight-zone-eerie-witty-stylishly-told-stories|title=The Twilight Zone: Eerie, witty, stylishly told stories|website=BBC|first=Caryn|last=James|date=April 2, 2019|accessdate=April 25, 2019}}</ref> ''[[The Week]]'' was more mixed in its review, calling the first episodes \"unforgivably long\", but also saying that the series stays \"true to the ethos of ''The Twilight Zone''\" and that \"the episodes are free-standing and timeless\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/articles/832528/jordan-peeles-twilight-zone-unforgivably-long|title=Jordan Peele's Twilight Zone is Unforgivably Long|website=The Week|first=Java|last=Lange|date=April 2, 2019|accessdate=April 25, 2019}}</ref> ''[[The Verge]]'' also gave it a mixed review, praising Jordan Peele as the narrator, but saying the series should try to step away from the original.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/4/1/18287537/jordan-peele-twilight-zone-reboot-review-cbs-adam-scott-steven-yuen-kumail-nanjiani-tracy-morgan|title=Jordan Peele's Twilight Zone reboot leans too heavily on the original|website=The Verge|first=Samantha|last=Nelson|date=April 1, 2019|accessdate=April 25, 2019}}</ref> ''[[The Atlantic]]'' was more critical, comparing it to the original series, stating, \"[w]ith the exception of one superior episode, 'Replay', it's hard to conceive that an artist as prodigiously talented and thoughtful as Peele is creatively involved at all.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Gilbert|first1=Sophie|title=What the Twilight Zone Reboot Is Missing|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/04/jordan-peeles-twilight-zone-reboot-missing-something/586396/|website=The Atlantic|accessdate=April 19, 2019|date=April 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nFor the [[71st Primetime Emmy Awards]], [[Kumail Nanjiani]] received a nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Actor in a Drama Series]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/16/arts/television/emmy-nominations-list.html |title=Here's a Full List of the 2019 Emmy Nominations |work=The New York Times |first=Sara |last=Aridi |date=July 16, 2019 |accessdate=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official|https://www.cbs.com/shows/the-twilight-zone/}}\n* {{IMDb title|2583620}}\n\n{{Twilight Zone}}\n{{Jordan Peele}}\n{{Simon Kinberg}}\n{{CBS All Access}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Twilight Zone, The}}\n\n[[Category:2010s American anthology television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:2019 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:CBS All Access original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Fantasy web series]]\n[[Category:Horror anthology web series]]\n[[Category:Science fiction anthology web series]]\n[[Category:Television series by CBS Television Studios]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Jordan Peele]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Simon Kinberg]]\n[[Category:Television series produced in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Television series reboots]]\n[[Category:The Twilight Zone]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 American web television series}}\n{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Twilight Zone\n| image                    = Twilight zone 2019 logo.jpg\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Anthology series|Anthology]]\n*[[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]\n*[[Fantasy]]\n*[[Horror fiction|Horror]]\n*[[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]]\n*[[Science fiction]]\n}}\n| creator                  = [[Rod Serling]]\n| developer                = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Simon Kinberg]]\n*[[Jordan Peele]]\n*Marco Ramirez\n}}\n| narrated                 = Jordan Peele\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Marco Beltrami]]\n* Brandon Roberts\n* [[Marius Constant]] {{Small|(original theme)}}\n}}\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1\n| num_episodes             = 10\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n*Simon Kinberg\n*Jordan Peele\n*Win Rosenfeld\n*Audrey Chon\n*Carolyn Serling\n*Rick Berg\n*[[Greg Yaitanes]]\n*[[Glen Morgan]]\n}}\n| producer                 = \n| cinematography           = {{Plainlist|\n*Mathias Herndl\n*[[Craig Wrobleski]]\n}}\n| location                 = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]]\n| editor                   = Scott Turner\n| runtime                  = 37\u201356 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n*[[CBS Television Studios]]\n*{{nowrap|[[Monkeypaw Productions]]}}\n*[[Genre Films]]\n}}\n| network                  = [[CBS All Access]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2019|4|1}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|present}}\n| preceded_by              = {{nowrap|''[[The Twilight Zone (2002 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'' (2002\u201303)}}\n| website                  = https://www.cbs.com/shows/the-twilight-zone/\n| website_title            = Official website\n}}\n'''''The Twilight Zone''''' is an American [[Anthology series|anthology]] [[web television]] series developed by [[Simon Kinberg]], [[Jordan Peele]], and Marco Ramirez, based on the [[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|original 1959 television series]] created by [[Rod Serling]]. The series premiered on April 1, 2019, on [[CBS All Access]]. Peele serves as the narrator of this incarnation, in addition to executive producing through [[Monkeypaw Productions]]. On April 29, 2019, the series was renewed for a second season.\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nOn December 19, 2012, it was announced that [[Bryan Singer]] had finalized a deal to develop, executive produce, and potentially direct a third revival of ''The Twilight Zone'' for [[CBS Television Studios]]. Additionally, at the time of the announcement, the production had yet to hire a writer, begun being shopped to networks and was still finalizing a deal with the Serling estate.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|title=Bryan Singer To Spearhead \u2018Twilight Zone\u2019 Series Reboot For CBS TV Studios|url=https://deadline.com/2012/12/bryan-singer-to-spearhead-twilight-zone-series-reboot-for-cbs-tv-studios-391732/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=August 22, 2018|date=December 19, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013014429/https://deadline.com/2012/12/bryan-singer-to-spearhead-twilight-zone-series-reboot-for-cbs-tv-studios-391732/|archive-date=October 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Goldberg|first1=Lesley|title='X-Men's' Bryan Singer Prepping 'Twilight Zone' Reboot|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/twilight-zone-bryan-singer-405478|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=August 22, 2018|date=August 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923200542/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/twilight-zone-bryan-singer-405478|archive-date=September 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 7, 2013, it was reported that a writer was in negotiations to join the series.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cornet|first1=Roth|title=What's Happening with Bryan Singer's Planned Twilight Zone Series Reboot?|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/03/08/whats-happening-with-bryan-singers-planned-twilight-zone-series-reboot|website=[[IGN]]|accessdate=August 22, 2018|date=March 7, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923163345/http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/03/08/whats-happening-with-bryan-singers-planned-twilight-zone-series-reboot|archive-date=September 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> By 2016, [[Simon Kinberg]] and [[Craig Sweeny]] had joined the production and CBS was weighing whether to shop the project to other networks or streaming services or to place it on their own [[CBS All Access]]. Kinberg eventually left the project to write and direct the film ''[[Dark Phoenix (film)|Dark Phoenix]]'' and Singer and Sweeny soon dropped out as well.<ref name=\"CBSAllAccess\">{{cite web|last1=Steinberg|first1=Brian|last2=Holloway|first2=Daniel|title=CBS Will Revive \u2018Twilight Zone\u2019 on All Access Streaming Service|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/cbs-twilight-zone-all-access-streaming-1202605761/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=August 22, 2018|date=November 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180806180933/https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/cbs-twilight-zone-all-access-streaming-1202605761/|archive-date=August 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn November 2, 2017, it was announced that CBS was redeveloping the revival for their streaming service CBS All Access. Additionally, it was reported that [[Jordan Peele]] was in talks to executive produce the series through his production company [[Monkeypaw Productions]] and that Marco Ramirez was in talks to serve as showrunner.<ref name=\"CBSAllAccess\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hayes|first1=Dade|last2=Hipes|first2=Patrick|title=\u2018Twilight Zone\u2019 Series Reboot in Works at CBS All Access|url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/twilight-zone-reboot-cbs-all-access-1202200631/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 22, 2018|date=November 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006195047/https://deadline.com/2017/11/twilight-zone-reboot-cbs-all-access-1202200631/|archive-date=October 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On December 6, 2017, it was announced that CBS had given the production a series order. Peele and Ramirez were confirmed to executive produce alongside Simon Kinberg, Win Rosenfeld, Audrey Chon, Carol Serling, and Rick Berg. Peele, Ramirez, and Kinberg were also set to collaborate on the series' premiere episode. Production companies involved with the series were slated to consist of CBS Television Studios, Monkeypaw Productions, and [[Genre Films]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: Jordan Peele, Simon Kinberg & Marco Ramirez Board Reboot On CBS All Access|url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/the-twilight-zone-jordan-peele-simon-kinberg-marco-ramirez-reboot-cbs-all-access-1202221147/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 22, 2018|date=December 6, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180806212321/https://deadline.com/2017/12/the-twilight-zone-jordan-peele-simon-kinberg-marco-ramirez-reboot-cbs-all-access-1202221147/|archive-date=August 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn August 6, 2018, it was confirmed that the first season would consist of ten episodes. Additionally, it was reported that the production had established a writers' room and completed concepts, outlines, and scripts for the first season in various stages of development. The series was not planned to have a formal showrunner but director [[Greg Yaitanes]] was set to be in charge of overseeing continuity among episodes.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|last2=Patten|first2=Dominic|title=CBS All Access Bosses On More \u2018Star Trek\u2019 Series, \u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019 Status, Stephen King & More \u2013 TCA|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/patrick-stewart-star-trek-franchise-expansion-plans-cbs-all-access-executives-interview-tca-1202440492/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 22, 2018|date=August 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821213223/https://deadline.com/2018/08/patrick-stewart-star-trek-franchise-expansion-plans-cbs-all-access-executives-interview-tca-1202440492/|archive-date=August 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 20, 2018, it was announced that, in addition to executive producing, Peele would serve as the series' narrator and host.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ramos|first1=Dino-Ray|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: Jordan Peele To Host & Narrate CBS All Access Reboot|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/jordan-peele-twilight-zone-cbs-all-access-rod-serling-1202468028/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=September 20, 2018|date=September 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920173153/https://deadline.com/2018/09/jordan-peele-twilight-zone-cbs-all-access-rod-serling-1202468028/|archive-date=September 20, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 2, 2018, it was announced via a promotional video for the series that Gerard McMurray was directing an episode with Mathias Herndl serving as his director of photography.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Foutch|first1=Haleigh|title=Watch: 'The Twilight Zone' Announces Start of Production, First Director with New Teaser|url=http://collider.com/the-twilight-zone-filming-video/#images|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|accessdate=October 8, 2018|date=October 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008095742/http://collider.com/the-twilight-zone-filming-video/#images#images|archive-date=October 8, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On November 15, 2018, it was reported that [[Alex Rubens]] would write an episode of the series.<ref name=\"RubensNanjiani\">{{cite web|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: Kumail Nanjiani To Star in Episode Of CBS All Access Reboot|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/the-twilight-zone-kumail-nanjiani-star-episode-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202502659/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=November 23, 2018|date=November 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181123154240/https://deadline.com/2018/11/the-twilight-zone-kumail-nanjiani-star-episode-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202502659/|archive-date=November 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn April 29, 2019, the series was renewed for a second season.<ref name=\"Season 2 Renewal\">{{cite web|title=CBS All Access Renews 'The Twilight Zone' for Season Two|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2019/04/29/cbs-all-access-renews-the-twilight-zone-for-season-two-700215/20190429cbs01/|work=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=April 29, 2019|accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nIn October 2018, it was announced that [[Sanaa Lathan]] and [[Adam Scott (actor)|Adam Scott]] had been cast in guest-starring roles; Lathan would appear in an episode titled \"Rewind\"<ref name=\"Rewind\">{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: Sanaa Lathan To Star In \"Rewind\" Episode in CBS All Access Series|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/the-twilight-zone-sanaa-lathan-star-season-1-cbs-all-access-series-1202480928/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=October 11, 2018|date=October 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011205338/https://deadline.com/2018/10/the-twilight-zone-sanaa-lathan-star-season-1-cbs-all-access-series-1202480928/|archive-date=October 11, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and Scott in an episode titled \"Nightmare at 30,000 Feet\", a remake of the original series episode \"[[Nightmare at 20,000 Feet]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Haring|first=Bruce|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019 Adds Adam Scott For \u2018Nightmare at 30,000 Feet\u2019 Episode|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/the-twilight-zone-adds-adam-scott-for-nightmare-at-30000-feet-episode-1202489947/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=October 26, 2018|date=October 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026184018/https://deadline.com/2018/10/the-twilight-zone-adds-adam-scott-for-nightmare-at-30000-feet-episode-1202489947/|archive-date=October 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On November 15, 2018, it was reported that [[Kumail Nanjiani]] had been cast in a guest starring role.<ref name=\"RubensNanjiani\"/> In December 2018, it was announced that [[John Cho]], [[Allison Tolman]], [[Jacob Tremblay]], Erica Tremblay, [[Steven Yeun]], and [[Greg Kinnear]] would appear in guest starring roles. Cho, Tolman, and the Tremblays would appear in an episode titled \"The Wunderkind\"<ref name=\"The Wunderkind\">{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: John Cho, Allison Tolman & Jacob Tremblay To Star in Episode Of CBS All Access Reboot|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/the-twilight-zone-john-cho-allison-tolman-jacob-tremblay-to-star-in-episode-of-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202512838/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 3, 2018|date=December 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204004224/https://deadline.com/2018/12/the-twilight-zone-john-cho-allison-tolman-jacob-tremblay-to-star-in-episode-of-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202512838/|archive-date=December 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and Yeun<ref>{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=Steven Yeun Joins \u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019; Miley Cyrus In \u2018Black Mirror\u2019|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/stevenyeun-the-twilight-zone-miley-cyrus-black-mirror-1202519043/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 12, 2018|date=December 12, 2018}}</ref> and Kinnear in an episode titled \"The Traveler\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: Greg Kinnear To Star in Episode Of CBS All Access Reboot|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/the-twilight-zone-greg-kinnear-star-episode-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202519719/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 13, 2018|date=December 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214132417/https://deadline.com/2018/12/the-twilight-zone-greg-kinnear-star-episode-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202519719/|archive-date=December 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2019, it was reported that [[DeWanda Wise]], [[Jessica Williams (actress)|Jessica Williams]], [[Lucinda Dryzek]], Jefferson White, Jonathan Whitesell, [[Taissa Farmiga]], [[Rhea Seehorn]], [[Luke Kirby]], [[Ike Barinholtz]], and [[Percy Hynes White]] had been cast in guest starring roles. Wise, Williams, Dryzek, White, and Whitesell would appear in one episode<ref>{{cite web|last=Boucher|first=Geoff|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: DeWanda Wise, Jessica Williams Recruited For Jordan Peele Sci-Fi Show|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/the-twilight-zone-jordan-peele-cbs-all-access-1202534823/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=January 14, 2019|date=January 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114221131/https://deadline.com/2019/01/the-twilight-zone-jordan-peele-cbs-all-access-1202534823/|archive-date=January 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> while Farmiga, Seehorn, Kirby, Barinholtz, and Hynes-White would be featured in another.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: Taissa Farmiga, Rhea Seehorn, Luke Kirby & Ike Barinholtz To Star in Episode Of CBS All Access Reboot|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/the-twilight-zone-taissa-farmiga-rhea-seehorn-luke-kirby-ike-barinholtz-star-episode-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202543926/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=January 28, 2019|date=January 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129122903/https://deadline.com/2019/01/the-twilight-zone-taissa-farmiga-rhea-seehorn-luke-kirby-ike-barinholtz-star-episode-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202543926/|archive-date=January 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On February 7, 2019, it was announced that [[Ginnifer Goodwin]], [[James Frain]], and [[Zabryna Guevara]] had been cast to guest star in an episode titled \"Point of Origin\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: Ginnifer Goodwin To Star in Episode Of CBS All Access Reboot|url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/the-twilight-zone-ginnifer-goodwin-star-episode-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202551972/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=February 7, 2019|date=February 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209124523/https://deadline.com/2019/02/the-twilight-zone-ginnifer-goodwin-star-episode-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202551972/|archive-date=February 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The full trailer revealed that [[Tracy Morgan]], [[Glenn Fleshler]] and [[Chris Diamantopoulos]] would make guest appearances with Morgan appearing alongside Nanjiani, Fleshler in \"Rewind\" alongside Lathan, and Diamantopoulos joining Scott in \"Nightmare at 30,000 Feet\".<ref name=\"TrailerCast\"/> It was revealed through the official Twitter page that [[Seth Rogen]] would appear in an episode.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=TheTwilightZone|number=1101581425789173761|date=March 1, 2019|title=Enter the fifth dimension with @SethRogen as we he will star in an upcoming episode of #TheTwilightZone. The new @CBSAllAccess Original Series premieres April 1.}}</ref> On March 8, 2019, it was announced [[Zazie Beetz]] and [[Betty Gabriel]] would appear in an episode,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/the-twilight-zone-zazie-beetz-and-betty-gabriel-step-into-cbs-all-access-anthology-1202572128/|title=The Twilight Zone: Zazie Beetz And Betty Gabriel Step Into CBS All-Access Anthology|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Geoff|last=Boucher|date=March 8, 2019|accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref> while [[Chris O'Dowd]] and [[Amy Landecker]] would appear in an episode titled \"The Blue Scorpion\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/the-twilight-zone-chris-odowd-cbs-all-access-reboot-1202578408/|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019: Chris O\u2019Dowd To Star in Episode Of CBS All Access Reboot|work=Deadline Hollywood|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|date=March 19, 2019|accessdate=March 20, 2019}}</ref> On March 28, 2019, it was announced that [[Damson Idris]] would appear in an episode titled \"Replay\", which was previously titled \"Rewind\".<ref name=\"Replay\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/3/28/18285952/jordan-peele-twilight-zone-review-classic-episodes-connections/|title=Jordan Peele's Twilight Zone inverts classic episodes to tell urgent, new stories|website=Polygon|last=Frederick|first=Candice|date=March 28, 2019|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nPrincipal photography for season one began on October 1, 2018, in [[Vancouver]], British Columbia,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ramos|first1=Dino-Ray|title=Jordan Peele's \u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019 Begins Production, Celebrates 59 Years Of Iconic Sci-Fi Original|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/the-twilight-zone-production-jordan-peele-simon-kinberg-59-years-1202474946/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=October 2, 2018|date=October 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003004936/https://deadline.com/2018/10/the-twilight-zone-production-jordan-peele-simon-kinberg-59-years-1202474946/|archive-date=October 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and concluded on March 20, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mirchandani|first1=Amar|title=27 TV Shows Filming in Vancouver Right Now (December 2018)|url=https://604now.com/tv-shows-filming-vancouver-december-2018/|website=604 Now|accessdate=December 2, 2018|date=November 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202202629/https://604now.com/tv-shows-filming-vancouver-december-2018/|archive-date=December 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n===Season 1 (2019)===\n{{Episode table |background=#22202E |overall=5 |season=5 |title=18 |director=16 |writer=41 |airdate=15 |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = The Comedian\n| DirectedBy      = [[Owen Harris (director)|Owen Harris]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Alex Rubens]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|4|1}}\n| ShortSummary    = Struggling comedian Samir Wassan meets legendary comic J.C. Wheeler, who advises him to include personal material in his routines. After doing a successful routine centered around his dog, Samir returns home and discovers that not only did his dog vanish, but no one seems to remember that it ever existed. He then learns that jokes about the people in his life get laughs, but cause them to disappear from existence. After accidentally erasing his nephew, Devin, Samir starts erasing people he thinks the world would be better off without. His girlfriend, Rena, leaves him after the erasing of David Kendall causes her to go from a successful lawyer to a struggling [[Waiting staff|waitress]]. After another encounter with Wheeler, Samir continues abusing his power, going so far as erasing rival comic Didi Scott. Rena confronts him during a set with a journal containing names of those he's erased. Realizing what he has done, Samir erases himself from existence while everyone previously erased exists again. Didi, now a rising star, meets Wheeler following a set and asks for his advice.{{Episode cast}} [[Kumail Nanjiani]], [[Amara Karan]], Diarra Kilpatrick, [[Ryan Robbins]], [[Tracy Morgan]]<br>\nThe inspiration for this episode was \"[[List of The Twilight Zone (1985 TV series) episodes|Take My Life, Please]]\" from the [[The Twilight Zone (1985 TV series)|1985 series]]. Rosie Knight of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' stated \"Samir's story appears to take a large influence from [...] ''[[Death Note]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Knight, Rosie|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/twilight-zone-comedian-nightmare-at-30000-feet-explained-1198347|title='The Twilight Zone' Takes on Classic Episode, Lust for Fame in CBS All Access Debut|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=2019-04-01|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| Title           = Nightmare at 30,000 Feet\n| DirectedBy      = [[Greg Yaitanes]]\n| WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=[[Simon Kinberg]], [[Jordan Peele]] and Marco Ramirez|t=Marco Ramirez|ex1label=Based on ''\"[[Nightmare at 20,000 Feet]]\"'' by|ex1=[[Richard Matheson]]}}\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|4|1}}\n| ShortSummary    = PTSD-afflicted journalist Justin Sanderson boards Northern Goldstar Airlines Flight 1015 from Washington, D.C. to Tel Aviv after accepting a job offer. Shortly before takeoff, Justin finds an MP3 player in his seat pocket and discovers it contains a podcast hosted by Rodman Edwards revolving around \"the mystery of Northern Goldstar Flight 1015\", which disappeared an hour into the flight. As the podcast accurately describes events involving his fellow passengers, Justin juggles controlling his nerves and confiding in Joe Beaumont, a former pilot who seems to be the only person who believes him and had lost his job for crashing a previous airplane. He tries using clues from the podcast to avert the disaster, but every attempt results in irritated crew and passengers. Joe then convinces Justin to help him gain access to the flight deck so he can land the plane safely in Canada. The two accomplish their mission, but Justin realizes from the podcast at the last minute that Joe is responsible for the crash. Waking up on an atoll, Justin learns via the podcast that everyone that survived was rescued months later while he is considered missing. The other survivors appear, surround Justin from all sides, and beat him to death as he claims that he was trying to save them. {{Episode cast}} [[Adam Scott (actor)|Adam Scott]], [[Chris Diamantopoulos]], [[Dan Carlin]], [[Katie Findlay]], [[Nicholas Lea]]\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| Title           = Replay\n| DirectedBy      = Gerard McMurray\n| WrittenBy       = [[Selwyn Seyfu Hinds]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|4|11}}\n| ShortSummary    = While at a roadside diner with her college-bound son Dorian, Nina Harrison discovers her old family camcorder has the power to [[Time travel|turn back time]] when she presses the rewind button and that she is the only one aware of its capabilities. The two encounter Lasky, a racist [[State police (United States)|state trooper]] who pulls them over for speeding before becoming violent with them. Nina rewinds time and convinces Dorian to pull over by claiming she doesn't feel well. This time however, Lasky holds them for not pulling over properly. Nina attempts to change time by first stopping at a motel and then trying to sympathize with Lasky at the diner, but both attempts end in Lasky harming or killing Dorian. Nina then visits her estranged brother Neil who not only believes her story, but helps her get Dorian to the college campus. When Lasky arrives with a group of state troopers, Nina, Neil, and the students stand their ground; prompting Lasky to leave. Ten years later, Dorian has become a father to daughter Trinity while Nina holds onto the camcorder. After Trinity accidentally breaks the camcorder, Dorian tells Nina to let go and leaves to run an errand as she and Trinity look on. As the credits begin to roll, the sound of a police siren is heard. {{Episode cast}} [[Sanaa Lathan]], [[Damson Idris]], [[Glenn Fleshler]], [[Steve Harris (actor)|Steve Harris]]\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| Title           = A Traveler\n| DirectedBy      = [[Ana Lily Amirpour]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Glen Morgan]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|4|18}}\n| ShortSummary    = Alaska police sergeant Yuka Mongoyak arranges for her brother, Jack, to be pardoned at [[Police captain|Captain]] Lane Pendleton's annual Christmas party, which she detests. At the height of the festivities, Yuka discovers another inmate has mysteriously appeared in the station's holding cells. The stranger, whose name is \"legally\" A. Traveler, claims he is an extreme tourist who has heard of Pendleton's \"famous\" parties. As Traveler becomes friendly with the guests, Yuka grows suspicious of his identity. Pendleton soon grows suspicious when Traveler reveals information he should have no way of knowing like the actions done by Mayor Matheson. When Yuka, Jack, and Pendleton spot antennas on Traveler's head, Traveler deflects their suspicions by claiming Pendleton is in league with the Russians. Pendleton then leaves to check on the shed powering the town while Traveler promises Yuka that she will be in charge and that \"[his] people\" will come and take over. Yuka proceeds to corner Pendleton and hold him at gunpoint as they witness UFOs descend from the sky. At the station, Jack shares a piece of pumpkin pie with Traveler, now in his true alien form, and states things would be better with them in charge.{{Episode cast}} [[Steven Yeun]], Marika Sila, [[Patrick Gallagher (actor)|Patrick Gallagher]], [[Eric Keenleyside]], [[Andrew Kavadas]], Gail Maurice, [[Greg Kinnear]]\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n| Title           = The Wunderkind\n| DirectedBy      = [[Richard Shepard]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Andrew Guest]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|4|25}}\n| ShortSummary    = [[Campaign manager]] Raff Hanks finds himself in a hospital and recounts the events leading up to his hospitalization to an orderly. Years earlier, Raff considered himself a wunderkind and had been a successful campaign manager. After he and his partner Maura fail to get then-sitting and unpopular President of the United States James Stevens reelected, Raff's career is ruined. While at the bar years later, Raff spots a news item about eleven-year-old YouTube star Oliver Foley announcing his candidacy for President. Seizing the opportunity to redeem himself, Raff convinces Oliver's parents about having him run. While the public supports Oliver, he struggles to answer questions about current issues and humiliates himself during a debate. Raff then bases Oliver's campaign around family after learning his dog is dying of cancer; resulting in Oliver winning the Iowa caucus and subsequently becoming President while his mother becomes the Vice President. Oliver takes control of the White House, prompting Raff to regret his actions. When Oliver catches wind of Raff's \"treason\", he reveals he lied about his dog dying to get votes before convincing the Secret Service to shoot Raff. In the present, Raff learns from the orderly that the surgeon operating on him is an apathetic child due to Oliver's having passed a law forbidding old doctors.{{Episode cast}} [[John Cho]], [[Jacob Tremblay]], [[Allison Tolman]], Kimberley Sustad, Lane Edwards, Erica Tremblay, [[John Larroquette]]\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 6\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n| Title           = Six Degrees of Freedom\n| DirectedBy      = [[Jakob Verbruggen]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Heather Anne Campbell]] and Glen Morgan\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|5|2}}\n| ShortSummary    = The crew of the Bradbury spacecraft, led by Alexa Brandt, decide to head for the planet [[Mars]] after a nuclear war breaks out on earth. The crew members soon begin to turn on one another, in spite of Brandt's attempts to convince them to come together under times of stress. However, she too begins to break, devastating fellow crew member Katherine Langford. One crewman, Jerry Pierson, goes crazy and starts rambling that they are being watched, to which the other crewmen don't believe him. Later on, he is seemingly killed after going out the airlock. The crew successfully lands on Mars. It is later revealed that Jerry had been taken away by aliens and that he was correct: aliens have been monitoring the crew trying to determine if they are worth saving and pass through the [[great filter]].{{Episode cast}} [[DeWanda Wise]], [[Jessica Williams (actress)|Jessica Williams]], Jefferson White, [[Lucinda Dryzek]], Jonathan Whitesell\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 7\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n| Title           = Not All Men\n| DirectedBy      = Christina Choe\n| WrittenBy       = Heather Anne Campbell\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|5|9}}\n| ShortSummary    = Reporter Annie Miller is invited by her co-worker Dylan to watch a meteor shower. During the event, Dylan picks up one of the rocks, causing his attitude to change. Annie leaves early after witnessing Dylan destroy his record player. The next day, Annie visits her sister Martha who is celebrating her birthday with her husband Mike, nephew Cole, and Phil. While having cake, they hear a neighbor scream about contaminated water before witnessing most of the town's men, including Mike, partake in violent acts; with Phil being killed in the process. Dylan appears and tries to strangle Annie before she gets free and knocks him back. Annie, Martha, and Cole are later rescued and taken to a quarantine center, where they learn that a virus infected the town's water supply and affected almost all of the men. Even though he had one of the meteors in his pocket, Cole is deemed healthy, as he was able to control his rage, and revealing that the meteorites were just a placebo for the men's violent behaviors. The three are eventually allowed to leave as the news blames the incident on road rage and late night crime sprees.{{Episode cast}} [[Taissa Farmiga]], [[Rhea Seehorn]], [[Percy Hynes White]], [[Luke Kirby]], [[Peter Kelamis]], [[Ike Barinholtz]]\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 8\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n| Title           = Point of Origin\n| DirectedBy      = Mathias Herndl\n| WrittenBy       = John Griffin\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|5|16}}\n| ShortSummary    = Wealthy socialite Eve Martin is approached by her [[Housekeeper (domestic worker)|housekeeper]] and [[nanny]] Anna Fuentas who asks if her grandson can use her address as she's an illegal immigrant from Guatemala. Eve agrees while she prepares for a party for new parents. However, Anna is taken by [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|ICE]]. While out grocery shopping with her daughters, Eve finds that her credit cards have been declined. In the parking lot, they are picked up by [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement#Homeland Security Investigations (HSI)|HSI]]. She and her husband William are interrogated by Agent Allandale. While her family is released, Eve remains in HSI custody so Allandale can figure out where she came from. The machine she is subjected to gives her the fake illusion that HSI later released her as well as visions of a ruined world. Eve is shocked to find out that Anna is an illegal alien from another dimension and that she is too. Eve and Anna manage to formulate an escape plan as they dodge HSI agents. While Anna goes in a different direction, Eve heads home where William says she can't be here. Agent Allandale arrives with the HSI agents. When Eve tells him to get out of her house, Allandale tells her to get out of \"his house.\" Eve is taken away by the HSI to be reimprisoned as William sheds a tear.{{Episode cast}} [[Ginnifer Goodwin]], [[James Frain]], Toby Levins, [[Zabryna Guevara]], [[Karin Konoval]], [[Michael Eklund]], Robert Mann\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 9\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 9\n| Title           = The Blue Scorpion\n| DirectedBy      = [[Craig William Macneill]]\n| WrittenBy       = Glen Morgan\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|5|23}}\n| ShortSummary    = Depressed anthropology professor Jeff Storck is about to divorce from his wife despite his pleas for counseling. On top of that, he finds that his father has apparently committed suicide. While in his dad\u2019s house, he finds a gun called the Blue Scorpion with a bullet with his name on it. At the funeral, Jeff questions why his father would kill himself. With all that's going on in his life, Jeff contemplates killing himself with the gun after testing it at a gun range. Meanwhile, Jeff\u2019s estranged wife has begun seeing another man, also named Jeff, which gets Jeff to thinking about killing the man due to his feelings for his wife. Jeff goes to her house and shoots at his wife\u2019s boyfriend. The bullet misses him, but hits and kills a burglar in the house, also named Jeff. In the aftermath of this after being praised for stopping the burglar, Jeff decides to rid himself of the gun that has caused him his misfortune. He throws it into the harbor and leaves. Later, the gun is found by two kids with the bullet now reading the name \u201cKyle\u201d after the kid who picked it up.{{Episode cast}} [[Chris O'Dowd]], [[Amy Landecker]], [[Alex Diakun]], [[James Morrison (actor)|James Morrison]], [[Adam Korson]], [[Luisa D'Oliveira]]\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 10\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 10\n| Title           = Blurryman\n| DirectedBy      = Simon Kinberg\n| WrittenBy       = Alex Rubens\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|5|30}}\n| ShortSummary    = After rewriting the opening narration for an episode of ''The Twilight Zone'' starring Seth Rogen and Betty Gabriel for Jordan Peele in this meta-fictional episode, screenwriter and ''Twilight Zone'' fan Sophie Gelson discovers someone changed it to be about her. She later notices a mysterious blurry figure appearing in the background of several scenes as well as scenes from previous episodes. While searching for Jordan, Sophie encounters the Blurryman, who chases her through the studio and triggers a flashback to her childhood. After a brief encounter with [[Jason Priestley]], she hands a new version of the narration to Jordan before finding herself in the world of the iconic episode \"[[Time Enough at Last]].\" When she finally encounters the Blurryman and agrees to hear it out, the Blurryman reveals himself as original series host [[Rod Serling]]. Claiming that they have \"a lot of work to do,\" Serling escorts Sophie through a door into the Twilight Zone.{{Episode cast}} [[Zazie Beetz]], [[Betty Gabriel]], Zibby Allen, Caitlin Stryker, [[Seth Rogen]]\n| LineColor       = 22202E\n}}\n}}\n\n===Season 2===\n<!--Per WP:TVUPCOMING, do not include 2020 until episodes have actually aired in 2020!-->\nThe season will consist of ten episodes.<ref name=\"TwilightZoneSeason2\" />\n{{Episode table |background=#3CB3C8 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=18 |director=16 |writer=41 |airdate=15 |released=y |airdateR=<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/01/the-twilight-zone-season-2-cast-list-jordan-peele-episode-1202202551/|title=\u2018The Twilight Zone\u2019 Season 2 Sets New Cast, Jordan Peele to Write New Episode|first=Ben|last=Travers|publisher=IndieWire|date=January 12, 2020|accessdate=January 13, 2020}}</ref> |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = \n| EpisodeNumber2  = \n| Title           = Downtime\n| RTitle          =<ref name=\"TwilightZoneSeason2\" />\n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = [[Jordan Peele]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020}}\n| ShortSummary    = {{Episode cast|hr=n}} [[Morena Baccarin]], [[Colman Domingo]], [[Tony Hale]]\n| LineColor       = 3CB3C8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = \n| EpisodeNumber2  = \n| Title           = The Who of You\n| RTitle          =<ref name=\"TwilightZoneSeason2\" />\n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = Win Rosenfeld\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020}}\n| ShortSummary    = {{Episode cast|hr=n}} [[Daniel Sunjata]], [[Ethan Embry]], [[Billy Porter (entertainer)|Billy Porter]]\n| LineColor       = 3CB3C8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = \n| EpisodeNumber2  = \n| Title           = A Human Face\n| RTitle          =<ref name=\"TwilightZoneSeason2\" />\n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = [[Alex Rubens]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020}}\n| ShortSummary    = {{Episode cast|hr=n}} [[Jenna Elfman]], [[Christopher Meloni]], [[Tavi Gevinson]]\n| LineColor       = 3CB3C8\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = \n| EpisodeNumber2  = \n| Title           = 8\n| RTitle          =<ref name=\"TwilightZoneSeason2\" />\n| Direct